	
Cookie
	
Many Microsoft sites use small text files called "cookies." This file is placed on the user's device and later read by the web server of the domain that issued the cookie. We use cookies to store user preferences and preferences, help you sign in, provide personalized advertising, and analyze your site interactions. For more information, please see the Cookies and Similar Technologies section of this Privacy Statement.
	
•EU-US, UK Extension, Swiss-US Data Privacy Framework
	
Microsoft complies with the EU-US, the UK extension to the EU-US, and the Swiss-US Data Privacy Framework. For more information, please refer to the Where personal data is stored and processed section (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainwherewestoreandprocessdatamodule) and visit the U.S. Department of Commerce's Data Privacy Framework website (https://www.dataprivacyframework.gov/).
	
Contact us
	
If you have any privacy concerns, complaints, or questions to Microsoft's Chief Privacy Officer or Data Protection Officer, please contact us using our web form (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2126612). For more information about contacting Microsoft (including Microsoft Ireland Operations Limited), see the "How to Contact Us (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainhowtocontactusmodule)" section of this statement.
	
Microsoft respects your privacy. This Privacy Statement describes the types of personal data processed by Microsoft, how they are processed, and what we use them.
	
Microsoft offers a wide range of products, including server products to help businesses around the world do their jobs, devices for use at home, software for students to use at school, and services for developers to create and host new products. This statement refers to Microsoft products, including Microsoft services, websites, apps, software, servers, and devices.
	
The product-specific details contained in this statement include additional relevant information. This statement applies to your interactions with Microsoft and to the Microsoft products listed below, as well as to other Microsoft products in which this statement appears.
	
Younger people may prefer to start with the "Privacy Page for Young People (https://aka.ms/youngpeopleprivacy/)." The page highlights information that may be useful to young people.
	
If you are an individual in the United States, please see the U.S. State Data Privacy Law Notice (https://aka.ms/USStatePrivacyNotice) and the Consumer Health Data Privacy Policy (https://privacy.microsoft.com/microsoft-consumer-health-data-privacy-policy) for additional information regarding the processing of personal data and your rights under applicable U.S. state data privacy laws. 
	
Personal Information We Collect
	
Microsoft collects data from your interactions with or through our products for a variety of purposes, including to improve the efficiency of our services and to optimize your experience on our products, as described below. Some of the data we collect is data provided to us directly by users. For example, when you create a Microsoft account, manage your organization's license account, send a search query to Bing, register for a Microsoft event, upload a document to OneDrive, sign up for Microsoft 365, contact support, and so on. Some of this data is collected by us about your interaction, use, and experience of our products and your communication with us. In addition, Microsoft receives data from Microsoft's affiliates, subsidiaries, and third parties.
	
We process data on various legal grounds and permissions (also known as "legal bases"), such as your consent, the need to maintain legitimate interests, the need to enter into and perform a contract, compliance with a legal obligation, and the various purposes listed below.
	
In addition, data is provided by third parties. Data obtained from third parties is protected in accordance with the policies described in this Statement and the additional restrictions set forth in the data acquisition destination. Third-party data sources can change, but here are some examples:
		
•	Data brokers for demographic data that Microsoft purchases to supplement the data it collects.
		
•	A service that allows users to create content, such as local business reviews or public social media posts, and make that content available to others.
		
•	Communication services such as email providers and social networks (if you have given us permission to access your data for such third-party services or networks).
		
•	Service providers that help you locate your device.
		
•	Partners who offer services and co-marketing activities under co-branding with Microsoft.
		
•	Developers who create experiences through or Microsoft products.
		
•	Third parties that provide experiences through Microsoft products, such as Cortana-related skills.
		
•	Publicly available sources such as publicly available public sector, academic, commercial data sets, and other data sources.
	
If you are a representative of an organization that uses Microsoft enterprise and developer products, such as businesses and schools, please see the Enterprise and developer products section of this Privacy Statement for information about how we process your data. For end users of Microsoft products or Microsoft accounts provided by your organization, see the Products provided by your organization and the Microsoft account sections for more information.
	
Users can choose which technology to use and what data to share. If you are asked to provide personal data, you can refuse. Many of our products require personal data to perform the service and provide it to users. If the data required for the operation of a product or feature and its provision to the user is not provided, the user cannot use the product or feature. Similarly, if we are required by law to collect personal data or enter into or perform a contract with the user, we cannot enter into a contract if we cannot obtain data from the user. If it is related to your existing product, you may need to stop or cancel your use. If this is the case, the user will be notified at that time. If you choose not to share your personal data if you are voluntary, you will not be able to use features such as personalization settings that use that data.
	
The data collected depends on the context of your interactions with Microsoft, your choices such as privacy settings, the products and features you use, your location, and applicable laws.
	
The data collected may include:
	
Name and contact data. Your name, email address, address, phone number, and other similar contact data.
	
Credentials. Passwords, password tips, and similar security info that you use to authenticate or access your account.
	
Demographic data. Data such as the user's age, gender, country, and preferred language.
	
Payment information. Data required to process the payment, such as the user's payment method number (such as credit card number) and the security code associated with the payment method.
	
Subscription and license data. Information about subscriptions, licenses, and other rights.
	
Interaction. Data about your use of Microsoft products. This may be data provided by users to use the product, such as through search queries, or data generated by us, such as error reports. Other interaction data includes:
		
•	Device and usage data. Data about your device and the products and features you use, such as hardware and software information, product performance, and settings. Here are some examples:
		
◦	Payment and account history. Data about the items you purchased and the activity associated with your account.
		
◦	Browsing history. Data about the web pages you visit.
		
◦	Data about devices, connections, and configurations. Data about the device, device configuration, and nearby networks. For example, data about the operating system and other software, including product keys installed on your device. In addition, information about IP addresses, device identifiers (such as the phone's IMEI number), region and language settings, and Wi-Fi access points near the device.
		
◦	Error reports and performance data. Data about product performance and issues encountered, including error reports. An error report (also known as a "crash dump") may include details about the software or hardware associated with the error, the contents of the file that was opened when the error occurred, and data about other software on the device.
		
◦	Troubleshooting and help data. The data you provide when you contact Microsoft, such as other details that can help us provide support, such as the products you use. For example, contact or authentication data, chats and other communications with Microsoft, data about the state of your device, and products you use in connection with a help query. When you contact our customer support, for example, our phone conversations and chats with our representatives may be monitored and recorded.
		
◦	Bot usage data. Interact with bots and skills available through Microsoft products, such as bots and skills provided by third parties.
		
•	Interests and favorites. Data about your interests and favorites, such as the sports teams you support, the programming languages you use mostly, the stocks you constantly research, the cities you've added to track weather, traffic, and more. In addition to what you explicitly provide, we may also infer or derive your interests and favorites from other data we collect, such as your interactions on websites that use Microsoft technologies to display or measure ads.
		
•	Content consumption data. Information about the media content (e.g., TV, video, music, audio, textbooks, apps, and games) that you access from our products.
		
•	Search and command. Search queries and commands when using search capabilities or related productivity features, such as interacting with chat bots.
		
•	Audio data. A user's voice data (sometimes called a "voice clip"), such as a search query or command, or a user's dictation may include background sounds.
		
•	Text, hand-drawn input, and typing data. Text, hand-drawn input, and typing data and related information. For example, when collecting hand-drawn input data, information about the installation of hand-drawn input equipment on the device is also collected.
		
•	Image. Images and related information, such as image metadata. For example, images that you specify when you use the Bing image-enabled service are collected.
		
•	Contacts and relationships. Data about your contacts and their relationships if you use our products to share information with others, manage contacts, communicate with others, or improve productivity.
		
•	Social data. Information about the relationship and interaction between a user and another person or organization, such as the type of engagement with a person or organization (e.g., preferences, dislikes, events).
		
•	Location data. Data about the location of the user's device. Accuracy can vary and may or may not be accurate. For example, location data from the Global Positioning Satellite System (GNSS) (such as GPS) and data about nearby cell towers and Wi-Fi spots are collected. Location information can also be inferred from data that indicates the IP address of a device or the location contained in an account's profile (for example, with low accuracy at the city or zip code level).
		
•	Other inputs. Other inputs provided when using our products. Examples of data collected include buttons pressed on the Xbox Wireless Controller when using the Xbox network, skeleton tracking data when using Kinect, and applicable center data (such as steps) when using devices with other sensors. We collect data that you provide to us when you register for or during an event when you attend an in-store event. In addition, if you apply for a promotion of a product, we will collect the data you enter in the application form.
	
Content. The content of files and communications that users enter, upload, receive, create, and control. For example, if you use Teams to send a file to another Teams user, we need to collect the contents of that file in order to display it to the sender and the other user. When you use Outlook.com to receive emails, we need to collect the content of the email to put it in your inbox, display it, make it available for reply, and store it until you delete it. Other content collected when offering products includes:
		
•	Communication, including audio, video, text (keyboard, handwriting, dictation, and other types), messages, emails, calls, meeting requests, and chats.
		
•	Media and documents such as photos, images, music, videos, and software that you have stored, retrieved, or otherwise processed in the cloud.
	
Video or recording. Recording/recording of events and activities in Microsoft buildings, sales spaces, and other locations. When a user enters a Microsoft Store store or other property, or when they participate in a recorded/recorded Microsoft event, the user's image and audio data may be processed.
	
Feedback and evaluation. The content of the information you provide to us or the messages you send, such as feedback you complete, survey data, and product ratings.
	
Traffic data. Data generated by your use of Microsoft's communication services. Traffic data shows you who you communicated with and when. Microsoft only uses traffic data to provide, maintain, and improve our communication services, and we do so with your consent.
	
The following product-specific sections describe the actual data collection that applies to your use of those products.
	
Use of your personal data
	
Microsoft uses the data we collect to provide users with a rich, interactive experience. Specific uses of the data include:
		
•	Offering our products. This includes providing updates, security, troubleshooting, and support. This includes sharing data when a user needs to provide a service or perform a transaction requested by a user.
		
•	Improvement and development of our products.
		
•	Customization and recommendation of our products.
		
•	Advertising and sales to users. This includes promotional communications, targeted advertising, and presenting products or services that are relevant to users.
	
We also use the data to conduct our business. This includes applications such as analyzing performance, adhering to legal obligations, developing employees, and conducting surveys.
	
To do this, we may also combine data collected from different contexts (such as two Microsoft products that you use). For example, the Microsoft Store uses information about the apps and services you use to recommend apps that are right for each user. However, we have incorporated technical and procedural precautions to prevent the combination of certain personal data where required by law. For example, if required by law, data collected when a user is not authenticated (not signed in) is stored separately from account information that can directly identify the user, such as name, email address, and phone number.
	
The processing of personal data for such purposes includes both automated and manual (human) methods. Automated methods are often associated with and supported by manual methods. For example, to build, train, and improve the accuracy of automated processing methods (including artificial intelligence or AI), we manually review some of the output generated by automated methods against the underlying data.
	
As part of product improvement and development, we may use your data to develop and train AI models. Learn more here (https://www.microsoft.com/microsoft-copilot/learn/?ep=0&form=MA13LV&es=31#faq).
	
Purpose and legal basis of processing
	
Microsoft has changed the details of this section and the "Why do we share personal data" in the Privacy Statement? As described in the section, as necessary to provide you with the products you use, to operate Microsoft's business, to fulfill our contractual and legal obligations, to protect the security and safety of Microsoft's systems and customers, and to fulfill any other legitimate interests of Microsoft or any third party. We process your personal data with your consent. The basis for processing your personal data may vary depending on how we process your data and our products and services. 
	
If we process personal data based on our or a third party's legitimate interests, we will only process your personal data if our legitimate interests in processing do not outweigh your interests, taking into account the balance between those interests and your rights and freedoms.
	
When we transfer personal data from the European Economic Area, we do so in accordance with the "Where and process personal information (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainwherewestoreandprocessdatamodule)" section of this Privacy Statement and are based on various legal mechanisms.
	
The processing of personal data also serves the following purposes:
		
•	Offering our products. We use data to run our products and provide you with rich, interactive experiences. For example, if a user is using OneDrive, documents uploaded by users to OneDrive as part of the service are processed so that users can perform tasks such as retrieving, deleting, editing, and transferring. Also, if you enter a search query into the Bing search engine, for example, it will use that query to display search results. In addition, because communication is built into the functionality of various products, programs and activities, data may be used when contacting users. For example, Microsoft may contact you by phone, email, or other means to notify you when your subscription is about to end or to explain your license account. In addition, we may contact you to protect our products, such as to notify you when product updates are available.
		
•	Product improvements. We use data to continuously improve our products, including adding new features and capabilities. For example, the use of error reporting to improve security features, the use of Bing search queries and clicks to improve the relevance of search results, the use of usage data to prioritize new features, and the use of voice data to improve speech recognition accuracy.
		
•	Personal settings. Many products include personalization features, such as recommendations that expand user productivity and enjoyment. This feature uses an automated process to customize your product experience based on the data we hold about you, such as you, your product usage and activity, your interests, and Microsoft's guesses about your location. For example, depending on your settings, you might want to see recommended apps from the Microsoft Store that are more stream-efficient when streaming movies in a browser on your Windows device. If you're using a Microsoft account, you can also sync settings across multiple devices with your permission. Many of our products provide controls to disable the ability to personalize your preferences.
		
•	Product activation. We use data such as device and application type, location information, and unique device, application, network, and subscription identifiers to activate products that require activation.
		
•	Product development. We use data to develop new products. For example, they often use anonymized data to train and fine-tune AI models that can better understand customers' computing and productivity needs and shape the development of new products. 
		
•	Customer support. Microsoft uses data to troubleshoot and diagnose product issues, repair users' devices, and provide other user care and support services. This includes providing products, services, and training, improving quality, protecting security, and investigating security incidents. You can also use the data from your call recordings to authenticate or identify you based on your voice so that Microsoft can provide support services and investigate security incidents.
		
•	Security protection and troubleshooting. We use data to secure and troubleshoot our products. This includes using data to protect the safety and security of our products and our customers, detect malware and malicious activity, troubleshoot performance and compatibility issues to improve the user experience, and notify users of updates about our products. They may also use automated systems to detect security and safety issues.
		
•	Security. Data is used to protect the safety of our products and users. Our security features and products can stop malicious software from working and notify users when malicious software is found on their devices. For example, our products, such as Outlook.com and OneDrive, systematically and automatically scan content to detect suspected spam, viruses, and fraudulent activity, as well as identify URLs that are flagged as links to scams, phishing, or malware. In addition, if any communication or content violates the terms of the Agreement, we reserve the right to block the transmission of communications or remove the content. Pursuant to European Union Regulation (EU) 2021/1232, Microsoft has invoked the exemptions permitted by the EU Directive 2002/58/EC in Articles 5(1) and 6(1). We use scanning technology to create digital signatures (called "hashes") for specific images and video content on the system. These technologies then compare the generated hashes with the hashes of reported images of child sexual exploitation and abuse (called "hash sets") in a process called "hash matching." Microsoft obtains hash sets from organizations that work in the public interest against child sexual abuse. This allows us to share information with the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children (NCMEC) and law enforcement. We also use tools to detect misuse of video calling features to deter high-risk users from generating or sharing images of child sexual exploitation and abuse. Learn more about our efforts to prevent and detect child exploitation here (https://www.microsoft.com/corporate-responsibility/digital-safety-content-report). 
		
•	Updates。 The data we collect is used to develop product updates and security fixes. For example, we may use information about your device's features, such as available memory, to provide software updates or security fixes. The purpose of updates and fixes is to maximize the user experience with our products, to help protect your privacy and data security, to provide new features, and to evaluate your device's readiness to handle such updates.
		
•	Promotional communications. We use the data we collect to provide you with promotional communications. Users can sign up for email subscriptions and choose how to communicate with Microsoft via email, SMS, mail, and phone. For more information about managing your contact data, email subscriptions, and promotional communications, please see the "How to access and manage your personal data" section of this Privacy Statement.
		
•	related products and services. Microsoft uses data to provide you with relevant and valuable information about our products. By analyzing data from diverse sources, it predicts the most relevant and interesting information for users and provides such information in a variety of ways. For example, if you predict that users will be interested in your game, let them know about new games they are likely to like.
		
•	Advertisement. Microsoft does not use your speech, documents, photos, or personal files in email, person-to-person chat, or video calls for targeted advertising. We use data collected through interactions with you through some first-party products, services, apps, web properties (Microsoft properties), and third-party web properties to serve ads on Microsoft properties and third-party sites. Party properties. Automated processes may also be used to show users ads that are more relevant. For information about how data about you is used for advertising, please refer to the Advertising (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainadvertisingmodule) section of this Privacy Statement.
		
•	Prize promotions and events. Your data is used to promote prizes offered in physical Microsoft Stores and to conduct events. For example, if you enter a prize promotion, we may use your data for the purpose of selecting winners and presenting prizes to winning customers. And when you register for a coding workshop or gaming event, we add your name to the list of potential attendees.
		
•	Processing of commercial transactions. Data is used to process your transactions with us. For example, we process payment information to provide users with subscriptions to our products and use contact information to deliver products purchased from the Microsoft Store.
		
•	Reporting and business operations. Data is used to analyze operations and perform business intelligence. This allows you to make informed decisions and generate reports on the performance of your operations.
		
•	protection of rights and property; Data is used to detect fraud, resolve disputes, enforce contracts, and protect property. For example, data is used to verify the validity of software licenses and reduce unauthorized copying. We may also use automated processes to detect and avoid behavior that violates our rights and the rights of others, such as fraud.
		
•	Compliance with laws and regulations. Microsoft processes data to comply with applicable laws and regulations. For example, we use your age information so that we can fulfill our obligations to protect your child's privacy. We also process contact information and credentials to help users exercise their data protection rights.
		
•	Research. We use data to conduct research such as advanced machine learning and artificial intelligence capabilities, for example, in the public interest and for scientific purposes, using appropriate technical and organizational measures to protect the rights and freedoms of individuals.
	
Why do we share personal data?
	
We will share your personal information with your consent or to the extent necessary to complete a transaction or provide you with a product you have requested or certified. For example, if a user requests it, share content information with a third party. For example, you might want to send an email to a friend, share photos or documents in OneDrive, or link your account with another service. When you use Microsoft products from your organization (such as work or school) or use an email address provided by such an organization to access Microsoft products, we share certain data (interaction and diagnostic data) to help your organization administer the product. When you provide payment information for purchases, Microsoft may share payment information with financial institutions that provide payment processing and financial services to prevent fraud and limit credit risk. In addition, if you or another Microsoft account holder stores a payment method (such as a card) in your account that you or another Microsoft account holder uses to make purchases from Microsoft or its affiliates, your purchase receipt may be shared with other users who use the same payment method (including the designated account holder for the payment method) for purchases from Microsoft and have access. If you allow push notifications for Microsoft products or applications on a non-Windows device, that device's operating system processes some personal data to provide push notifications. Therefore, Microsoft may send data to external third-party notification providers to deliver push notifications. Device push notification services are subject to their own service-specific terms of use and privacy statement.
	
We also share personal data for digital advertising purposes. When you visit a website or use an app that displays ads, your digital properties may allow you to access or receive device data or certain other data identified by the personal data collected in the sections above. We may then share this information with third-party advertising platforms and advertisers to facilitate the delivery and measurement of ads on such digital properties. For more information about how data is used for advertising, see the "Advertising and US State Data Privacy" section below.
	
In addition, we share personal information among Microsoft affiliates and subsidiaries. We also share personal information with vendors and agents who perform business on our behalf for the purposes set forth in this Statement. For example, our contractors who provide customer service support or help protect our systems and services may need access to your personal information to perform their jobs. In this case, they must comply with our personal data protection and security requirements. In addition, the personal information we receive from us may not be used for any other purpose. We may also disclose personal data as part of a business-to-business transaction, such as a merger or asset sale.
	
Finally, if we have a good conscience belief that it is necessary to do any of the following, we will access and maintain, disclose, transfer, or store your personal data, including your content (for example Outlook.com, the content of your email or files in a private folder on OneDrive).
		
•	To comply with applicable laws or to respond to due legal process, such as from a judicial or other government agency.
		
•	Protect the safety of users, organizations, and the public. For example, to prevent spam, fraud, or other damaging behavior, and to detect, prevent, and address harmful or illegal activity, including creating or sharing harmful or illegal content.
		
•	To manage and maintain the security of our products, including to prevent or stop attacks on computer systems and networks.
		
•	To protect Microsoft's rights or property, including to enforce terms governing the use of the Services. – However, if we receive information that someone else is using our services to transfer stolen Microsoft intellectual or physical property, we will not examine your personal information, but we will refer it to law enforcement.
	
For more information about the data we disclose at the request of judicial and other government authorities, see the Report on Requests from Law Enforcement (https://www.microsoft.com/about/corporate-responsibility/lerr/)Authorities.
	
Please note that some of our products may contain links to or otherwise make third-party products accessible to third-party products that have different privacy policies than Microsoft's products. If you provide personal data for these products, your data will be subject to that third-party privacy policy.
	
How to access and manage your personal data
	
You can also make choices regarding Microsoft's collection and use of your data. You can exercise your data protection rights by controlling your personal data obtained by Microsoft and by contacting Microsoft or using various tools provided by Microsoft. In some cases, your access to or control of your personal data will be restricted as required or permitted by applicable law. How you access and manage your personal data also depends on the product you use. For example:
		
•	 Visit our opt-out page (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=286759) to control the use of your data for personalized advertising from Microsoft.
		
•	You can choose whether to receive promotional emails, SMS messages, phone calls, and mail from Microsoft.
		
•	 You can access and erase some data from the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy).
	
Not all personal data processed by Microsoft can be accessed or controlled using the tools described above. If you would like to access or control personal data processed by Microsoft that is not available directly through the tools described above or directly from your Microsoft products, you may contact Microsoft at any time using the address or web form (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2126612) provided in the How to Contact (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainhowtocontactusmodule) Us section. You can contact us.
	 
The Microsoft Privacy Report (https://aka.ms/PrivacyReport) provides aggregated metrics about user requests to exercise your data protection rights.
	
You may access and control your personal data obtained by Microsoft by using Microsoft-provided tools described below or by contacting Microsoft. Example:
		
•	If you have consented to Microsoft using your personal data, you can revoke that consent at any time.
		
•	Users can request access, erasure, or update of their personal data.
		
•	If you want to port your data to another location, you can use the tools provided by Microsoft. If you can't use the tool, contact Microsoft.
	
You can also deny or restrict Microsoft's use of your personal data. For example, you can object to the use of your personal data at any time.
		
•	If it is used for direct marketing purposes.
		
•	If we are performing work in the public interest or pursuing our legitimate interests or those of a third party.
	
This right may be recognized by applicable law, such as the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), but we allow you to exercise this right, regardless of your location. In some cases, your access to or control of your personal data will be restricted as required or permitted by applicable law.
	
If your organization, such as your workplace, school, or service provider, has granted you access to Microsoft products and your use is controlled, contact your organization's representative to learn how to access and control your personal data.
	
You can exercise your data protection rights by accessing and controlling your personal data obtained by Microsoft and by using various tools provided by Microsoft. The most useful tools depend on your relationship with us and how you use our products. The following is a list of tools provided by us to help you control your personal data. Some products may offer additional controls.
		
•	Bing。 If you're signed in to Bing, you can view and clear your search and chat history stored in your privacy dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy). If you're not signed in to Bing, you can view and clear your search history associated with your saved device in Bing settings (https://www.bing.com/profile/history).
		
•	Microsoft account. You can access, edit, or delete your profile and payment information in your Microsoft account, change your password, add your security info, and suspend your account by visiting the Microsoft account website (https://account.microsoft.com/).
		
•	 If you have a public profile in the Microsoft Developer Network (MSDN), you can sign in to the MSDN forums (https://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/MSDNForum) to access and edit your data.
		
•	Microsoft Privacy Dashboard. The Microsoft Privacy Dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy) allows you to control some of the data processed by Microsoft through your use of your Microsoft account. Here, you can review and clear your browsing, search, and location data associated with your Microsoft account.
		
•	Microsoft Store。 To access your profile and account information, go to the Microsoft Store (https://www.microsoftstore.com/)and select View account or Order history. 
		
•	Microsoft Teams for personal use. You can visit this page (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2128346) to learn how to export or delete Teams data associated with your personal Microsoft account.
		
•	OneDrive。 When you sign in to OneDrive (https://onedrive.live.com/), you can view, download, and delete OneDrive files and photos.
		
•	Outlook.com。 You can download your email on Outlook.com (https://outlook.live.com/mail/inbox) by signing in to your account and going to your Privacy & Data settings.
		
•	Skype。 If you want to access, edit, or delete your Skype profile and payment information, or change your password, sign in to your account (https://login.skype.com/login). If you want to export your Skype chat history and files shared in Skype, you can request a copy (https://go.skype.com/export).
		
•	Volume Licensing Service Center (VLSC). Volume Licensing customers can visit the Volume Licensing Service Center website (https://www.microsoft.com/Licensing/servicecenter/default.aspx) to centrally manage their contract information and subscription and license data.
		
•	Xbox。 If you're on the Xbox network or Xbox.com, you can view or edit your personal data, such as billing (https://xbox.com/play/user) and account information, privacy settings, online safety, and data sharing settings, by accessing it from My Xbox on your Xbox console or from the Xbox.com website.
	
Not all personal data processed by Microsoft can be accessed or controlled using the tools described above. If you would like to access or control personal data processed by Microsoft that is not available directly through the tools described above or directly from your Microsoft product, please contact us at the address provided in the How to Contact (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainhowtocontactusmodule) Us section or through the web form (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2126612)You can contact Microsoft at any time. We will respond to your request for control of your personal data as required by applicable law.
	
Basic Communication Settings
	
You can choose how Microsoft notifies you about your promotions by email, SMS, mail, or phone. If you've received promotional emails or SMS messages and no longer want to receive them, follow the instructions in the messages below. To choose whether to receive promotional emails, phone calls, and mail, sign in to your personal Microsoft account and select Communication permissions (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=243191) Check it out. Here, you can choose whether to update your contact information, manage your contact preferences across Microsoft, unsubscribe from email subscriptions, and provide contact information to Microsoft partners. If you don't have a personal Microsoft account, you can use this web form (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=243189) to manage your settings, such as email notifications from Microsoft. The above selections do not apply to Required Service Communications that are part of certain Microsoft products, programs, or activities. It also does not apply to surveys or other informational communications with a different unsubscribe method.
	
Ad selection
	
To opt out of receiving personalized advertising (including Xandr) from Microsoft, visit our opt-out (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=286759)page. If you opt out, your settings will be stored in a cookie unique to your web browser. Opt-out cookies are valid for 5 years. If you delete cookies from your device, you will need to opt out again.
	
You can also link your opt-out choice with your personal Microsoft account. It will then apply to all devices you use with that account, and will continue until you sign in with a different personal Microsoft account on that device. If you delete cookies from your device, you'll need to sign in again to apply your settings. You can find out more about Microsoft's third-party advertising partners (https://learn.microsoft.com/xandr/policies-regulations/third-party-providers) in the U.S. State Data Privacy Law Notice (https://aka.ms/USStatePrivacyNotice), and you can opt out of sharing your data with third parties on the opt-out page (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2214802).
	
For Microsoft-controlled ads that appear in Windows apps, you can opt-out by using the opt-out linked to your personal Microsoft account, or you can opt out of interest-based advertising by turning off the advertising identifier in Windows settings.
	
Because the data used for interest-based advertising is used for other necessary purposes (including product delivery, analytics, and fraud prevention), opting out of interest-based advertising does not stop this data collection. Your ads will still appear, but they may be less relevant to your users.
	
You can opt out of receiving interest-based advertising from third parties by visiting our partners' sites (see above).
	
Browser-based management
	
If you use a browser, you can use certain features to control your personal data. Example:
		
•	Cookie controls. You can use the browser-based cookie management described in the Cookiessection of this Privacy Statement to control the data stored by cookies and to withdraw your consent to cookies.
		
•	Tracking prevention. You can control the data collected about you on third-party sites using Internet Explorer (version 9 or higher) and Microsoft Edge's tracking protection feature. This feature blocks third-party content, including cookies, on sites that are included in user-added anti-tracking lists.
		
•	Some browsers have built-in Do Not Track (DNT) features, which can signal to websites that they do not want to be tracked. Because there is still no common understanding of how to interpret DNT signals, Microsoft services are not currently responding to browser DNT signals. We are working with other online vendors to define a common understanding of how to handle DNT signals. In this context, you may use other tools we provide to manage data collection and use, such as the ability to opt-out of the delivery of interest-based advertising from Microsoft, as described above.
	
Cookies and similar technologies
	
Cookies are small text files that are placed on a user's device. This file stores the data and is later read by the web server of the domain that issued the cookie. This data consists of a string of numbers and letters that uniquely identify your computer, but it may also contain other information. Some cookies are placed by third parties and work on our behalf. We use cookies and similar technologies for the legitimate purposes described below, such as storing user choices and settings, performing sign-ins, serving interest-based advertising, preventing fraud, and analyzing the performance of our products. Microsoft apps use additional identifiers, such as the Windows advertising identifier, for similar purposes. Many of our websites and applications contain web beacons and similar technologies, such as:
	
Microsoft's use of cookies and similar technologies
	
Microsoft uses cookies and similar technologies for a variety of purposes, including the following purposes, depending on the context or product.
		
•	Saving user settings and settings. Cookies are used to store preferences and preferences on the user's device and to enhance the experience. For example, depending on your preferences, if you enter your area name or zip code to see local news and weather information on our websites, that information will be stored in cookies and will show you relevant local information when you return to the site. You can use cookies to save your preferences, such as your preferred language, so you don't have to repeatedly specify your preferences. If a user opts out of interest-based advertising, a cookie placed on the user's device stores their opt-out preferences. And if you have your consent to add cookies to your device, we will store your choices in cookies.
		
•	Sign-in and authentication. Cookies are used to authenticate users. When a user signs in to a website using a personal Microsoft account, their unique ID number and sign-in time are stored as an encrypted cookie on the user's device. This cookie allows you to navigate to different pages without having to sign in for each page. You can also save your sign-in information so you don't have to sign in every time you return to the same site.
		
•	Security. Cookies are used to process information that helps secure our products and detect unauthorized use or abuse.
		
•	storage of information that users provide to websites; Cookies are used to store information shared by users. When you provide information to Microsoft (for example, by adding a product to your shopping cart on our website), the data is stored in cookies for the purpose of remembering the information.
		
•	Social media. Some of our websites contain social media cookies. For example, cookies that allow users who sign in to a social media service to share content using that service.
		
•	Feedback. Microsoft uses cookies to allow us to provide feedback about our website.
		
•	Interest-based advertising. Microsoft uses cookies to collect data about your online activity so that we can provide you with relevant advertising and to determine your interests. As described in the "How to access and manage your personal data" section of this Privacy Statement, you can opt out of receiving interest-based advertising from Microsoft.
		
•	Display ads. Microsoft uses cookies to record the number of visitors who click on your ads. We also use it to record information such as which ads were shown to users so that the same ad is not shown repeatedly.
		
•	Analysis. To collect usage and performance data, we use cookies and other identifiers from first and third parties. For example, we use cookies to count visits to web pages or services and to create other statistics about the behavior of our sites and products.
		
•	Performance. Microsoft uses cookies to understand and improve the performance of our products. For example, we use cookies to collect data to help with load balancing. This helps keep our website up and running.
	
If necessary, we will obtain your consent before placing optional cookies that are (i) not strictly necessary to provide the website or (ii) necessary to facilitate communication. For more information, please refer to the "How to control cookies" section below.
	
Here are some examples of the cookies we typically use: This list is not exhaustive, but it does indicate the main purpose for which we set cookies. When you visit a Microsoft website, that site sets all or some of the following cookies:
		
•	MSCC。 Includes most Microsoft property choices.
		
•	MUID、MC1、MSFPC、MSPTC。 Identify the unique browser that visits Microsoft's site. These cookies are used for necessary operational purposes. If you have consent, these cookies may also be used for advertising.
		
•	ANON。 It includes an ANID (a unique identifier derived from a user's Microsoft account that determines which ads they prefer or is used for operational purposes). We also use it to store your choice to opt out of seeing interest-based ads from Microsoft if you choose to associate your Microsoft account with them.
		
•	CC。 It contains the country name code that is determined by the IP address.
		
•	PPAuth、MSPAuth、MSNRPSAuth、KievRPSAuth、WLSSC、MSPProf。 Microsoft accounts help users verify the authentication required when they sign in.
		
•	MC0。 Detect if cookies are enabled in your browser.
		
•	MS0。 Identify specific sessions.
		
•	NAP。 Store encrypted information about the user's country, zip code, age, gender, language, and occupation to the extent that it is known based on the user's Microsoft account profile.
		
•	MH。 It appears on co-branded sites that Microsoft partners with advertisers. This cookie identifies advertisers to help select the right ads.
		
•	childinfo、kcdob、kcrelid、kcru、pcfm。 On the Microsoft account page, store the information you use in connection with your child's account.
		
•	MR。 This cookie is used by Microsoft to reset or update the MUID cookie.
		
•	x-ms-gateway-slice。 Identify the gateway for load balancing.
		
•	TOptOut。 Record your decision not to receive interest-based advertising from Microsoft. If necessary, we place this cookie by default and delete it when you consent to interest-based advertising.
		
•	ApplicationGatewayAffinity and ApplicationGatewayAffinityCORS. These session cookies are used for load balancing and ensure that user session requests are handled by the same server.
	
We may also use cookies from other Microsoft affiliates, companies, and partners, such as LinkedIn and Xandr.
	
Third-party cookies
	
In addition to the cookies that Microsoft sets when you visit our websites, we use cookies from third parties to enhance our site's services. Some third parties may also set cookies when you visit a Microsoft site. Example:
		
•	When you browse our site, cookies are placed by the companies we contract to provide services such as site analytics.
		
•	Companies that deliver content on Microsoft sites, such as videos, news, and advertisements, place their own cookies.
	
These companies may use the processed data in accordance with their own privacy policies, which may allow them to collect and combine information about user activity on their websites, apps, and online services.
	
Depending on the context, service or product, and your preferences and permissions, we may use the following types of third-party cookies:
		
•	Social Media Cookies. We and third parties use social media cookies to display ads and content based on your social media profiles and activity on our website. They are used to associate your activity on our website with your social media profiles, so that the ads and content you see on our website and social media will better reflect your interests.
		
•	Analytics cookies. Third parties use analytics cookies to help us understand how you use our website. This allows third parties to develop and improve products that may be used on websites that are not owned or operated by Microsoft. For example, analytics cookies are used to collect information about the pages you visit and the number of clicks you need to perform a task. These cookies may also be used for advertising purposes.
		
•	Advertising cookies. We and third parties use advertising cookies to show you new ads by recording ads you have already viewed. It is also used to track ads that you click on for payment purposes or purchases you make after clicking on an ad, as well as to show you more relevant ads. For example, it is used to detect that you have clicked on an ad based on your social media interests or website browsing history and to display ads.
		
•	Essential cookies. We use essential cookies to perform important website functions. For example, it logs in, saves language preferences, provides a shopping cart experience, improves performance, routes traffic between web servers, detects screen size, determines page load times, and measures target audiences. These cookies are necessary for our website to function.
	
If necessary, we will obtain your consent before placing optional cookies that are (i) not strictly necessary to provide the website or (ii) necessary to facilitate communication.
	
For a list of third parties that have set cookies on our website, including service providers on our behalf, please refer to our Third-Party Cookie Inventory (https://support.microsoft.com/topic/81ca0c3d-c122-415c-874c-55610e017a6a)See ". The third-party cookie inventory also includes links to third-party websites or privacy notices. For more information about the privacy policy regarding cookies that may be set on Microsoft's websites, see the third-party website or privacy notice. Some websites make third-party listings available directly on the site. Third parties on these sites may not be on the list of third-party cookies inventory (https://support.microsoft.com/topic/81ca0c3d-c122-415c-874c-55610e017a6a).
	
How to control cookies
	
While many web browsers automatically accept cookies, they also offer controls to block or delete cookies. For example, in Microsoft Edge, you can block or delete cookies by selecting Settings> Privacy & Services> Clear browsing data> Cookies and other site data. For more information about how to delete cookies in the Microsoft browser, see Microsoft Edge (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2112473), Microsoft Edge Legacy (https://support.microsoft.com/microsoft-edge/delete-cookies-in-microsoft-edge-63947406-40ac-c3b8-57b9-2a946a29ae09), or Internet Explorer (https://support.microsoft.com/windows/delete-and-manage-cookies-168dab11-0753-043d-7c16-ede5947fc64d). If you are using a different browser, see the instructions for your browser.
	
As noted above, if necessary, we will obtain your consent before placing or using optional cookies that are (i) not strictly necessary to provide the website or (ii) not necessary to facilitate communication. These optional cookies are separated according to their purpose, such as for advertising or social media use. You may agree to certain categories of optional cookies and not others. You can also adjust your choice by clicking "Manage cookies" in the footer of the website or by setting it to be available on the website. Some features of Microsoft products rely on cookies. If you choose to block cookies, you will not be able to sign in, you will not be able to use some features that rely on cookies, and you will lose any preferences that rely on cookies. If you choose to delete cookies, your personal preferences controlled by cookies, such as your ad preferences, will be deleted. Please note that if you need it later, you will have to set it up again.
	
For additional privacy controls that affect cookies, including the Microsoft browser's anti-tracking capabilities, please see the "How to access and manage your personal data" section of this privacy statement.
	
Web Beacon and Analytics Services
	
Some Microsoft web pages contain electronic tags called web beacons. Microsoft uses web beacons to send cookies to Microsoft websites to count visits to those websites and to provide products through co-branding. The electronic communications we send also use web beacons or similar technologies to let us know when a message has been opened or what has happened after it has been opened.
	
In addition to placing web beacons on our websites, we may also work with other companies to place web beacons on their websites and advertisements. This allows us to capture statistics on how clicks on ads placed on Microsoft's websites led to purchases of products or other actions on the advertiser's website. It also allows us to understand activity on Microsoft partner websites in connection with your use of Microsoft products or services.
	
Finally, Microsoft products typically include web beacons and similar technologies provided by third-party analytics providers that we use to gather aggregated statistics about the effectiveness of our promotional campaigns and other activities. These technologies enable analytics providers to set or read their own cookies and other identifiers on your device to collect information about your online activities in applications, websites, and other products. However, we prohibit these analytics providers from using web beacons on our sites to collect or access information that directly identifies you (such as your name or email address). You can opt out of the collection or use of your data by these analytics providers by visiting one of the following sites: Adjust (https://www.adjust.com/opt-out/), AppsFlyer (https://www.appsflyer.com/optout), Clicktale (https://www.clicktale.net/disable.html), Flurry Analytics (https://developer.yahoo.com/flurry/end-user-opt-out/), and Google Analytics (https://tools.google.com/dlpage/gaoptout) (You need to install the add-on for your browser), Kissmetrics (https://signin.kissmetrics.com/privacy/#controls), Mixpanel (https://mixpanel.com/optout), Nielsen (https://priv-policy.imrworldwide.com/priv/browser/us/en/optout.html), Acuity Ads (https://www.acuityads.com/opt-out/), WebTrends (https://ondemand.webtrends.com/support/optout.asp), or Optimizely (https://www.optimizely.com/legal/opt-out/).
	
Other Similar Technologies
	
Our products may use regular cookies and web beacons, as well as other similar technologies, to store and load data files on your computer. Typically, saving specific files locally allows you to maintain user settings and improve speed and performance. However, in addition to storing a user's computer-specific identifier like regular cookies, these technologies can also track user behavior. These technologies include local shared objects (or "Flash cookies") and Silverlight application storage.
	
Local shared objects or "Flash cookies." Websites that use Adobe Flash technology can use local shared objects or "Flash cookies" to store data on your computer. To learn how to manage or block Flash cookies, visit the Flash Player Help page (https://www.macromedia.com/support/documentation/en/flashplayer/help/settings_manager.html).
	
Silverlight application storage. Websites and applications that use Microsoft Silverlight technology also have the ability to store data with Silverlight application storage. For information on how to manage and block the storage of such data, see the Silverlight (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainsilverlightmodule)section of this Privacy Statement.
	
