– notifications to end users
	
If you use Microsoft products using an account provided by your organization (such as a work or school account), your organization may:
		
•	Manage your Microsoft products and product accounts, including managing privacy-related settings for your products or product accounts.
		
•	Access and processing of your data, including interactive data, diagnostic data, and the contents of communications and files associated with your Microsoft products and product accounts.
	
If you lose access to your work or school account (for example, if you change your place of work), you may also lose access to the product and the content associated with that product, including any that you acquired, for products that were signed in to that work or school account.
	
Many Microsoft products are intended for use in organizations, such as schools and businesses. See the Enterprise and Developer Products section of this Privacy Statement. If your organization provides access to Microsoft products, your use of Microsoft products is subject to your organization's policies (if any). If you have any privacy questions, such as requests to exercise your data protection rights, please contact your organization's administrator. When you use social features in Microsoft products, your activity may be known to other users on your network. For more information about social features and other features, see the documentation or help content specific to the Microsoft product in question. Microsoft is not responsible for your privacy or security practices, which may differ from those set forth in this Statement.
	
If you use a Microsoft product provided by your organization, the agreement between Microsoft and your organization governs how Microsoft processes your personal data in connection with that product. Microsoft is committed to providing products to organizations and users, and to create products for enterprise and developers. We process your personal data for Microsoft's business operations in connection with the offering of the products described in the section. As noted above, if you have any questions about Microsoft's processing of your personal data in connection with the provision of products to your organization, please contact your organization. If you have any questions about Microsoft's business operations related to the provision of products to your organization as described in the Product Agreement, please contact Microsoft as described in the How to Contact Us (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainhowtocontactusmodule) section. For more information about Microsoft's business operations, see Enterprise and Developer Productssection.
	
For Microsoft products offered by kindergarten through high school educational institutions, such as Microsoft 365 Education, Microsoft is doing the following:
		
•	We do not collect or use any personal data of students beyond what is necessary for accredited educational or school purposes.
		
•	We do not sell or rent student personal data.
		
•	We do not use or share student personal data for advertising or similar commercial purposes, such as behavioral targeting of advertising to students.
		
•	We do not create a personal profile of a student unless it supports the purpose of an accredited education or school, or is certified by a parent, guardian, or student of appropriate age.
		
•	We require vendors (if any) with whom we share student personal data to provide educational services to be obligated to implement these similar commitments for student personal data.
	
Microsoft account
	
With a Microsoft account, you can sign in to Microsoft products, as well as products from select Microsoft partners. The personal data associated with your Microsoft account includes credentials, name, contact data, payment data, device and usage data, contacts, activity, and information about your interests and favorites. When users sign in to their Microsoft account, they enable personalization and a consistent experience across products and devices, as well as the ability to use cloud data storage, pay with payment methods stored in their Microsoft account, and other features. There are three types of Microsoft accounts:
		
•	If a user creates their own Microsoft account associated with a personal email address, that account is considered a personal Microsoft account.
		
•	If a Microsoft account is created by a user or an organization (such as work or school) associated with an email address provided to the user by that organization, the account is considered a work or school account.
		
•	If a Microsoft account is created by a user or service provider (such as a cable TV or Internet service provider) associated with an email address that contains that service provider's domain, the account is considered a third-party account.
	
Personal Microsoft account. The data associated with your personal Microsoft account and how you use that data depends on how you use your account.
		
•	Create a Microsoft account. When you create a personal Microsoft account, you will be asked to provide certain personal data. We assign a unique ID number to identify your account and the information associated with it. Some products with payment require a real name, while others can be used by signing in without providing a real name. Some data you provide, such as your display name, email address, and phone number, may help others search and contact you within Microsoft products. For example, other people who know your display name, email address, or phone number may use it to search for and interact with your personal Microsoft Teams. If you create a personal Microsoft account using your work or school email address, your employer or school may have access to your data. In some cases, you may need to change your email address to a personal email address to continue accessing consumer products (such as the Xbox network).
		
•	Sign in to your Microsoft account. When you sign in to your Microsoft account, a sign-in record is created. This includes the date and time, the product you signed in to, the sign-in name, the unique number assigned to your account, the unique identifier assigned to your device, your IP address, and your operating system and browser version.
		
•	Sign in to Microsoft products. When users sign in to their accounts, they can provide even more personalized settings, providing a seamless and consistent experience across products and devices. It also allows you to access and use cloud data storage, pay with payment methods stored in your Microsoft account, and other enhancements and settings. For example, when you sign in, Microsoft makes the information stored in your account available across Microsoft products, so important things are where they need to be. When a user signs in to their account, it remains that way until they sign out. If a user adds a Microsoft account to a Windows device (version 8 or later), Windows automatically signs in to that product when the user accesses a product that uses a Microsoft account on that device. When you sign in, some products display your full name or username or profile picture as part of your use of Microsoft products (if you've added them to your profile). This includes user interactions, social interactions, and public posts. Learn more about your Microsoft account, data, and choices (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2205470).
		
•	Sign in to a third-party product. If you sign in to a third-party product with a Microsoft account, your data will be shared with the third party in accordance with the third-party privacy policy. The third party also receives the version number assigned to the account (a new version number is assigned each time the sign-in information changes) and information that indicates whether the account is disabled. When a user shares their profile data, a third party can display the user's name or username and profile picture (if the user adds a photo to their profile) when the user signs in to that third-party product. If you use your Microsoft account to pay a third-party business, the information stored in your Microsoft account that is necessary to process your payment and order, such as your name, credit card number, billing/shipping address, and related contact information, may be stored by Microsoft from the third-party or contractor (such as a storage agent) It is provided to. Third parties may use or share data received when a user logs in or purchases a product in accordance with their own policies and policies. Please read the privacy statement of each service or product vendor you sign in to understand how the information collected by that product is used.
	
Work or school account. The data associated with a work or school account and how it is used is generally similar to the use and collection of data associated with an individual's Microsoft account.
	
If an account provided by your work or school is managed using Microsoft Entra ID, users can use their work or school account to sign in to Microsoft products such as Microsoft 365 and Office 365, as well as third-party products provided by your organization. If requested by a company, school, etc., users may be asked to provide a phone number or alternative email address for additional security verification. If your organization allows you to sign in to Microsoft products or third-party products that you get using your work or school account.
	
If you use your work or school account to sign in to Microsoft products, keep the following in mind:
		
•	The owner of the domain associated with the user's email address may control the account to access and process user data, such as communications and file content. This includes data stored in products provided to users by your organization and products you obtain yourself.
		
•	Use of the product is subject to your organization's policies, if any. Before you decide to use your work or school account to sign in to a product you obtained, you should review your organization's policies and consider whether you don't mind allowing your organization access to your data.
		
•	If you lose access to your work or school account (for example, if you change your place of work), you may also lose access to the product and the content associated with that product, including any that you acquired, for products that were signed in to that work or school account.
		
•	The privacy and security practices of your organization may differ from Microsoft's, and Microsoft is not responsible for them.
		
•	If your organization controls your use of Microsoft products, contact your organization's administrator if you have any privacy questions, such as requests to exercise data subject rights. Please also see the "Notice to End Users" section of this Privacy Statement.
		
•	If you're not sure whether your account is a work or school account, contact your organization.
	
Third-party accounts. The data associated with a third-party Microsoft account and its use is generally similar to the use and collection of data associated with an individual's Microsoft account. The service provider controls the user's account and can access or delete the account. You should carefully review the terms and conditions provided by the third party and understand what the third party can do with your account.
	
Collection of data from your child
	
For users under the age of 13 specified in jurisdictions, certain Microsoft products and services require parental consent or approval before use, including blocking users under that age or creating an account to access Microsoft services. We will not ask for more data than necessary to provide products to children of that age.
	
Once parental consent or approval is obtained, your child's account will be treated like any other account. In that case, your child can access communication services like Outlook and Teams, freely communicate with other users of all ages, and share data. View parental consent and your child's Microsoft account details (https://support.microsoft.com/help/4090274/microsoft-account-parental-consent-and-child-accounts).
	
Parents can change or revoke previously given consent choices. As a Microsoft Family Group organizer, parents or guardians can manage their child's personal information and settings on the Family Safety (https://account.microsoft.com/family) page and in the Privacy Dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy). You can view and delete your child's data on the Accounts that require parental consent to create are automatically included as part of the family group of individuals who have consented to create an account. If you don't need parental consent to create a child's account (for example, if your child is over the legally required age for parental consent), the parent or guardian can still use the family group, but you'll need to add your child's account to the family group after the account is created. For more information on how to access and delete your child's data, see:
	
Additional information about the collection of data from children related to Xbox, including more information, is provided below.
	
Accessing and deleting your child's data. For Microsoft products and services that require parental consent, parents can view and delete certain data belonging to their child from the parental privacy dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy). This includes browsing history, search history, location activity, media activity, app and service activity, and product and service performance data. To delete this data, parents can sign in to the Privacy Dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy) and manage their child's activities. Parents' ability to access and delete their child's personal information in the Privacy Dashboard depends on the laws of your location.
	
In addition, parents can complete the Privacy Support Form (https://aka.ms/privacyresponse) through the Privacy Support Team (https://aka.ms/privacyresponse) After verification, you can request that we delete the following data along with the data types in the Privacy Dashboard: Software, Setup, Inventory, Device Connectivity and Configuration, Feedback and Ratings, Fitness and Activity, Support Content, Support Interactions, and Environmental Sensors. Authenticated removal requests will be processed within 30 days of receipt.
	
Content such as emails, contacts, and chats can be accessed through the in-product experience. For more information about the data you can control within Microsoft products, see Microsoft's Privacy Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs). (https://aka.ms/privacyfaq)
	
If your child's account is not part of a Microsoft family group and you don't have access to their activity in the privacy dashboard, you must submit a request for your child's data using the privacy support form (https://aka.ms/privacyresponse). The Privacy Team will require account verification before processing the request.
	
To delete all of your child's personal information, you must use the "Delete Account" form (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=523898) to request deletion of your child's account. When you click this link, you will be prompted to sign in with your child's account credentials. Make sure you see the correct Microsoft account on the page, and follow the instructions to request the removal of your child's account. Learn more about how to delete your Microsoft account (https://support.microsoft.com/account-billing/how-to-close-your-microsoft-account-c1b2d13f-4de6-6e1b-4a31-d9d668849979).
	
You have a 60-day grace period before your child's account is permanently deleted after you submit a request to delete your child's account, in case you want to undo the account deletion later or need to access the data on your account before it is permanently deleted. During the grace period, the account is subject to suspension and permanent deletion, but it still exists. If you want to reactivate your child's Microsoft account, sign in again within 60 days of the grace period. The account termination will be canceled and the account will be reactivated.
	
What is Xbox? Xbox is Microsoft's gaming and entertainment segment. Xbox hosts an online network made up of software, enabling online experiences across multiple platforms. This network allows children to search and play games, view content, and connect with friends on Xbox and other games and social networks.
	
When a user signs in to Xbox with an app, game, or Xbox console, the device is assigned a unique identifier. For example, if your Xbox console is connected to the Internet and you sign in to your console, it identifies the console you're using and the version of your console's operating system.
	
Xbox will continue to deliver new experiences with client apps that connect to and are supported by networks, such as Xbox services and cloud gaming. When you sign in to an Xbox experience, Microsoft collects essential data to keep these experiences secure, reliable, up-to-date, and working properly.
	
Data collected when you create an Xbox profile. As a parent or guardian, you must consent to the collection of personal data from children under the age of 13 or in accordance with jurisdictional designations. Use permissions to help your child get an Xbox profile and use Xbox on an online network. During the child's Xbox profile, sign in with their Microsoft account and verify that they're the adult host in the Microsoft family group. Collect alternative email addresses or phone numbers to improve account security. If your child needs help accessing their account, we will use this alternative information to verify that they have a Microsft account.
	
Limited information about your child is collected, such as name, date of birth, email address, and region. When your child signs up for an Xbox profile, they get a gamertag (a public nickname) and a unique identifier. When you create an Xbox profile for your child, you consent to the collection, use, and sharing of information by Microsoft based on your privacy and communications settings on the Xbox online network. Your child's privacy and communication settings are the most restrictive by default.
	
Data we collect. When your child uses Xbox services, games, apps, and devices, we collect the following information:
		
•	Xbox sign-in/sign-out dates and times, purchases, and content earned.
		
•	Games played, apps used, game progress, achievements, time played per game, and other statistics about playing.
		
•	Performance data about your Xbox console, Xbox Game Pass, and other Xbox apps, the Xbox network, connected accessories, and network connections, such as software and hardware errors.
		
•	Content that you add, upload, or share over the Xbox network, such as text, photos, and videos captured in games and apps.
		
•	Social activities such as chat data, interactions with other gamers, and connections on the Xbox network (friends you add or people you follow).
	
If you use your Xbox console or the Xbox app on another device that has access to the Xbox network, and that device contains a storage device (hard drive or memory unit), your usage data will be stored on the storage device and sent to Microsoft the next time you sign in to Xbox. The same applies even if you are playing offline.
	
Xbox diagnostic data. If your child is using an Xbox console, Xbox will send the required data to Microsoft. Required data is the minimum amount of data needed to keep your Xbox safe, secure, and up to date and working correctly.
	
Game capture. Any player in a multiplayer gaming session can record video (game clips) and capture screenshots of the view of the gameplay. Game clips and screenshots of other players can capture in-game characters and gamertags during that session. If a player captures a game clip or screenshot on their PC, the resulting game clip may also capture voice chat if the child's privacy or communication settings allow it on the Xbox online network.
	
Subtitles. During real-time ("party") chat on Xbox, players can activate the voice-to-text feature that allows them to view the chat as text. If the player enables this feature, Microsoft will use the resulting text data for the purpose of providing subtitles for chat to users who need them. This data can also be used to provide a safe gaming environment and enforce Xbox's community standards (https://www.xbox.com/legal/codeofconduct).
	
Use of Data. We use the data we collect to improve our game products and experiences when your child uses Xbox, making them safer and more enjoyable over time. The data we collect can also provide our children with a curated experience. This includes connecting children to games, content, services, and recommendations.
	
Xbox data that other users can view. When your child uses the Xbox network, their online presence (which can be set to "Offline" or "Blocked"), gamertag, gameplay stats, and achievement are visible to other players on the network. Your child's Xbox may share information when they play games or communicate with other players on the Xbox network, depending on their safety settings.
	
Security. To make the Xbox network a safe gaming environment and to enforce Xbox's Community Standards, we may collect and review audio, text, images, video, and in-game content (game clips, conversations, and content posted in clubs and games that your child uploads).
	
Anti-fraud and fraud prevention. Providing a fair gameplay environment is important to us. We prohibit cheating, hacking, account theft, and other cheating or cheating activities when your child uses Xbox online games or network-connected apps on their Xbox console, PC, or mobile device. We may use anti-cheat tools, anti-fraud tools, applications, and other technologies to detect and prevent cheating and cheating. Such technologies may use certain information collected from your Xbox console, PC, or mobile device and how you use that device to create a digital signature (called a "hash"). This may include information about your browser, device, activity, game identifiers, and operating system.
	
Xbox data shared with the publisher of the game or app. When a child uses an Xbox online game or networked app on an Xbox console, PC, or mobile device, the publisher of that game or app has access to usage data to help the publisher provide, support, and improve the product. This data may include your child's Xbox user ID, gamertag, and limited account information (such as country and age range), as well as data about in-game communications, Xbox running activity (such as in-game movements and the type of vehicle used in the game), presence on the Xbox network, time spent in the game or app, rankings, statistics, gamer profile, This includes your avatar or gamer icon, friends list, activity feed for your official club, club memberships, and content you create or submit in-game or in-app.
	
Third-party publishers and developers of games and apps have their own independent relationships with users, and the collection and use of personal data is subject to specific privacy policies. To find out how your child's data is used, read the publisher's policy carefully. For example, publishers may disclose or display game data through their own services (e.g., in leaderboards). These policies may be linked from the game or app details page in the Microsoft Store.
	
For more information, see Data sharing with games and apps (https://www.xbox.com/Legal/ThirdPartyDataSharing).
	
To stop sharing your game or app data with site administrators, remove it from all devices where you installed the game or app. Some publishers' access to children's data may be revoked in https://microsoft.com/consent.
	
AI-powered features. Children in certain jurisdictions may have access to AI-enhanced features on Xbox, such as Microsoft's support virtual agent. It allows users to enter prompts with text or voice. Support virtual agents are designed to assist users with support-related questions. To provide responses, these AI-enhanced features use prompts, publicly available support articles, and other relevant data described in the "Personal Data We Collect (https://www.microsoft.com/privacy/privacystatement#mainpersonaldatawecollectmodule)" section or features. Xbox's AI-powered features don't use your child's data to train your model. Learn more about Xbox Support Virtual Agents here (https://support.xbox.com/help/games-apps/xbox-ai/virtual-agent-faq).
	
Manage your child's settings. As a Microsoft Family Group organizer, you can manage your child's personal information and settings on the Family Safety (https://account.microsoft.com/family) page, and you can manage your Xbox profile privacy settings on the Xbox Privacy & Online Safety page (https://account.xbox.com/settings).
	 
You can also use the Xbox Family Settings (https://www.xbox.com/apps/family-settings-app) app to manage your child's experience, including Microsoft Store and Xbox Store consumption on the Xbox network, viewing your child's Xbox activity, and setting age ratings and amount of time spent. Xbox-specific Family Safety settings apply via Xbox on your Xbox console or PC or mobile device, but may not apply on other platforms.
	
For more information about managing your Xbox profile, see Xbox online safety and privacy settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2170314).
	
For more information about Microsoft family groups, see Simplify your family's life (https://account.microsoft.com/family/about).
	
•Legacy.
		
•	Xbox 360。 This Xbox console collects limited mandatory diagnostic data. This data helps you make sure your child's console is working correctly.
		
•	Kinect。 The Kinect sensor is a combination of camera, microphone, and infrared sensor that uses movement and voice to control gameplay. Here are some examples:
		
◦	If selected, you can use your camera to automatically sign in to the Xbox network with facial recognition. This data remains on the console, is not shared with anyone, and can be deleted at any time.
		
◦	In game play, Kinect maps the distance between the joints of the child's body, allowing them to create and play stickman representations.
		
◦	Kinect's microphone allows players to voice chat with each other, even while playing. You can use voice commands with this microphone to control your console, enter games, apps, and search criteria.
		
◦	The Kinect sensor can also be used for audio and video communication.
	
For more information about Kinect, see Xbox Kinect and privacy (https://aka.ms/kinectprivacy/).
	
Other important information about privacy
	
The following is additional information about privacy, such as how we protect your data, where we process it, and how long we store it. For more information about Microsoft and its commitment to privacy, see Microsoft privacy (https://privacy.microsoft.com/).
	
Security of personal information
	
Microsoft is committed to keeping your personal information secure. Microsoft uses a variety of security technologies and techniques to protect your personal information from unauthorized access, use, or disclosure. For example, personal information collected from users is stored on computers that are only accessible to a limited number of people in controlled facilities. When we send sensitive information, such as credit card numbers and passwords, over the Internet, we use encryption to protect it. Microsoft follows applicable data protection laws. This includes applicable laws regarding security breach notifications.

Where personal data is stored and processed
	
Personal data collected by Microsoft may be stored and processed in your region or in the United States, or in other jurisdictions where Microsoft, its affiliates, subsidiaries, or service provider facilities operate. Microsoft has major data centers in Australia, Austria, Brazil, Canada, Finland, France, Germany, Hong Kong SAR, India, Ireland, Japan, South Korea, Luxembourg, Malaysia, the Netherlands, Singapore, South Africa, the United Kingdom, and the United States. Typically, the primary storage location is in the user's region or in the United States (data center backups are often located in other regions). Storage locations are chosen to operate and deliver services efficiently, improve performance, and ensure redundancy to protect data in case of failures or other issues. We have taken the necessary measures to process the data we collect based on this Privacy Statement in accordance with the provisions of this Statement and the requirements of the law.
	
We transfer personal data from the European Economic Area, the United Kingdom, and Switzerland to other countries, some of which are not recognized by the European Commission as having an adequate level of data protection. For example, the laws of such countries may not guarantee the same rights, or there may not be a privacy supervisory authority that can handle complaints. We use a variety of legal mechanisms, including the Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs) issued by the European Commission under the Commission Implementing Decision 2021/914 to protect data as well as user rights. For more information about the European Commission's decisions on the adequacy of personal data protection in the countries where Microsoft processes personal data, please visit the European Commission website (https://commission.europa.eu/law/law-topic/data-protection/international-dimension-data-protection_en) article.
	
Microsoft Corporation complies with the EU-U.S. Data Privacy Framework (EU-U.S. DPF) as set forth by the U.S. Department of Commerce, the UK extension to the EU-U.S. DPF, and the Swiss-U.S. Data Privacy Framework (Swiss-U.S. DPF). Microsoft Corporation has certified to the U.S. Department of Commerce that it complies with the EU-U.S. Data Privacy Framework Principles (EU-U.S. DPF Principles) with respect to the processing of personal data received from the European Union under the EU-U.S. DPF and from the United Kingdom (and Gibraltar) under the UK extension to the EU-U.S. DPF. Microsoft Corporation has been certified by the U.S. Department of Commerce to comply with the Swiss-U.S. Data Privacy Framework Principles (Swiss-U.S. DPF Principles) with respect to the processing of personal data received from Switzerland in reliance on the Swiss-U.S. DPF. For transfers, Microsoft Corporation is responsible for the processing of personal data received under the DPF and subsequently transfers to third parties acting as agents on our behalf. Microsoft Corporation will remain liable under the DPF unless Microsoft Corporation can prove that its agents are not responsible for the event causing the damage if our agents process such personal information contrary to the DPF. In the event of any conflict between the terms of this Privacy Statement and the EU-U.S. DPF Principles and/or the Swiss-U.S. DPF Principles, the Principles will control. To learn more about the Data Privacy Framework (DPF) program and its certifications, visit the U.S. Department of Commerce's Data Privacy Framework website (https://www.dataprivacyframework.gov/). The U.S. affiliates of Microsoft Corporation identified in the self-attestation application also follow the DPF Principles. For more information, see the list of Microsoft affiliates in the United States that are eligible for Data Privacy Framework certification (https://microsoft.com/privacy/microsoft-data-privacy-framework-covered-entities).
	
If you have any questions or complaints about Microsoft's participation in the DPF framework, please contact us in the web form (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2126612)Please contact us from. For complaints about the DPF framework that cannot be resolved directly by Microsoft, you can contact the relevant EU data protection authorities, the Commission established by the European Data Protection Authority to Resolve Disputes Concerning EU Individuals, the UK Information Commissioner (UK Individuals), and the Swiss Federal Data Protection and Information Commission (FDPIC) for Resolving Disputes Concerning Swiss Individuals We will cooperate with the Resolution of Disputes. For contact details of data protection authorities, please contact us. As detailed in the DPF Principles, there is also a means of binding arbitration for complaints that cannot be resolved otherwise. Microsoft is subject to the investigative and enforcement powers of the U.S. Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
	
Individuals whose personal data is protected by Japan's laws on the protection of personal information should refer to the article on the Personal Information Protection Commission website (Japanese (https://www.ppc.go.jp/personalinfo/legal/kaiseihogohou/#gaikoku)) (published only in Japanese) for more information on the Commission's review of the personal data protection system in a particular country. For individuals in Japan, please click here (https://aka.ms/JapanTBAnotice)for more information on the processing of information under the Telecommunications Business Act (Japanese only).
	
Retention of personal data
	
Microsoft retains personal data for as long as necessary to provide the Products, fulfill the transactions requested by users, and to fulfill legitimate purposes, such as complying with legal obligations, resolving disputes, and enforcing contracts. This need depends on the type of data, the agreement between you and us, or the use of each product, so the actual storage period can vary greatly.
	
Other conditions for determining the 
storage period include:
		
•	When customers provide, create, or manage data, are they required to be stored by Microsoft until the customer intentionally deletes it? This includes documents stored in OneDrive, email messages stored in Outlook.com inbox, and more. In such cases, Microsoft aims to save the data until the user actively deletes it (for example, by moving the email from the Outlook.com inbox to the Deleted Items folder and then emptying the folder). If a user empties the Deleted Items folder, the items in that folder will remain on Microsoft's systems for up to 30 days before they are finally deleted (or for other reasons, such as if you exceed the amount of data you can keep in your account, you may need to delete your data sooner).
		
•	Are there any automated controls that allow customers to access and delete their personal data at any time, such as the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard? If not, a short data retention period is generally employed.
		
•	Whether your personal data is confidential. If your personal data is confidential, a short retention period is usually applied.
		
•	Does Microsoft apply and announce specific retention periods for certain types of data? For example, for Bing search queries, the stored search queries are anonymized. As such, IP addresses are permanently deleted after 6 months, and cookies and other inter-session identifiers used to identify specific accounts or devices are permanently deleted after 18 months.
		
•	Does the user agree to long-term retention? In this case, the data will be stored according to your consent.
	
•	Does Microsoft have a legal or contractual or similar obligation to store or delete data? For example, you should consider data retention laws that are enforceable in your applicable jurisdiction, administrative orders regarding the retention of data related to investigations, and data that needs to be stored for litigation purposes. On the other hand, if the law requires the removal of illegal content, we will take action to do so.
	
U.S. State Data Privacy
	
If you are a U.S. resident, we process your personal data in accordance with applicable U.S. state data privacy laws, including the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA). This section of our Privacy Statement contains information required by the CCPA and other U.S. state data privacy laws and supplements our Privacy Statement.
	
It should be noted that the rules implementing some of these laws have not yet been finalized. These implementation rules are finalized and, as appropriate, the process, disclosures, and this notice are updated.
	
Please also see the U.S. State Data Privacy Law Notice (https://aka.ms/USStatePrivacyNotice) and the Consumer Health Data Privacy Policy (https://privacy.microsoft.com/microsoft-consumer-health-data-privacy-policy) for additional information about the data we collect, process, share, and disclose, and your rights under applicable U.S. state data privacy laws.
	
Sale. Microsoft does not sell personal information. For this reason, we do not provide you with the ability to opt out of the sale of your personal data.
	
profile. Microsoft does not engage in "profiles" that utilize personal data for automated decision-making that produces legal or equally important effects. As such, we do not provide opt-out for this type of profile.
	
Shared. We may "share" your personal data as defined in California and other applicable U.S. state laws. As described in the Ads (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainadvertisingmodule) section, we do not serve personalized ads to children identified as under the age of 18 by their date of birth in their Microsoft account.
	
