We will not use or disclose Confidential Data for any purpose other than the following purposes:
		
•	To perform services or provide goods that you reasonably expect
		
•	To the extent the processing is reasonably necessary and appropriate to ensure the security and integrity of our services, systems, and data, to combat malicious deceptive, fraudulent, or illegal activities, and to protect the physical safety of individuals.
		
•	For short-term, temporary use (including non-personalized advertising) unless the personal data is disclosed to third parties, used for profiling, and used to modify the individual's experience outside of current interactions with Microsoft;
		
•	Perform services on Microsoft's behalf, such as maintaining accounts, providing customer service, processing or fulfilling orders/transactions, verifying customer information, processing payments, providing financing, providing analytics, providing storage, and similar services
		
•	Conduct activities to verify or maintain the quality or safety of, or to improve, upgrade, or enhance Microsoft-owned or controlled services or devices
		
•	Collect or process sensitive data not to infer personal characteristics
		
•	Other activities in accordance with future regulations issued in accordance with U.S. state data privacy laws
	
De-identified data. In some circumstances, Microsoft may process anonymized data. If we are unable to associate the data with an individual to whom such data may be associated without taking additional steps, the data will be in this state. In such cases, we will maintain such information in an anonymized state and will not attempt to re-identify the individual to whom the anonymized data relates, unless permitted by applicable law.
	
Disclosure of personal data for business or commercial purposes. As indicated in the "Why We Share Personal Data" section, we share personal data with third parties for a variety of business or commercial purposes. The main business and commercial purposes for which we share personal data are the processing purposes set out in the table above. However, we share all categories of personal data with third parties for business and commercial purposes as described in the "Why We Share Personal Data" section.
	
Parties that control the collection of personal data. In certain circumstances, we may allow third parties to control the collection of your personal data. For example, third-party applications or extensions running on Windows or Edge browsers may collect personal data based on their own practices.
	
Microsoft allows advertising companies to collect information about your interactions with our websites in order to serve personalized ads on Microsoft's behalf. You can find out more about Microsoft's third-party advertising partners (https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/xandr/policies-regulations/third-party-providers) in the U.S. State Data Privacy Law Notice (https://aka.ms/USStatePrivacyNotice) and opt out of sharing your data with third parties on the opt-out page (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2214802).
	
advertisement
	
Advertising helps us provide, support, and improve our products. Microsoft does not use your statements, documents, photos, or personal files in email, chat, or video calls for targeted advertising. We use other data detailed below to advertise on Microsoft and third-party properties. Example:
		
•	Microsoft may use the data we collect to select and serve you some of the ads that appear on Microsoft web properties, such as Microsoft.com (https://protect-us.mimecast.com/s/OrHGC0R9D5fY4mx8Cwq8Qu?domain=microsoft.com), Microsoft Start, and Bing. We may also use this data to select and serve ads for third-party digital properties.
		
•	If advertising identifiers are enabled as part of your Windows privacy settings, third parties can access and use them to select and serve ads that appear in your app. This works much the same way that a website accesses and uses a unique identifier stored in a cookie.
		
•	Microsoft may share the data we collect with internal and external partners, such as Xandr, Yahoo, and Facebook (see below). This makes Microsoft products and the ads they appear on them more relevant and valuable to our customers.
		
•	Advertisers can choose to place web beacons on their sites or use similar technologies to help Microsoft collect information such as activity, purchases, and visits on advertisers' sites. We use this data to serve ads on behalf of advertisers.
	
The ads you see may be selected based on the data you process with your personal information, such as your interests and favorites, location, transactions, how you use our products, search queries, and the content you view. For example, if you view content about cars in Microsoft Start, you may see ads about cars. When you search for "pizzerias in Seattle" on Bing, you may see ads for restaurants in Seattle in search results.
	
In addition, you may see ads that are selected based on other information that you have learned about you over time. We use demographic data, location data, search queries, interests and favorites, usage data of our products and sites, and information about users collected from our advertisers and partners' sites and apps. In this statement, we refer to these ads as "personalized ads". For example, if you access game content on xbox.com (https://www.xbox.com/), you may see ads for your game on Microsoft Start. To provide you with personalized advertising, we use the information we collect when your browser interacts with our website (such as your IP address) to combine multiple cookies placed on your device. If you choose not to receive personalized ads, the data associated with these cookies will not be used.
	
When you use Microsoft services, Microsoft may use information about you to provide personalized advertising. If you're signed in with a Microsoft account and have consented to Microsoft Edge using your online activities for personalized advertising, you'll see ads for products and services based on your online activity while using Microsoft Edge. To configure Edge privacy settings, go to Microsoft Edge > Settings > Privacy & services. To configure your Microsoft account's privacy and advertising settings for your online activities across browsers, such as when you visit Microsoft Edge or third-party websites or apps, visit your privacy.microsoft.com (https://privacy.microsoft.com/) dashboard.
	
For more information about our use of personal data in connection with advertising, please see below.
		
•	Best practices and commitments in the advertising industry. Microsoft is a member of the Network Advertising Initiative (https://www.networkadvertising.org/) (NAI) and adheres to the NAI's Code of Ethics. Microsoft also adheres to the following self-regulatory programs:
		
◦	In the United States:  Digital Advertising Alliance (DAA) (https://www.aboutads.info/)
		
◦	In Europe:  European Interactive Digital Advertising Alliance (EDAA) (https://www.youronlinechoices.com/)
		
◦	In Canada: Ad Choices: Digital Advertising Alliance of Canada (DAAC) (https://www.youradchoices.ca/)
		
•	Targeting health-related ads. In the United States, we offer limited personalized ads for the usual, non-confidential health-related categories such as allergies, arthritis, cholesterol, colds, flu, diabetes, gastrointestinal health, headaches/migraines, healthy eating, healthy heart, men's health, oral health, osteoporosis, skin health, sleep, and vision/eye care. We also tailor our ads to your tailored health-related interest categories upon request.
		
•	Children and advertising. We don't serve personalized ads to children whose Microsoft account can verify that they are 18 years of age or younger.
		
•	Data retention. We retain personal information for up to 13 months for personalized advertising. However, this does not apply if the user agrees to keep personal information for a longer period of time.
		
•	Sensitive data. Microsoft Advertising does not collect, process, or disclose personal data that is considered "sensitive data" under applicable U.S. data privacy laws for the purpose of providing personalized advertising.
		
•	Data sharing. We may share reports with advertisers about the personal information we collect on their sites and advertisements.
	
Information collected by other advertising companies. Advertisers may set and load their own cookies, including advertisers' web beacons (or those of other advertisers' advertising partners) in those ads we display. In addition, Microsoft uses Xandr (https://about.ads.microsoft.com/solutions/xandr/platform-privacy-policy) to help provide some of Microsoft's advertising services. 
Microsoft companies, and third-party advertising companies that allow other third-party advertising companies to display ads on our site. These third parties may place cookies on your computer and may also collect information about your online activities across websites or online services. These companies currently include, but are not limited to: Facebook (https://www.facebook.com/help/568137493302217), Media.net (https://www.media.net/adchoices), Outbrain (https://my.outbrain.com/recommendations-settings/home), Taboola (https://www.taboola.com/privacy-policy#user-choices-and-optout), Yahoo (https://legal.yahoo.com/xw/en/yahoo/privacy/intl/index.html)。 For more information about the processing and choices of each company regarding your personal data, please select one of the links above. Many of these companies are also members of the NAI (https://thenai.org/opt-out/) or DAA (http://www.aboutads.info/choices/). Both organizations provide an easy way to opt out of targeted advertising for participating companies.
	
To opt out of receiving personalized ads from Microsoft, visit our opt-out (http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=286759) page. If you opt out, your settings will be stored in a cookie unique to your web browser. Opt-out cookies are valid for 5 years. If you delete cookies from your device, you will need to opt out again.
	
Speech recognition technology
	
Speech recognition is integrated into many Microsoft products and services. Microsoft offers both device-based speech recognition and cloud-based (online) speech recognition capabilities. Microsoft's speech recognition technology converts speech data into text. With your permission, Microsoft employees or vendors on behalf of Microsoft may review snippets of audio data and audio clips to build and improve speech recognition technology. This improvement will enable the creation of better voice-enabled capabilities that will benefit all consumer and business products and services. Microsoft protects user privacy before employees or vendors review their voice data in the following ways: Perform data anonymization steps and require relevant vendors and their employees to submit non-disclosure agreements to ensure that employees and vendors meet high privacy standards. Learn more about Microsoft and voice data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2145715).
	
Preview release or free release
	
Microsoft offers free products and features, including previews, insiders, and betas ("Previews"). You can evaluate these and provide Microsoft with data about your product usage, such as feedback and data about your device or usage. As a result, previews may automatically collect more data than our general products and have different privacy and security measures than our typical products, such as poor management capabilities. If you participate in the preview, we may contact you with your feedback or whether you would like to continue using the product after the general release.
	
