Artificial Intelligence and Microsoft Copilot Features
	
Microsoft harnesses the power of artificial intelligence (AI) in many of its products and services, including the incorporation of generative AI capabilities such as the Microsoft Copilot feature. Microsoft's AI deployment and use are aligned with Microsoft's AI Principles (https://aka.ms/RAI) and Microsoft's Responsible AI Standards (https://aka.ms/RAIStandardPDF)The collection and use of personal data in the development and deployment of Microsoft's AI capabilities is consistent with the commitments outlined in this Privacy Statement. Product-specific details provide additional relevant information. Learn more about how Microsoft is using AI.
	
Microsoft Copilot features. Microsoft Copilot (https://www.microsoft.com/microsoft-copilot) is Microsoft's everyday AI assistant, designed to help you achieve more through a single experience that runs across different devices, understanding relevant context across the web, PC, and apps to deliver the right skills at the right time. With the help of Copilot, users can start drafting a new Word document, generate PowerPoint presentations when accessing Copilot in the M365 app, quickly find answers to complex search queries online, find related documents and other personal content from other tasks, and create new songs, You can get inspiration to create stories, images, and other content. Copilot is a family of services, and Microsoft's collection and use of data may vary depending on the service and the intended features in a particular scenario.
	
The Copilot website (https://copilot.microsoft.com/) and app (available on iOS and Android) are at the core of the consumer Copilot experience. Within this core experience, users can perform web search, create text, images, songs, or other outputs, and work with other features such as plugins. On websites and apps, users enter a "prompt" that provides instructions to Copilot (for example, "What are the recommended restaurants near me that can accommodate a gathering of 10 people"). To provide a relevant response, Copilot uses this prompt along with the user's location, language, and similar settings to create a helpful response. In some markets, authenticated users can choose to allow Copilot to access their previous prompt history to better customize the product. The Copilot for Consumer product uses the data collected to provide and improve the Copilot service, including providing relevant ads. Users signed in to their account can manage their prompt history in the product and the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard, and can adjust product location, language, and other settings, including additional privacy choices.
	
Copilot will also appear as an assistant for other Microsoft consumer products, such as Bing, Microsoft Edge, and Xbox. In these situations, data processing activities typically align with the primary use of those products. For more information about Copilot features in these products, see the Bing, Microsoft Edge, and Xbox sections of this privacy statement.
	
For example, Bing's Copilot's use and collection of personal data is consistent with Bing's core web search service offerings described in this Privacy Statement. For more information about Copilot in Bing, see Copilot in Bing. Committed to responsible AI (https://aka.ms/ResponsibleAI-NewBing). In Microsoft Edge, Copilot appears in the sidebar experience to help users complete tasks related to the webpage they visit (e.g., "Summarize this page"). This data will be used in conjunction with the Microsoft Edge section of this Privacy Statement.
	
Copilot Pro (https://www.microsoft.com/store/b/copilotpro) is another consumer Copilot offering, offering subscriber priority access to the latest models, improved image creation capabilities, and access to Copilot in Microsoft Word, PowerPoint, OneNote, Excel, and Outlook. The main Copilot Pro website and app have similar data collection, use, and control as Copilot for Consumer, as mentioned earlier. Similar Copilot features are also included in Microsoft 365 Family and Microsoft 365 Personal subscriptions. When Copilot is integrated with Microsoft 365 products, Copilot's data collection is consistent with how we collect and use data as described in the "Productivity and communication" section of this privacy statement.
	
There is also a Copilot offering designed for enterprise users. If enabled by an eligible company, users who log in using Entra ID to access the Copilot for Consumer service will receive Copilot with Commercial Data Protection. This ensures that data collection and use are minimal and aligned with enterprise user expectations. Learn more about Copilot with commercial data protection here (https://learn.microsoft.com/copilot/privacy-and-protections). 
	
Microsoft 365 Copilot, available in Microsoft 365 enterprise services, provides enterprise-level data protection, access to corporate graphs, Copilot within Microsoft 365 and Teams, and additional customization capabilities. The collection and use of data by Microsoft 365 Copilot is consistent with the practices described in the Enterprise and Developer Products section of this privacy statement.
	
Enterprise and developer products
	
Enterprise and developer products are Microsoft products and related software that are offered and designed primarily for use by organizations and developers. These include:
		
Cloud services mentioned as online services in the product agreement. These include Microsoft 365, Office 365, Microsoft Azure, Microsoft Dynamics 365, Microsoft Intune, and more. For these purposes, an agreement is entered into between your organization (our customers) and Microsoft for the Services ("Enterprise Online Services").
		
Other enterprise and developer tools and cloud-based services, such as Azure PlayFab Services (see Azure PlayFab Services Terms of Use (https://playfab.com/terms/) for more information).
		
Server, developer, and hybrid cloud products, including Windows Server, SQL Server, Visual Studio, System Center, Azure Stack, and open source software (e.g., Bot Framework solutions) ("Enterprise and Developer Software").
		
Appliances and hardware used in storage infrastructure, such as StorSimple ("Enterprise Appliances").
		
Specialized services mentioned in the product agreement that are available for Enterprise Online Services, including onboarding services, data migration services, data science services, and services that complement existing services in Enterprise Online Services.
	
In the event of any conflict between this Microsoft Privacy Statement and the terms and conditions between you and Microsoft for enterprise and developer products, the terms and conditions between you and Microsoft will control.
	
Please also refer to the product documentation for more information about the features and settings of our enterprise and developer products, including choices that affect your privacy and the privacy of your end users.
	
If the following terms and conditions are not defined in the Privacy Statement or the Product Terms of Use (https://www.microsoft.com/licensing/product-licensing/products#OST), the following definitions will apply.
	
In general. When you try, purchase, use, or subscribe to enterprise and developer products, or receive support or professional services for such products, Microsoft receives data from you and collects and generates data. This personal data is used to provide services (including improving, protecting, and updating services), to conduct our business operations, and to communicate with you. Here are some examples:
		
When you contact a Microsoft sales representative, we collect your name, contact data, and information about your organization as the basis for that consultation.
		 
When you contact a Microsoft support representative, we collect device and usage data and error reports to diagnose and resolve issues.
		
When you pay for a product, we collect contact and payment data to process payment.
		
When Microsoft sends you a notice, we use the data to tailor the content of the notice to you.
		
When you interact with Microsoft about professional services, we collect the name and data of the contact you designate and use the information you provide to provide you with the services you request.
	
Enterprise and developer products allow you to purchase, subscribe, and use other Microsoft or third-party products and online services that have different privacy practices. These other products and online services are subject to their respective privacy statements and policies.
	
Enterprise Online Services
	
To provide enterprise online services, Microsoft uses data provided by Microsoft uses users (including customer data, personal data, administrator data, payment data, and support data) and data that Microsoft collects and generates in connection with your use of enterprise online services. We process data as described in the Product Terms of Use (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=873404), the Microsoft Products and Services Data Protection Supplement (Product and Services DPA), (https://aka.ms/dpa) and the Microsoft Trust Center (https://www.microsoft.com/trustcenter/privacy/how-Microsoft-defines-customer-data).
	
Personal Data. The customer is the controller of personal data, and Microsoft processes such data. This is an exception where (a) you process your personal data and Microsoft does secondary processing, or (b) as described in other standard Product and Services DPAs (https://aka.ms/dpa). In addition, as described in the standard Product and Services DPA (https://aka.ms/dpa), Microsoft assumes additional responsibilities as a data controller under the GDPR when processing personal data in connection with the provision of services to Microsoft's corporate customers for the purposes of legitimate business operations. These include invoice and account management, remediation, internal reporting and business modeling, and financial reporting. Personal data is used in the most difficult way to identify an individual, while supporting the processing necessary for business operations. Personal data is aggregated by using statistical data and pseudonymized before using it for business operations. This makes it impossible to identify the individual.
	
Admin data. Admin data is information that you provide to Microsoft when you sign up, purchase, or manage enterprise online services. We use Admin Data to provide enterprise online services, perform transactions, service accounts, detect and prevent fraud, and comply with legal responsibilities. Admin data includes the name, address, phone number, and email address provided by the user, as well as aggregated usage data associated with the account, such as selected controls. If you agree to provide Microsoft with your colleagues and friends for the sole purpose of sending them invitations to use Enterprise Online Services, that information will be included in your Admin Data. When we contact these people, we will include information such as your name and profile picture.
	
We may use Admin Data to inform you about your account, subscription, billing, and renewals for Enterprise Online Services, such as new features, security, or other technical issues, as appropriate. As set forth in the terms of the Agreement, we will also contact you for third-party inquiries regarding your use of the Enterprise Online Services. You cannot stop contacting us for non-promotional purposes. We may contact you about information and offers for other products and services, and we may share your contact information with Microsoft partners. If the services and solutions provided by these partners meet your needs or optimize your use of enterprise online services, limited aggregate information about your organization's account may be shared with the partner. Microsoft will not share sensitive or contact information with authorized partners unless you have sufficient permissions. You can manage your contact settings and update your information within your account profile.
	
Payment data. We use payment data to perform transactions and detect and prevent fraud.
	
Supporting data. When you receive technical support for Enterprise Online Services, you provide data or authorize Microsoft to collect data. We process the support data to provide the support team as described in the Product and Service DPA (https://aka.ms/dpa).
	
Local software and diagnostic data. Some enterprise online services require the installation of local software (such as agents and device management applications) or are enhanced by installing local software. Local software may collect diagnostic data about the use and performance of that software (Product and Service DPA (https://aka.ms/dpa)). That data may be sent to Microsoft and used for the purposes described in the Products and Services DPA (https://aka.ms/dpa).
	
Bing Search Service data. The Bing search service, as defined in the Product Agreement, uses data such as search queries as described in the "Bing (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainbingmodule)" section of this Privacy Statement.
	
Enterprise and developer software and enterprise appliances
	
Enterprise and developer software and enterprise appliances collect data to operate efficiently and provide the best experience. The data collected depends on the features you use and your configuration and settings, but is generally limited to device data and usage data. You can choose the information you provide to us. Here are some examples of the data we collect:
		
When installing or upgrading enterprise and developer software, we may collect device data and usage data to ensure that you do not encounter any issues.
		
When you use enterprise software or enterprise appliances, we may collect device data and usage data to obtain information about your operating environment and improve security features.
		
If a crash occurs while using enterprise software or enterprise appliances, you can send us an error report to help Microsoft diagnose the problem and provide customer support.
	
Microsoft uses the data we collect from enterprise and developer software and enterprise appliances to provide and improve the quality of our products, provide customer support, activate our products, communicate with you, and perform our business.
	
Microsoft SQL Server is a relational database management platform that includes products that can be installed on their own, such as SQL Server Management Studio. For more information about the types of data collected by Microsoft and how to manage your privacy options, visit the SQL Server Privacy page (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=868444). In your organization, administrators can specify the appropriate usage statistics settings in SQL Server through Group Policy.
	
HoloLens。 HoloLens headsets are standalone Windows computers with Wi-Fi connectivity that enable mixed reality experiences with apps and solutions. Microsoft collects diagnostic data and uses it to troubleshoot issues and keep Windows running on HoloLens up to date, secure, and working properly. Diagnostic data also helps us improve HoloLens and related Microsoft products and services, depending on the diagnostic data settings you choose for your device. Learn more about Windows diagnostic data (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#maindiagnosticsmodule).
	
HoloLens also processes and collects data related to the HoloLens experience and device, including cameras, microphones, and infrared sensors. These devices enable movement and voice navigation.
		
You can also use your camera to choose to sign in automatically with iris authentication. To do this, HoloLens takes an image of the iris, measures the distance between key points, generates an individual, and stores it. This information is stored on HoloLens and is not visible to anyone, and users can delete this data from HoloLens at any time.
		
HoloLens also detects hand movements to perform system interactions (menu movements, panning/zooming, scrolling, etc.). This data is processed on the HoloLens device and is not stored.
	
HoloLens derives tracking points based on the user's environment to understand the surface in space. Users can place digital assets on top of it. There are no images associated with this environment data, and they are stored locally on the HoloLens device. You can delete this data from your HoloLens at any time.
	
Use voice commands on the headset's microphone to navigate, control apps, enter search terms, and more. Learn more about voice data collection (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainspeechinkingtypingmodule).
	
Productivity and Communication Products
	
Productivity and communication products are applications, software, and services that can be used to create, store, and share documents, as well as communicate with others.
	
Microsoft 365, Office, and other productivity apps
	
The previous version of Microsoft 365, called Office 365, is a collection of subscription productivity services and applications, including Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Outlook, and OneNote. Office is a one-time purchase version of these applications available for PC or Mac and includes Access and Publisher. Both Microsoft 365 and Office consist of client software applications and connected online services (web apps in the case of Microsoft 365 for the web), which span many platforms and have a large number of interdependent experiences. For more information about Outlook, see the Outlook (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainoutlookmodule) section of this privacy statement.
	
Use it to design and recommend file content across a variety of cloud-based Microsoft 365 services, collaborate with others in documents, and take advantage of the capabilities of other Microsoft products and third-party connected products, such as Bing. In your organization, administrators can disable these connected services. You can access privacy controls within Microsoft 365 and Office apps. For more information, see Account privacy settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2086538).
	
Office roaming service. The Office Roaming Service helps keep settings up to date, such as privacy settings, across devices running Microsoft 365 or Office apps. When you sign in to an app using a Microsoft account or an account issued by your organization, the service syncs some of your customized settings to Microsoft servers. For example, the service synchronizes a list of recently used documents and the last seen location in the document. When you sign in to another device with the same account, the Office roaming service downloads settings from Microsoft servers and applies them to additional devices. When you sign out of the app, the service removes the settings from your device. Any changes you make to your customized settings will be sent to Microsoft servers.
	
Updates from Microsoft. Microsoft uses services such as Click-to-Run, Microsoft AutoUpdate (for Mac), or Microsoft Update (for some versions of Office) to provide security and other important updates.
	
These services can automatically detect the availability of online updates for Microsoft 365 or Office apps on your device and automatically download and install them.
	
Diagnostic data. Diagnostic data is used to (i) keep Microsoft 365 or Office apps secure and up-to-date; (ii) detect, diagnose, and repair problems; (iii) Product Improvements. This data does not include the user's name or email address, the contents of the user's files, or information about apps that are not related to Microsoft 365 or Office. Users can select "Required" or "Optional" as the level of diagnostic data collection.

must. The minimum data required to keep the app safe and up-to-date and work as expected on the device on which the app is installed.

Options. Collect additional data to help you enhance your product and detect, diagnose, and remediate issues.
	
For more information, see Diagnostic data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2083611).
	
Connected experience. Microsoft 365 will continue to provide even more experiences with client applications that are connected to and supported by cloud-based services. A subset of these connected experiences are also available in Office. If you choose to use Connected Experiences, we collect service data that is necessary to keep these Connected Experiences reliable, up-to-date, secure, and functioning properly. For more information about the required service data, see:
	
Working with others on documents stored in OneDrive or translating the content of a Word document into another language are examples of connected experiences. There are two types of connected experiences:

Experience analyzing content. An experience that uses file content to provide design recommendations, editing suggestions, data insights, and similar functionality. Examples include PowerPoint designers and Word editors.

Experience downloading online content. Experience searching and downloading online content such as templates, images, 3D models, videos, and reference materials to enhance your documents. Templates and PowerPoint Quick Starters are examples.
	
You can access privacy controls within Microsoft 365 and Office client apps. These privacy settings allow you to configure your connected experience. For example, you can enable the Connected Experience to download online content and disable the Connected Experience to analyze the content. Disabling the connected experience also disables other experiences, such as document collaboration and online file storage. However, if you use this privacy setting to disable the connected experience, you will still be able to use certain features, such as mailbox syncing in Outlook and the important services described below. If you're using Microsoft 365 for the web, you can't use these controls because you're already connected to the cloud. For more information about accessing these controls, see Set account privacy (https://support.microsoft.com/office/3e7bc183-bf52-4fd0-8e6b-78978f7f121b).
	
If you disable a specific type of connected experience, the ribbon or menu command corresponding to that connected experience will be grayed out, or an error message will be displayed when you try to use that connected experience.
	
Critical Services. There is a set of services that are essential to the functionality of Microsoft 365 and Office and cannot be disabled. For example, a licensing service that ensures that you have the right licenses to use Microsoft 365 is important. The required service data for these services is collected and sent to Microsoft, regardless of any other settings configured by the user. For more information, see Critical services (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2086224).
	
Required service data for the connected experience. When you use a connected environment, your data is sent to Microsoft for processing and providing connectivity capabilities. This data is needed because this information allows you to achieve such a cloud-based connected environment. This data is mandatory as service data.
	
The required service data can include information related to the operation of the connected environment required to maintain the security of the underlying services and keep them up to date. When you use a connected experience that analyzes content, for example, when using the Translate feature in Word, the text that is typed or selected for translation is sent and processed to provide a connected experience. Texts and translations are not stored by our service. The required service data can also include information that connected experiences need to perform their tasks, such as configuration information about Microsoft 365 or Office apps.
	
For more information, see Required service data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2086313).
	
Copilot and Copilot Pro in Microsoft 365. Copilot features that appear in Microsoft 365 apps as part of a Microsoft 365 Personal, Microsoft 365 Family, or Copilot Pro subscription are available as a separate subscription service in select countries. This feature provides AI-powered productivity features through real-time conversational experiences by applying large language model (LLM) processing to content provided in Microsoft 365 apps such as Word, Excel, OneNote, Outlook, and PowerPoint. Copilot and Copilot Pro in Microsoft 365 are not available with Office desktop licenses. When used in an available Microsoft 365 app, Copilot will only use the content in the file when it asks you to take a specific action on that specific content. For example, you might ask Copilot to help you rewrite a paragraph in a Word document, or you might ask Copilot to generate a to-do list from a notebook in OneNote. As with connected experiences, essential service data is collected while using Copilot. This includes information related to the security, up-to-date, and operations required to keep the underlying services operating as expected.
	 
Copilot Pro: For more information, see Microsoft 365 apps and privacy (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink?linkid=2258434) and frequently asked questions about Copilot for Microsoft 365 Family and Personal subscriptions (https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/frequently-asked-questions-about-copilot-in-microsoft-365-family-and-personal-subscriptions-bda0d6e8-346d-41ce-ab1e-f6af6229c462).
	
Other productivity apps. Microsoft offers some productivity apps that are separate from Microsoft 365 and Office, such as Whiteboard (a free-form digital canvas with touch, type, and pen), To Do (a cloud-based task management app), and Sticky Notes (a desktop notes app).
	
The app uses a variety of cloud-based services to provide other Microsoft product features, such as providing images from Bing for Whiteboard, suggesting task suggestions to add to today's to-do events, and leveraging Outlook and Sticky Notes integration.
	
Use of device features. Some Microsoft 365 applications use specific features to leverage device capabilities. PowerPoint allows you to record presentations with audio and video by accessing your device's microphone and camera with the presentation recording feature. The device's microphone can also be accessed using the speaker coach from the audio recording feature. During the conversation, the speaker coach will provide on-screen guidance regarding pacing, inclusive language, use of profanity, fillers, and even whether or not you are reading the text on the slides. When creating a PowerPoint presentation, you can also use the screenshot and screen cutout feature to capture the content of your screen. Some Microsoft 365 applications, PowerPoint, Word, and OneNote, provide dictation for connected experiences that allow you to create content while using a microphone using speech-to-text. Word and OneNote use a microphone in a connected transcription experience, or use voice audio recording to convert audio recorded directly into a text transcript separated by each speaker. OneNote allows you to use your camera to insert photos and record videos. To Do, Whiteboard, and all Microsoft 365 apps have a sharing feature that accesses your contacts, allowing you to share documents with others in your contact list. The application will not access the features of your device until you start using this feature.
	
You can manage your microphone and camera access settings in the Windows Privacy Settings menu. Go to Start > Settings > Privacy or Privacy & Security. For more information about how to control privacy settings in your app, see What Windows privacy settings apps use (https://support.microsoft.com/windows/windows-privacy-settings-that-apps-use-8b7f2cf4-c359-bf99-0f69-2123cc9ddfc1).
	
Microsoft family
	
This section applies to Microsoft Family Safety M365 products, where family groups can connect via the Microsoft Family Safety app on Windows, Xbox, or mobile devices. If you choose to create or join a family group, review the information in Microsoft Family Safety (https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/account-billing/microsoft-family-safety-bb97220e-9dd8-4b4a-9d15-8194d5941dc5) carefully.
	
Microsoft Family Safety helps parents create a safe environment for family groups with digital content filtering, screen time limits, Microsoft and Xbox Store spending, age rating settings for apps and games, and location sharing. For information about how Microsoft collects and uses your child's data, see the Collection of data from your children (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#maincollectionofdatafromchildrenmodule)section of the Privacy Statement. If you are using Microsoft Family Safety on Windows, see the Windows See the Security and Safety Features section (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainsecurityandsafetyfeaturesmodule) for additional information.
	
To enable Family Safety Controls on your child's account, your child's account must be part of a family group. Accounts that require parental consent to create are automatically included as part of a family group of individuals who have consented to create a child's account. For accounts that don't require parental consent to create, the parent or guardian must add the account to the family group to use Family Safety Controls.
	
When you enable your child's Family Activity Report, Microsoft collects details about your child's device usage, including search, web, app, and gaming activity, and provides you with a report of their child's online activity. Activity reports are periodically deleted from Microsoft servers.
	
Certain Family Safety features, such as Location Sharing, Drive Safety, Drive Sharing, Location, and Location Notifications, use your location when enabled. For example, when you enable location sharing, your device uploads your location data to the cloud and shares it with other users in your family group. Microsoft will only keep the last known location as part of the location-sharing feature (each new location replaces the previous location). When you enable Drive Safety, your location is used to record your driving habits, such as whether you are driving within driving limits, whether you are using your phone while driving, and whether you have accelerated or braked suddenly. These reports are uploaded to the cloud, and you can choose to share the Drive reports with family groups. You can turn off these location features at any time in Family Safety settings. You can manage your device's location data in the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard. Learn more about Family Safety and location data (https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/account-billing/location-based-experiences-in-microsoft-family-safety-48704c11-da47-05c3-6c75-e032d54bc563).
	
Microsoft Launcher
	
Microsoft Launcher is an Android app that provides a highly customizable app launcher experience on Android devices.
	
You can use Microsoft Launcher with a personal or work account, or without an account. However, if you don't grant specific permissions, some features may be restricted.
	
To use Microsoft Launcher, you need to install the application on your Android device, and you need optional permissions to enable the following features:
	
Microsoft Copilot。 Once signed in with your personal Microsoft account, you can seamlessly use Copilot features such as chat, web search, voice search, and Image Search. Some Copilot features require access to device features, such as the device's camera, microphone, photos, and videos. For more information, check out our section on AI and Copilot features. Learn more about Copilot's terms of service here (https://www.bing.com/new/termsofuse). 
	
Grance View Feed. Glens View helps you organize your daily activities, such as Outlook calendars, to-do lists, sticky notes, and recent documents in the M365 app. When you sign in with a personal or work account, your data is synced across devices signed in to the same account and is available in a personalized experience. You can also see recent activity, such as recent photos and app usage, but you'll need permission to access your device's photos, files, and app usage data.
	
News Feed. When you sign in with your Microsoft account, you can get personalized news feeds and ads in the Launcher news feed. This is synchronized across all your devices. You can also give Microsoft Launcher permissions to access your location to receive locally curated news. You can use the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard to manage your ad preferences and customize your experience.
	
Weather Notifications. Microsoft Launcher uses MSN Weather to receive the latest and most important weather changes on your home screen. You can allow the Launcher to access your current location or provide your zip code to receive the latest local weather information.
	
Backup and Restore: Microsoft Launcher's backup and restore feature allows you to easily transfer between phones and experiment with different home screen settings. Backups can be stored directly on your device or in a OneDrive account associated with your Microsoft account, making them easily accessible.
	
Microsoft Launcher supports Android's work profile feature, allowing you to maintain a clear boundary between personal and work data on your device. This means you can securely access workplace resources without mixing them with your personal apps or data.
	
Learn more about Microsoft Launcher and its supported features here (https://support.microsoft.com/topic/using-microsoft-launcher-on-android-c59f2824-0218-ae6d-3666-d93a7fc537e0).
	
Microsoft Teams
	
This section applies to Teams for consumers. If you're using Teams with a school or work account, see Enterprise and developer products (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainenterpriseservicesmodule) in this privacy statement.
	 
Teams is an all-in-one collaboration and communication hub. With Teams, you can stay connected with your peers over any period of time. In Teams, you can make use of voice and video calls to call your contacts. Teams makes it easy to find your friends, files, photos, conversations, tasks, and calendars in one convenient and secure place. Teams allows you to store sensitive information such as passwords, reward numbers, and login information and share them with others in Teams. You can also share your location with friends and family with permissions.
	
As part of providing these features, Microsoft collects data about the use of features and information about the time and users associated with communications. Microsoft may share this information with enterprise users when they interact with end users using school or work accounts through meetings and chats. For example, if you have a Teams chat with a user who uses Teams associated with your school account, Microsoft may share information with that user's school as part of providing the Teams service.
	 
Search for your Teams contacts. Your Teams profile contains the information you provided when you set up your Microsoft account. To help others find you in Teams (or products that work with your personal Teams, including Teams for Enterprise), your Teams profile may be included in the Teams public search directory and appear in Teams. Depending on your settings, Teams users can search for you by your name, email address, and phone number. Your profile includes your username, avatar, and any other data you choose to add to your profile or show to others. When you interact with end users in your organization in chats and meetings, enterprise users and their end users may see a Teams profile.
	 
Teams contacts. With permission, Teams periodically syncs your device with Outlook contacts and checks for other team users who match your contacts on your device or in your Outlook address book. You can always manage your contacts and stop syncing at any time. If you choose to stop syncing your devices or Outlook contacts, or if your device is inactive, any contacts that didn't match during the sync process will be removed from Teams. If you want to invite someone you know on your device or Outlook to a conversation, you can invite them directly on a one-on-one basis, or Microsoft can send you an invitation to a group conversation via SMS or email on your behalf. Users who do not want to receive messages can be blocked. You can also report the issue to Microsoft.
	
Notifications to non-user contacts. If the device or Outlook contact you choose to sync with your Teams contacts, the Teams user's device, or the Outlook address book, displays information, Microsoft may process the data to determine if the user is currently in Teams. Allow users and Teams users to invite to the service via SMS, email, and more. As long as the Teams user is active in Teams on their device and continues to enable contact syncing with the applicable device or service, your information will be stored on Microsoft's servers, and Microsoft will periodically process your information as part of the contact sync experience for Teams users, and you will subsequently use the Check if you have participated.
	
Learn more about how we handle your information in connection with the contact sync feature provided to Teams users (https://support.microsoft.com/topic/cdf3c478-df79-4efe-8c4b-8202078a1a67).
	
If you choose to join Teams, you will appear as a new Teams contact for a Teams user with information on your device or in your Outlook address book. As a Teams user, if you don't want to receive communications from other Teams users, you can block them. In addition, you can report your concerns to Microsoft.
	
Third-party contacts. You can also choose to sync contacts from third-party providers. If you choose to unsync third-party contacts in Teams, all third-party contacts will be removed from Teams. If you agree to use these third-party contacts in other Microsoft apps and services, these contacts will continue to be available in other Microsoft apps and services.
	
You can remove third-party contacts from all Microsoft apps and services by removing third-party accounts from Teams. Keep in mind that removing a third-party account from Teams may affect your experience with other Microsoft apps and services that use that third-party account.
	 
Teams calendar. You can also choose to sync your Teams calendar with your third-party provider's calendar. You can stop syncing your Teams calendar at any time by removing a third-party account from Teams. If you have consented to the use of third-party data in other Microsoft apps and services, please note that deleting this third-party account data in Teams may affect your experience in other Microsoft apps and services.
	
Location sharing. You can share a fixed or dynamic location with a user or group in Teams. This is controllable and can be stopped at any time. You can get parental consent or share your child's location with a Microsoft Family Group parent in a group.
	
Push notifications. To notify you of incoming calls, chats, and other messages, Teams uses the notification service on your device. On many devices, such services are provided by other companies. For example, in order to let users know who is calling or to show the first few characters of a new chat, Teams must tell the notification service to provide a notification to the user. This information will be used by the company providing the device's notification service in accordance with its own terms and privacy policies. Microsoft is not responsible for the personal data collected by the provider of the notification service.
	
If you don't want to use the notification service for incoming Teams calls and messages, disable the notification service in your device's settings.
	
Chat and conferencing with end users of enterprise users. Many Microsoft products are intended for use by organizations, such as schools and businesses, as well as individual users. If you use Teams with a work or school account, see the Enterprise and developer products section (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainenterprisedeveloperproductsmodule) of this privacy statement See When you participate in a Teams meeting or chat with your organization's end users, the data you share with your end users is subject to your organization's policies, if any. Privacy inquiries related to data shared through chats and meetings with your organization's end users, including requests to enforce data protection rights, should be directed to your organization's administrator. Microsoft is not responsible for your privacy or security practices, which may differ from those set forth in this Statement.
	
OneDrive
	
OneDrive allows you to store and access your files on virtually any device. You can also share files and collaborate with others. Depending on the version of the OneDrive application, users may be able to sign in and access both OneDrive for personal and business purposes. Sign in with a personal Microsoft account for personal use, or with a work or school account to use Microsoft 365 or Office 365 for business.
	
When you use OneDrive, we collect data about your use of the service, not just the content you store, to provide, improve, and protect the service. For example, the content of OneDrive documents may be indexed so that users can search for it later, or location may be used to search for photos based on where they were taken. We may also collect device information to provide you with a personalized experience, such as syncing content across multiple devices or roaming through customized settings.
	
When a user saves content to OneDrive, the sharing permissions in the folder where the content is located are carried over. For example, if you save content in a public folder, it will be public and visible to anyone who can view that folder on the internet. When you save content in a private folder, it becomes private.
	
When you share content from a device synced with your OneDrive account to a social network, such as Facebook, the content is uploaded to that social network or a link to the content is posted to the social network. This allows you to access your content from everyone on the social network. To remove content, you need to remove it from social networks (if it was actually uploaded, not a link post) and OneDrive.
	
If you share OneDrive content with a friend via a link, they'll receive an email with the link. The link contains an authorization code, so anyone with the link can access the user's content. When a user's friend sends a link to someone else, they can access your content even if they don't choose to share it with others. To revoke permission for content in OneDrive, sign in to your account and select the specific content for which you want to manage permission levels. To effectively disable a link, revoke permission for the link. Unless the user sets up to share the link again, they cannot use a link that allows them to access the content.
	
Files managed in OneDrive for Business are stored separately from files stored in Personal OneDrive. OneDrive for Business collects personal data for authentication, such as email addresses and passwords, and transfers them to Microsoft and providers of Microsoft 365 or Office 365 services.
	
Outlook
	
Outlook is a product designed to improve communication and productivity, and includes Outlook.com, Outlook applications, and related services.
	Outlook.com。 Outlook.com is Microsoft's flagship consumer email service that includes email accounts with addresses ending in outlook.com, live.com, hotmail.com, and msn.com. Outlook.com has the ability to connect friends with each other on social networks. You must create a Microsoft account to take advantage of Outlook.com.
	
When you delete a message or item from a mailbox in Outlook.com, the item is typically moved to the Deleted folder and stored in the Deleted folder for approximately 7 days unless you return it to your inbox, or unless you empty the folder or the service automatically empties the folder (from the date of the first of these actions). When the Deleted Items folder is empty, the deleted items remain in the system for up to 30 days before they are eventually deleted (unless you are legally required to keep that data for a longer period of time).
	
Outlook application. The Outlook client application is software that you can install on your device to manage mail, calendar items, files, contacts, and other data on mail, file storage, other services (such as Exchange Online and Outlook.com), and servers (such as Microsoft Exchange). Outlook applications, including the new Outlook for Windows app, allow you to use multiple accounts from different providers, including third-party providers.
	
To add an account, you must grant Outlook permissions to access data from your email and file storage services.
	
When you add an account to Outlook, the email, calendar items, files, contacts, settings, and other data in that account automatically sync with your device. If you're using the Outlook mobile application, your data will also be synced with Microsoft servers, and even more features will be available. For example, you can do fast search, filter less important emails with personalized settings, and add email attachments from linked file storage providers without leaving the Outlook application. If you're using the Outlook desktop application, you can choose whether to sync your data with our servers. You can delete your account at any time, and you can change the data you sync with your account at any time.
	
If you're adding an account provided by an organization, such as a company or school, the owner of your organization's domain may implement policies and controls (for example, requiring multi-factor authentication or the ability to remotely wipe device data), which may affect how you use Outlook.
	
Use of device features. For Outlook clients that support this feature, users can use the dictation feature to dictate and send the content of an email. The dictation feature can be configured to use the device's microphone or any other microphone that the user can connect to the device, such as a pair of microphone-enabled headphones. Outlook can also use your device's location to provide weather information for your current location or to search for nearby locations.
	
For more information about the data that the Outlook application collects and processes, see the Microsoft 365 (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainofficeservicesmodule) section of this privacy statement.
	
You can use Skype Dialpad to make and receive calls to landline and mobile numbers. This section describes the consumer version of Skype. If you're using Skype for Business, see the Enterprise and developer products (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainenterpriseservicesmodule) section of this privacy statement.
	
To provide these features, Microsoft collects usage data about your communications, such as the date and time of your communication, and the number and username that are part of your communication.
	
Compatible with Teams. Skype users can also use their Skype account to sign in to Teams. If you use your Skype credentials to log in to Teams, you can use Teams to chat and call other Teams users, and you can access your Skype missed calls and chat history through Teams. For more information about Teams, see the Microsoft Teams section (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainteamsmodule) of this privacy statement. 
	
Emergency calls from Skype dial pads in the United States. When you enable location sharing for emergency calls, your location is collected periodically so that Microsoft can share your location with your emergency service provider if you dial 911. Your location will only be shared if you initiate a 911 call with location sharing enabled for emergency calls.
	
Partner companies. We have partnered with other companies to allow Skype to be provided through their services. If you use Skype through a company other than Microsoft, the company's privacy policy will govern your handling of your personal data. We may access, transfer, disclose, and retain your data to comply with applicable laws, respond to valid legal process, or assist our partners and local businesses in complying with laws and legal process. Such data includes private content, such as stored video messages, voicemails, file transfers, and instant message content.

Skype Manager。 With Skype Manager, you can manage Skype usage for your group (such as a family) in one place. As a Skype Manager administrator, users who have set up a group can view usage patterns (traffic data, purchase details, and so on) of members in the group who have consented to access their information. The information you add, such as your name, can be viewed by other users in that group. Members of the group can revoke their consent to Skype Manager by visiting the Skype account page (https://login.skype.com/login).
	
Surface
	
Microsoft offers a great computing experience with its family of Surface devices and accessories, including browsing the web, watching and streaming videos, playing games, and running apps like Excel, Word, and OneNote. This includes devices and accessories such as Surface Laptop, Surface Studio, Surface Book, Surface Pro, Surface Headphones, Surface Earbuds, Surface Dock, and Surface Keyboard. As part of that experience, Microsoft collects certain diagnostic data that is described below.
	
Diagnostic data. Microsoft collects diagnostic data when you use Surface devices, Surface accessories, and Surface apps. Diagnostic data may include information about your Surface product crashes, performance, and usage. The data sent to Microsoft is used to ensure that your Surface remains secure and up-to-date, while still behaving properly and allowing you to further improve your Surface.

There are two levels of diagnostic and activity data: required diagnostic data and optional diagnostic data.

Required diagnostic data is the minimum amount of data required to secure, keep your Surface devices, Surface accessories, and Surface apps up to date and work as expected.

Optional diagnostic data is additional diagnostic and usage data for Surface devices, Surface accessories, and Surface apps. If you choose to send optional diagnostic data to Microsoft, it will also include required diagnostic data.
	
Mandatory diagnostic data is always sent to Microsoft for all Surface devices, Surface accessories, and Surface applications. However, you can choose whether to allow Surface to collect optional diagnostic data and send it to Microsoft. You can make that choice when you set up your Surface device for the first time or when you change settings from the Surface app without a timed one.
	
For more information, see Diagnostic data for Surface products (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2260527) and Surface app diagnostic data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2260527). For a list of required diagnostic data for Surface that has been collected, see Required diagnostic data for Surface products (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2260162).

Surface Duo
	
Surface Duo is a device that fits in your pocket and helps you be more productive on the go. Powered by the Google Android operating system, Surface Duo supports cellular data and Wi-Fi connections, so you can use it for email, internet browsing, gaming, and business connections.
	
Microsoft provides key features for the Surface Duo, running the Android operating system. Key features of Surface Duo include apps like Microsoft Launcher, setup wizard, and phone sync management app. You can sign in with your Google ID to enable various Google services. You can also sign in with your Microsoft account (MSA) to enable Microsoft services. Microsoft apps and services may rely on information provided by Google. Some features, such as location, require Google to enable this feature so that Microsoft can take advantage of this information.
	
Diagnostic data. Surface Duo collects diagnostic data and uses it to troubleshoot issues and keep key Surface Duo features up to date, secure, and working properly. This data also helps us improve Surface Duo and related Microsoft products and services. This data does not include usernames, email addresses, or file contents. Diagnostic data includes the required diagnostic data and optional diagnostic data.

must. Collect the minimum amount of data needed to keep your Surface Duo's key features secure, up-to-date, and work correctly.

Options. Collecting additional data helps us improve and enhance our products and help us detect, diagnose, and remediate issues.
	
Learn more about privacy settings on Surface Duo (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2127938).
	
Set your Surface Duo location. Surface Duo relies on Google's location services to determine the geographic location of your device to display weather forecasts for your location. Surface Duo's location can be located with different accuracy and can be strictly determined. To allow Microsoft apps to see or display weather forecasts and other location-related information, you need to enable Google's location services and Microsoft's location access. Some apps may need to enable these settings on a per-app basis, which you can set or change on your Surface Duo. The Google Privacy Policy (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2130411) provides details about Google's location services and related data privacy features. For more information, see Surface Duo location settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2128004) .
	
Microsoft apps included with Surface Duo. The diagnostic data option, a key feature of Surface Duo, is configured to be changed in Surface Duo settings in the Diagnostic data section when you first set up your Surface Duo.
	
Other Microsoft apps on Surface Duo may ask you to enable features that give you the full experience of the app. Or you may be asked to allow optional diagnostic data to be collected. You can change the settings for these apps under Surface Duo settings under the app name. For more information about these apps, please see the "Productivity and Communication Products" and "Search and Browse" sections of this Privacy Policy.

