Bing
	
Bing services include search and mapping services, as well as other apps and programs described in this section. Bing services collect and process data in various formats, including hand-typed or typed text, audio data, and images. Bing services are also included in other Microsoft services, such as Microsoft 365, some features of Windows (called Bing-provided operating environments).
	
When you perform a search or use a Bing-powered experience feature that involves performing a search or entering a command, Microsoft may use the search or command you specify (in the form of text, audio data, or images) to include your IP address, location, a unique identifier contained in cookies or similar technologies, the date and time of the search, Collect along with your browser configuration. For example, if you use Bing's speech-enabled services, your speech and performance data related to speech features will be sent to Microsoft. For more information about how Microsoft manages your speech data, see Speech recognition technology (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainspeechrecognitionmodule). Also, if you use Bing's image-enabled service, the images you use will be sent to Microsoft. When you use a Bing-powered experience (such as Bing Search) to search for a specific word or phrase in a web page or document, the context before and after is also sent to Bing along with that word or phrase to provide contextually relevant search results.
	
AI-enhanced Bing search. Bing Search includes AI-enhanced web search capabilities that use Bing's Microsoft Copilot. Support users by providing relevant search results, reviewing and summarizing from across the web, refining research queries through chat experiences, and improving creativity by helping users create content. Bing's Copilot's use and collection of personal data is consistent with Bing's core web search services, which are discussed in this section. For more information about Copilot in Bing, see Copilot in Bing. Committed to responsible AI (https://aka.ms/ResponsibleAI-NewBing).
	
Search suggestions. For search suggestions, Microsoft is sent the characters you type and click items in Bing-powered experiences (such as search suggestions and suggestions in the Microsoft Edge browser) to perform searches. This allows Microsoft to provide you with the right search suggestions based on the type of character you are searching for. To turn this feature on or off, go to Bing Settings (https://www.bing.com/account/general) when using Bing Search. There are other ways to control this feature in other Bing-powered experiences, such as the Microsoft Edge browser. You can't turn off the display of search suggestions in the search box in Windows 10 and Windows 11. You can always hide the search box or icon on the taskbar if you want.
	
Bing Experience Enhancement Program for Bing Desktop and Bing Toolbar。 If you use Bing Desktop or Bing Toolbar and participate in the Bing Experience Enhancement Program, we also collect information about how certain Bing applications are used, such as the address of the website you visit, to improve search rankings and relevance. For privacy reasons, we do not use the data collected by the Bing Experience Improvement Program to identify you, contact you, or target you with advertising. You can disable the Bing Experience Enhancement Program at any time through Bing desktop or Bing Toolbar settings. Finally, we delete the information we collect through the Bing Experience Improvement Program after 18 months.
	
Retention and anonymization. We anonymize stored search queries. To do so, IP addresses are permanently deleted after 6 months, and cookies and other inter-session identifiers used to identify specific accounts or devices are permanently deleted after 18 months.
	
Microsoft account personalization. Some Bing services offer an enhanced experience when you sign in to your personal Microsoft account. For example, you can sync your search history across multiple devices. You can use these personalization features to customize your interests and favorites and connect your account to third-party services. If you want to manage your personal settings, go to Bing Settings (https://www.bing.com/account/general) or if you want to manage your users' data, visit the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy).
	
Manage your search history. If you're signed in to your personal Microsoft account, go to the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy)You can clear your search history and chat history. The Bing Search History service in Bing Settings allows you to double-check the search criteria you enter and the results you click on in Bing Search using your browser. The service also allows you to clear the search history on your device. Conversations in Microsoft Copilot in Bing are also remembered as "recent activity." It saves a history of previous Recent Activity and gives the chat name based on the first query of the chat by default. While using the service, Recent Activity appears on the right side of the chat window. When you clear your history, you won't see it in your search or chat history, but it won't delete any information in your Microsoft search logs. This information is stored in an anonymized state or processed as specified in the Privacy Dashboard, as described above. If you're signed in to your work or school Microsoft account using Microsoft Search in Bing, you can export your Microsoft Search search history on Bing, but you can't delete it. As a service administrator for Microsoft Search in Bing, you can view aggregated search history across all enterprise users, but you can't view specific searches by user.
	
Third-party services that use Bing. Yahoo! When you use a third-party service such as Bing Equipment, you can access the experience. To provide these services, Bing receives search queries and related data from these partners, such as date and time, IP address, and unique identifiers. This data is sent to Microsoft to provide search services. Microsoft uses this data as described in this Statement or in a form further limited by our contractual obligations with our partners. If you have questions about the data collection and use practices of third-party services, please refer to the third-party services' privacy policies.
	
Data passed to the destination website. When you select a search result or ad on the Bing search results page and visit the desired website, the destination website receives the standard data that the user's browser sends to all the websites it navigates. For example, the user's IP address, browser type and language, and the hostname before the move (in this case, https://www.bing.com/).
	
Share data from Bing and Bing Device Experiences with third parties. Some of the anonymized data (non-user-identifiable data) of Bing and the Bing Equipment Experience will be shared with selected third parties. In this case, we will preemptively remove sensitive data that you include in your search criteria, such as your social security number or credit card number. In addition, Microsoft requires these third parties to keep their data secure and not use it for any purpose other than the purpose for which it was provided.
	
Microsoft Edge
	
Whenever you use a web browser to access the Internet, data about your device ("Standard Device Data") is sent to the websites you are visiting and to the online services you use. Standard device data includes the user's IP address, browser type, language, access time, and referring website address. This data is logged on to the web server of the website or online service. What data is logged on and how it is used depends on the privacy policy of the websites you visit and the web services you use. Certain features of Microsoft Edge, such as accessing Microsoft Start content and connecting the user's experience to content when opening a new tab in the browser, are covered by the "Microsoft Start" section of the Privacy Statement. In addition, Microsoft Edge sends a unique browser ID to specific websites so that Microsoft can develop aggregate data that we use to improve browser features and services.
	
Microsoft Edge for Windows, Linux, and MacOS. Microsoft Edge is the default web browser for Windows 10 and later, and is also available for other supported versions of Windows and macOS.
	
For example, data about how the user uses the browser, such as browsing history, web form data, temporary Internet files, and cookies, is stored on the user's device. Users can delete this data using Delete browsing history.
	
Microsoft Edge allows you to capture content such as and save it to your device:

Settings and more. You can manage your favorites, downloads, history, extension information, and collections.

collection. You can collect text, images, videos, and other content on your browser's notes page. When you drag content into a collection, it is cached on your device and can be removed from the collection.

Pin a website to the taskbar. You can pin your favorite websites to the Windows taskbar. Because websites can identify web pages that users have pinned, you can provide users with a notification badge to let them know that there is a new item to refer to on the website.
	
Microsoft collects the data necessary to provide you with the features you have requested in Microsoft Edge. When you sign in to Microsoft Edge using a Microsoft personal, work, or school account, Microsoft Edge syncs browser data stored on your device across other signed-in devices. You can choose which browser data you want to sync, such as favorites, browsing history, data related to extensions, settings, open tabs, autofill form entries (such as name, address, and phone number), passwords, payment information, and other types of data that become available. If you choose to sync extensions from third-party web stores, copies of these extensions are downloaded directly from the synced device's web store. If you turn on Password Monitor, your stored credentials are hashed, encrypted, and sent to Microsoft's Password Monitor service to alert you if credentials are detected as part of a malicious attack or breach. After the check is complete, this data is not retained by Microsoft. You can disable or configure sync in Microsoft Edge settings.
	
When you sign in to Microsoft Edge with a Microsoft personal, work, or school account, Microsoft Edge saves your account's privacy settings. Microsoft Edge uses saved preferences to transfer account privacy settings between signed-in devices, such as during Windows device setup or when you sign in to Microsoft Edge with that account on a new device.
	
Microsoft Edge search suggestions and suggestions use a user's search queries and browsing history to suggest faster browsing and more relevant search suggestions. Microsoft Edge sends the information entered in the browser address bar to the default search provider configured in the address bar, and when a character is typed, it will suggest a search. You can turn off these features at any time in your browser settings. To provide search results, Microsoft Edge sends search queries, standard device information, and location information (if location is enabled) to the default search provider. If Bing is your default search provider, we will use this data as described in the "Bing" section of this Statement.
	
Microsoft Edge collects and uses data from search activity across the web, including websites that are not owned or operated by Microsoft, to improve Microsoft services, such as Microsoft Edge, Microsoft Bing, and Microsoft News. This data may include your search queries, the search results you see, the demographic information that is part of the search results, and your interactions with those search results, such as the links you click. Microsoft Edge anonymizes the data it collects by deleting data that identifies the individual or device from which it was collected, and retains this data for one year after it is collected. Microsoft does not use this collected data to personalize or serve ads to customers. You can turn off the collection of this data at any time in your browser settings.
	
Microsoft Edge downloads content from Microsoft services to enhance your browsing experience. For example, you can make a pre-rendered site for immediate viewing if data is downloaded to the content, or provide the necessary content for the power functions you use, such as providing a template for a collection.
	
You can also share your Microsoft Edge browsing activity so that we can customize Microsoft Edge and Microsoft services, such as advertising, search, shopping, and news. Microsoft Edge browsing activity includes history, favorites, usage data, web content, and other browsing data. For more information about Microsoft's advertising privacy policy, see the "Ads" section of the privacy statement. In the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard, you can control the use of customized ad browsing activity in the "Show users interested ads" setting. If you disable this setting in the Microsoft Privacy Dashboard, you will continue to receive personalized web experiences, such as search and news, based on your browsing activity. Within Edge settings, "Allow Microsoft to use your browsing activity and other browsing data, such as history, favorites, and usage, to personalize Microsoft Edge and Microsoft services (such as ads, search, shopping, and news)" You can stop sharing your browsing activity in Microsoft Edge. When using the Copilot feature in the Microsoft Edge sidebar, you can choose to allow Copilot in Microsoft Edge to access the content of the webpage you're viewing to provide further insights, such as page overviews. The use of data connected to the Copilot experience is described in this privacy statement in the Bing section.
	
Microsoft Edge collects the diagnostic data you need to troubleshoot issues and keep Microsoft Edge up to date, secure, and working properly. The diagnostic data you need can also help you improve Microsoft Edge and Windows.
	
Apart from the search activity data mentioned above, you can send optional diagnostic data about how you use Microsoft Edge and information about your browser activity. This includes browsing history and search terms that help Microsoft improve Microsoft Edge and other Microsoft products and services. For Microsoft Edge on Windows 10 and later, this information appears when you enable optional diagnostic data. For more information, see the Windows Diagnostics section of the Privacy Statement. For Microsoft Edge for other operating systems, you can use the "Send data about browser usage to help us improve Microsoft products" or "Send us information about the websites you visit in Microsoft Edge to help you search and Microsoft Edge" in your browser settings. When you enable Help improve the product, optional diagnostic information is provided.
	
Diagnostic data collected by Microsoft Edge is sent to Microsoft and stored with one or more unique identifiers. These identifiers help identify individual browser installations on your device and help you understand browser service issues and usage patterns.
	
More information about Microsoft Edge, browsing data, and privacy (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2112165).
	
Microsoft Edge on iOS and Android. Microsoft Edge on iOS and Android devices collects the data needed to provide you with the features you have requested in Microsoft Edge. Microsoft also collects the diagnostic data you need to resolve issues and keep Microsoft Edge up to date, secure, and working properly. The diagnostic data you need will also help you improve Microsoft Edge.
	
In addition, we may share optional diagnostic data about how you use Microsoft Edge and information about the websites you visit (browsing history) for a personalized experience in your browser, Windows, and other Microsoft products and services. This information can also help us improve Microsoft Edge and other Microsoft products and services. This optional diagnostic data is sent to Microsoft if you enable "Share usage data for personal settings" or "Share information about websites you visit" in your browser settings.
	
Diagnostic data collected by Microsoft Edge is sent to Microsoft and stored with one or more unique identifiers. These identifiers allow you to identify individual users of your device and understand browser service issues and usage patterns.
	
Microsoft Edge collects and uses data from search activity across the web, including websites that are not owned or operated by Microsoft, to improve Microsoft services, such as Microsoft Edge, Microsoft Bing, and Microsoft News. The data collected by Microsoft Edge may include personal data. However, Microsoft Edge will take steps to scrub and anonymize your data. Microsoft Edge does not use this data to personalize or serve ads to you. You can turn off the collection of this data at any time in your browser settings. More information about search results data for product improvements (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2166676).
	
For more information about the privacy policy for legacy versions of Microsoft Edge (version 44 and earlier), see the Internet Explorer section of the Privacy Statement.
	
Microsoft Translator
	
Microsoft Translator is a machine translation system designed to automatically translate text and voice input across a multitude of supported languages. Microsoft Translator is available as a standalone consumer app for Android, iOS, and Windows. It is also integrated into various Microsoft products, including Translator Hub, Translator for Bing, and Translator for Microsoft Edge. Microsoft Translator processes data about your device and usage, along with text, image, and speech recognition data that you submit. We provide this data to Translator and use it to personalize the user experience and enhance our products. Microsoft has established business and technical methods for anonymizing data sent by users to Translator. For example, when randomly sampling text to enhance Translator and Microsoft's speech recognition technology, we remove identifiers or specific text (such as email addresses or sequences) in a sample that may contain personal data. For more information about how Microsoft manages your speech data, see Speech recognition technology (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainspeechrecognitionmodule).
	
Apart from Microsoft Translator, Microsoft's translation services are available as a feature within Microsoft products and services that have privacy policies that differ from Microsoft Translator. For more information about the Microsoft Azure Cognitive Services Translator Text API, Custom Translator, and Translator Speech API, see the Privacy Statement in Enterprise and Developer Products section. For information about the translation capabilities of Microsoft 365 apps, see the Productivity and communication products (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainprodcommproductsmodule)section of this privacy statement.

SwiftKey
	
Microsoft SwiftKey Keyboard and related cloud-based services (collectively, "SwiftKey Services") process data about the words you use and the way you type them, and use this data to understand your writing style to personalize auto-correction and predict text that is adapted to you. It also uses this data to provide various other features, such as emoji prediction.
	
SwiftKey's predictive technology learns how users use language to build a personalized language model. The model displays the words and phrases that users frequently use in that context in an optimized way, while also reflecting the user's unique writing style. The model itself contains words that users often type, sorted to allow predictions based on text already typed by SwiftKey's algorithms. This model uses data from all scenarios where you use the keyboard, such as typing while using an app or browsing a website. SwiftKey's keyboard and model attempt to avoid collecting sensitive data by not collecting data from specific fields that are recognized as containing password or payment data. Unless you have chosen to share your personal data with us (see below for more information), the SwiftKey Services do not record or store any data contained in your model. When you use the SwiftKey service, we also collect data about your device and usage. When you sign in to your SwiftKey account and agree to share the following data, we use anonymized device data, usage data, and model data to analyze the performance of the service and help us improve our products.
	
The SwiftKey service also includes an optional cloud component called a SwiftKey account. When a user creates a SwiftKey account, the language model syncs with the cloud service in the SwiftKey account, so the model is available on the different devices they use, as well as access services such as predictive synchronization, backup, and more. If you create a SwiftKey account, Microsoft will also collect your email address and basic demographic data. All collected data is transferred to our servers via encrypted channels. If you're signed in to your SwiftKey account, you can manage your personal data and SwiftKey account settings on data.swiftkey.com (https://data.swiftkey.com/).
	
As part of your SwiftKey account, you can also opt-in to sharing language and input data to improve Microsoft products and services. If you opt in, SwiftKey may send a short snippet of data about what and how you entered it, along with any associated correction data, to the server for processing. These text snippets are used in various automated processes to verify that the prediction service is functioning properly and to improve the product. To protect your privacy, the SwiftKey service ensures that you do not identify these text snippets. And even if you're using a SwiftKey account, these text snippets won't be linked.
	
If you sign in to your SwiftKey account and opt-in to sharing language and input data, Microsoft processes the shared language data to find new patterns in language usage across your user base. This allows you to improve the base model for individual languages. The language and input data used in this process are aggregated, and words or combinations of words that may belong to individuals or small groups are filtered out.
	
In SwiftKey settings, you can withdraw your consent to share language and input data for product improvement at any time. You can also revoke your consent to the storage of personal data in the SwiftKey Services in your SwiftKey settings. If you withdraw your consent for SwiftKey to store your personal data, all personal data collected through your use of the SwiftKey service will be deleted.
	
From time to time, notifications informing you of product updates and features that interest you may receive on your device. You can disable these notifications at any time in your SwiftKey settings.
	
When using the camera feature with SwiftKey, you can choose to use a third-party lens service to enhance your videos and images. Lenses are a feature that uses augmented reality (AR) to transform your selfies in fun ways, such as making them look like your favorite animals. The SwiftKey keyboard's camera allows you to transform your face or hands by selecting the built-in lens function on the keyboard. Depending on the lens you choose, videos and images may be processed to extract information about the location of different areas of the face or hands. The extracted data will be used solely for the purpose of applying AR effects to faces and hands. This data is not used to personally identify the user. This data is processed only during the session on the device and is deleted immediately thereafter. This data is not sent to SwiftKey or any third party.
	
Windows
	
Windows provides a customized computer environment. Users can seamlessly roam and access services, preferences, and content on their devices, from phones to tablets to Surface Hubs. The key components of Windows reside in the cloud, rather than as static software programs on the device, and the cloud and local elements of Windows are regularly updated to provide the latest improvements and features. To provide you with this computer experience, we collect data about you, your device, and how you use Windows. Windows is designed to be personal, so you can make choices about what personal information we collect and how we use that personal information. If a user's Windows device is managed by an organization to which the user belongs (such as work or school), that organization may use central management tools provided by Microsoft and others to access and process data, and to provide information about the device's settings (including privacy settings), device policies, software updates, and Microsoft or other characteristics of the user's device. In addition, organizations use management tools provided by Microsoft and others to access and process data from their devices, including interaction data, diagnostic data, and the contents of communications and files.
	
Windows Settings (formerly known as PC Settings) is an important component of Microsoft Windows. It provides a convenient interface for adjusting user settings, configuring the operating system, and managing connected devices, allowing you to manage user accounts, adjust network settings, and customize various aspects of Windows. Windows has mechanisms for apps to access various device features, such as the device's camera, microphone, location, calendar, contacts, call logs, and messages, to control access to personal data. Each feature has its own privacy settings page in Windows Settings, so you can control which apps can use each feature. Here are some of the key features of the settings:
		
1	Customization: You can customize various aspects of Windows, such as appearance, language settings, and privacy options. In Windows settings, you can customize Windows by using the microphone to control the volume, and the camera to use the integrated camera and location to change the brightness at night.
2	Manage peripherals: Install and manage peripherals such as printers, monitors, and external drives.
3	Network configuration: Adjust network settings such as Wi-Fi, Ethernet, cellular, and VPN connections, and use the physical MAC address, IMEI, and mobile number if your device supports cellular networks.
4	Manage Accounts: Add or remove user accounts, change account settings, and manage sign-in options.
5	System-level options: Configure display settings, notifications, power options, manage the list of installed apps, and more.
6	Privacy & Security Controls: Configure privacy settings, such as location, diagnostic data collection, and more. By turning it on or off, it fine-tunes individual apps and services to access your device's features.
	
For more information about data collection in Windows, see Overview of data collection in Windows (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=529552). This statement discusses Windows 10 and Windows 11, and references to Windows in this section are related to these product versions. Previous versions of Windows, including Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8, and Windows 8.1, have their own privacy statements.
	
Activation
	
When you activate Windows, a specific product key is associated with the device on which the software is installed. Data about product keys, software, and devices is sent to Microsoft and used to validate your software license. This data is retransmitted if the license needs to be reactivated or authenticated. On phones running Windows, device and network identifiers, as well as the device's initial power-on location, are sent to Microsoft for warranty registration, inventory replenishment, and fraud prevention.
	
Activity history
	
Activity history helps you record what you do on your device, such as what apps and services you use, what files you open, and what websites you visit. Your activity history is created when you use various apps and features, including Microsoft Edge classics, some Microsoft Store apps, and Microsoft 365 apps, and is stored locally on your device.
	
You can turn the setting to save your activity history locally on your device on or off. You can also clear your device's activity history at any time in the Windows Settings app under Privacy > Activity history. Learn more about your Windows activity history (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkId=865989).

Advertising Identifiers

Windows creates a unique advertising identifier for each user who uses the device. App developers and ad networks can use this advertising identifier for their own purposes, such as serving relevant ads in their apps. If the advertising identifier is enabled, both Microsoft apps and third-party apps can access and use the advertising identifier. This works in much the same way that websites access and use unique identifiers stored in cookies. App developers and ad networks can use ad identifiers to provide personalized experiences across the app and on the web, including showing users relevant ads. Microsoft collects advertising identifiers only for the purposes described herein if they are enabled by you as part of your privacy settings.
	
The advertising identifier setting applies to Windows apps that use the Windows advertising identifier. You can disable access to this identifier at any time by turning off Advertising Identifiers in the Windows Settings app. Re-enabling the old advertising identifier will be reset and a new one will be generated. If a third-party app accesses an advertising identifier, the app's use of the advertising identifier will be governed by the third party's own privacy policy. Learn more about Windows advertising identifiers (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=838419).

The advertising identifier setting does not apply to other methods of interest-based advertising served by Microsoft or third parties, such as cookies used to provide interest-based display advertising on websites. Third-party products that you access or install on Windows may also serve other forms of advertising based on interest, subject to their own privacy policies. Microsoft offers other forms of interest-based advertising on certain Microsoft products, either directly or in partnership with third-party advertising providers. For more information about Microsoft's use of data for advertising, please see the How we use your personal data (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainadvertisingmodule) section of this statement.
	
diagnosis
	
Microsoft collects Windows diagnostic data to help resolve issues and keep Windows up to date, secure, and working properly. It also helps improve Windows and related Microsoft products and services. While the device is running, diagnostic data is collected and sent to Microsoft periodically and stored with one or more unique identifiers. These identifiers help you recognize users and devices and understand device service issues and usage patterns.
	
There are two levels of diagnostic and activity data: required diagnostic data and optional diagnostic data. Certain product documentation and other documents may list the required diagnostic data as "Basic" diagnostic data and the optional diagnostic data as "Complete" diagnostic data.
	
If your organization (such as an employer or school) uses Microsoft Entra ID to manage the accounts you provide and to enroll your devices in a Windows diagnostic data processor configuration, Microsoft's processing of diagnostic data related to Windows is governed by the agreement between Microsoft and your organization. If your organization uses Microsoft's management tools or asks Microsoft to manage your devices, Microsoft and your organization will use diagnostic and error data from your devices to manage, monitor, and troubleshoot devices managed by your organization, and for other purposes of your organization.
	
Mandatory diagnostic data contains information about the device, its settings and features, and whether it is functioning properly. Mandatory diagnostic data will be collected, including:

Data on devices, connections, and configurations: 

Data about the device, such as processor type, OEM manufacturer, battery type and capacity, number and type of cameras, firmware and memory attributes, etc.

Data about network functionality and connectivity. Such as the device's IP address, mobile network (IMEI, mobile carrier, etc.), and whether the device is connected to a free or paid network.

Data about the operating system and its configuration, such as OS version and build number, region and language settings, diagnostic level, and whether the device is part of the Windows Insider Program.

Data about connected peripherals, such as model, manufacturer, driver, compatibility information.

Data about the applications installed on the device. Such as application name, version, and publisher.

Information about whether the device is ready to update or whether there are any factors that prevent it from receiving updates. Low battery, low disk space, connectivity to paid networks, etc.

Did the update complete successfully or fail?

Data on the reliability of the diagnostic information collection system itself.

Basic error reporting. Health data about the operating system and applications running on the device. For example, applications such as Microsoft Paint or third-party games report errors when they hang or crash.
	
Optional diagnostic data includes detailed information about the device and its settings, features, and device health. Optional diagnostic data may also include websites you visit, data about device activity (sometimes referred to as usage), and enhanced error reporting to help Microsoft fix and improve its products and services for all users. If you choose to send optional diagnostic data, the required diagnostic data is always included and the following additional information is collected:

Additional data on devices, connectivity, and configuration. Data beyond the range of mandatory diagnostic data will be collected.

Log information about the state and health of the operating system and other system components. Required diagnostic data collects data beyond what is collected for updates and diagnostic systems.

App activity. Such as the program launched on the device, the length of execution time, and the speed of response to input.

Your Microsoft browser (Microsoft Edge or Internet Explorer) activity, including browsing history and search terms.

Enhanced Error Reporting. Such as the memory state of the device when a system or app crash occurs, which may unintentionally contain user content, such as some of the files you were using at the time of the problem.
	
Even if you choose to send optional diagnostic data, some of the aforementioned data may not be collected from your device. Microsoft minimizes the amount of optional diagnostic data it collects from all devices by collecting data only from a subset of devices (a sample). By running the Diagnostic Data Viewer tool, you can display an icon that indicates whether your device is included in the sample and what data is being collected from the device. For instructions on how to download the Diagnostic Data Viewer tool, see Diagnostics & feedback in the Windows Settings app.
	
Certain data items collected by Windows Diagnostics are subject to change to give Microsoft the flexibility to collect the data required for the purposes described. For example, we may need data items that we did not previously collect to help Microsoft troubleshoot the latest performance issues that affect your computer experience or to update newly sold Windows devices. For an up-to-date list of data types collected in Required and Optional Diagnostic Data, see Required (Basic level) Windows Diagnostic Events and Fields (https://docs.microsoft.com/windows/configuration/basic-level-windows-diagnostic-events-and-fields) or Windows Optional (Full level) Diagnostic Data (https://docs.microsoft.com/windows/privacy/windows-diagnostic-data)See ". Some of the error reporting information is provided to partners (such as device manufacturers) to help troubleshoot products and services that correspond to Windows and other Microsoft products and services. The use of this information is limited to repairing or improving products and services. Some aggregated and anonymized diagnostic data, such as general usage trends for Windows apps and features, may also be shared with some third parties. Learn more about Windows diagnostic data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=614828).
	
Recognition of hand-drawn and keyboard inputs. By sending diagnostic data for your drawing and typing, you can choose to help Microsoft improve the recognition accuracy of your drawing and typing. If you choose, Microsoft collects samples of typed or hand-drawn content to enhance features such as handwriting recognition, autocomplete, next word prediction, and spelling correction in many languages used by Microsoft users. When Microsoft collects diagnostic data for hand-drawn and typed input, it is broken down into small samples and processed to remove any unique identifiers, sequence information, and other data (e.g., email addresses, numbers, etc.) that could lead to reconstruction of the original content or association with the user. It also includes relevant performance data, such as manual changes users make to their sentences and words they add to the dictionary. Learn more about handwriting in Windows, typing improvements (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=614828).
	
Personalized offers
	 
If you enable personalized offers, Microsoft will use information about your device and device usage. This includes Windows diagnostic data, as well as account information and data collected by other Microsoft products and services. They are used to provide personalized tips, ads, and recommendations to improve your Windows experience. Personalized offers include suggestions for customizing and optimizing Windows, as well as ads and suggestions about Microsoft and third-party products and services, features, apps, and hardware that can help improve your Windows experience. For example, Windows may explain new features that can help you get the most out of your device. If you're streaming videos in a browser, Windows may recommend Microsoft Store apps for more efficient streaming. Or, if you're running out of space on your hard drive, Windows may recommend you try OneDrive or add more storage.
	
If personalized offers are turned on, Windows may personalize the offer with mandatory diagnostic data. This data may include information about the device, its settings and features, and whether it is functioning properly. If you decide to share optional diagnostic data, the data used to personalize your offer may include additional information about your device's health in addition to information about how you use the app and features. And even if the data does not leave the device, it still has the possibility to personalize offers on the device locally with information about the device and activity. The content of crash dumps, voice, keystrokes, and hand-drawn input data is not used for personalization.
	
In addition to information about your device and how you use it (such as Windows Diagnostic Data), Microsoft may use the following data from other Microsoft products and accounts or combine it with Windows Diagnostic Data to personalize your offer:

Web activity (if you have given Microsoft Edge permission to collect web activity for personalized search, ads, and news).

Information about your use of other Microsoft products and services, including Microsoft Bing, Microsoft 365, Xbox, and Microsoft websites (such as MSN.com).

Subscription and purchase history.

Data from third-party websites that may be shared with Microsoft.
	
We may also use tips, recommendations, and information about working with promotions to provide and improve personalized offers and similar messages in other Microsoft products.
	
To control how data collected by other Microsoft products is personalized for your offers, visit the Personalized ads and offers page (https://aka.ms/personalized-offers). access. The data we use to personalize offers may change over time, but this page always shows a list of the most recent data sources so you can decide how Microsoft uses your data. In some regions, such as the European Economic Area, if you turn off personalized offers in Windows, you won't be able to use data from other Microsoft products to personalize Windows tips, ads, and recommendations. In other regions, you can visit the Personalized ads and offers page (https://aka.ms/personalized-offers) to control how data collected by other Microsoft products is personalized for your offers.
	
Contextual data from your device and some basic account data are used to display appropriate messaging in Windows, regardless of whether the setting for personalized offers or the use of data from other Microsoft products for offer personalization is turned off. For example, this data is used to ensure that the language of the content is correct and appropriate for the age group.
	
Personalized offers apply to tips, offers, ads, and recommendations that appear on Windows. Changing this setting doesn't affect the types of offers that appear in other Microsoft products. You can change this setting at any time by searching for "personalized offers" in the Windows Settings app. More information about personalized offers (https://support.microsoft.com/windows/807608ee-3de2-4498-8e7c-eb10d655567f).
	
[Tailored experiences] (Customize your experience)
	
Customized experiences are replaced with personalized offers in newer versions of Windows. Even if you haven't installed the latest Windows update, you may still see a customized experience on your device.
	
If you choose to enable experience customization, Windows diagnostic data (required or optional, depending on your choice) will be used to show you customized tips, ads, and recommendations to improve your Microsoft experience. If you select Required in your diagnostic data settings, personalization is based on information about your device, its settings and features, and whether it's working properly. If you choose Options, personalization is based on information about how you use apps and features, as well as additional information about the health of your device. However, information about the websites viewed or the content of crash dumps, voice, keystrokes, and hand-drawn input data received by users if they select Options is not used for customization. Data for customized experiences is sent to Microsoft and stored with a unique identifier. These identifiers help you recognize users and devices and understand device service issues and usage patterns.
	
Experience customization includes suggestions for customizing and optimizing Windows, as well as ads and suggestions about Microsoft and third-party products and services, features, apps, and hardware that can help you experience Windows. For example, it shows information about features or new features that users may not know about so they can get the most out of their device. If you are experiencing problems with your Windows device, they may also suggest solutions. You may be offered the opportunity to customize your lock screen with photos, show more types of photos you like, or avoid showing types of photos you don't like. If you're streaming videos in a browser, Microsoft Store apps may be recommended for more efficient streaming. Or, if you're running out of space on your hard drive, Windows may recommend that you try OneDrive or buy more hardware space. Learn more about customizing the Windows experience (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=614828).
	
Feedback Hub
	
The Feedback Hub provides a way to collect feedback about Microsoft products and installed first- and third-party apps. With Feedback Hub, the Feedback Hub periodically reads a list of installed apps and determines which apps can be submitted to feedback. The Feedback Hub determines which apps are installed on the device through public APIs. And on HoloLens, the Feedback Hub uses the camera and microphone when sharing audio input with the surroundings. You can also use the image and document library to access attached screenshots and screen recordings and send them as part of your feedback.
	
To sign in to the Feedback Hub, you can use either your personal Microsoft account or the account specified by the organization (work or school) you use to sign in to Microsoft products. When you sign in with your work or school account, you can associate it with your organization and send feedback to Microsoft. Whether you use a work or school account, or a personal Microsoft account, the feedback you provide may be made available to the public, depending on the settings configured by your organization's administrator. In addition, feedback provided using your work or school account can be viewed by your organization's admin through the Feedback Hub or admin center.
	
When you send us feedback about an issue or add details about the issue, diagnostic data is sent to Microsoft to improve our products and services. Depending on your diagnostic data settings in the Diagnostics & Feedback section of the Windows Settings app, you have the option to automatically send diagnostic data in the Feedback Hub or send it to Microsoft when you provide feedback. Based on the categories you choose when submitting feedback, we may collect additional personal data to help you troubleshoot your issue. For example, location-related information when you send feedback about location services, or gaze-related information when you send feedback about Mixed Reality. Microsoft may also share the data collected with the feedback with Microsoft partners (device manufacturers or firmware developers) when you submit feedback so that partners can troubleshoot products and services that correspond to Windows and other Microsoft products and services. Learn more about Windows diagnostic data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=614828).
	
Contact us
	
Contact us allows Windows users to get technical support for Windows and other Microsoft applications. It provides self-service support (such as links to help articles and instructions on how Windows users can resolve issues on their own), diagnostics, and the ability to connect customers to live Microsoft agents if needed. You can sign in to the Contact Us component using your Microsoft account to create a consumer support case. Enterprise account users may also be allowed to create customer support cases if enabled by the tenant administrator, depending on their organization's support contract.
	
Your inquiry may recommend that you perform diagnostics. If you agree, your diagnostic data will be processed according to the Diagnosticssection.
	
If your system settings allow it, you can use the system's microphone to capture support questions instead of typing. You can control this in the Microphone privacy settings in the Windows Settings application. Also, if you choose to start the feedback process within Inquiry, Inquiry will help you access the application list to open the Feedback Hub and view the appropriate app. As described in the Feedback Hub section of this Privacy Statement, all feedback is entered and managed by the Feedback Hub. Contact does not use location data as part of the service.
	
Live Captions
	
Live captions create a transcript of your audio to help you understand the audio content. Live captions allow you to generate captions from any voice, including speech. It doesn't matter if it's audio online, downloaded to your device, or received from your microphone. By default, microphone audio transcription creation is disabled.
	
Captioned audio data is only processed by the device and is not shared with the cloud or Microsoft. Learn more about live captions (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2156465).
	
Location Services and Recordings
	
Windows Location Services. Microsoft operates location services that help determine the exact geographic location of a particular Windows device. The accuracy with which a device can be located depends on the device's performance and may be able to be pinpointed. If you enable location services on a Windows device, or if you grant permission to a Microsoft app to access location information on a non-Windows device, Microsoft collects data and location information about cell towers and Wi-Fi access points. After you delete the data that identifies the person or device about that data, it is added to the location database. This anonymized location information is used to improve Microsoft's location services.
	
Windows services and features, apps that run on Windows, and websites that you open in the Windows browser can access your device's location through Windows, if your settings allow it. Some features and apps require location permissions when a user first installs Windows, some require the user to use the app for the first time, or each time the user accesses the device's location. For more information about some Windows apps that use your device's location, see the Windows apps section of this statement.
	
If an app or feature accesses your device's location and you're signed in with a Microsoft account, your Windows device will also upload that location to the cloud, which can then be used by other apps and services that you've given permission to use your Microsoft account. Microsoft only stores the last known location (replacing the previous location each time a new location is uploaded). You can view or delete this location data from your Microsoft account's privacy dashboard.
	
The Windows Settings app also allows you to see which apps have access to your device's precise location, enable and disable access to your device's location services from specific apps, and disable access to your device's location services. You can also set a default location, and if location services can't detect the exact location of your device, it will use the location you set.
	
There are some exceptions to how your device's location is located, which isn't directly managed by your location settings.
	
Desktop apps are specific types of apps, and location permissions are controlled by Windows location settings and don't appear in the list of apps that can use location. You can download it from the Microsoft Store. You can also download it from the Internet. You can install it using some type of media (such as a CD, DVD, or USB storage device). Learn more about third-party desktop apps and how they can determine your device's location when your device's location settings are turned off (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2007461).
	
If you turn off your device's location settings, some web-based experiences or third-party apps that appear in Windows may use other technologies (such as Bluetooth, IP addresses, cellular modems), or cloud-based location services to determine your device's location with varying levels of accuracy.
	
To help users make emergency calls in an emergency, Windows attempts to determine and share the user's precise location, regardless of the user's location settings. Also, if your device has a SIM card inserted or cellular service is used in other ways, your mobile carrier can also access your device's location. Windows location details (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=529987).
	
Approximate position. When you enable location services, apps that don't have precise location information access to your general location information, such as your city, zip code, or region.
	
Windows' limited feature set uses IP addresses to provide information about the context of the region, such as the weather on the taskbar, when location services are turned off. Learn more about Windows location (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=529987) and how to turn off these features.
	
Find your device. The Find Device feature allows Windows device administrators to search for the device's location from account.microsoft.com/devices. To enable Find Devices, admins must be signed in with a Microsoft account and have location settings enabled. You can use this feature even if other users deny access to your location for all apps. If an administrator tries to locate the device, a notification appears in the user's notification area. Learn more about how to find your device in Windows (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=533063).
	
Recording. Some Windows devices have a recording feature that allows you to save your device's activities, including communication with other users, as audio clips or video clips. If you record a session, the recorded recording is stored locally on the user's device. In some cases, you may choose to send the recorded data to a Microsoft product or service that distributes the recording to the public. Important: Before you record or send any communications, you must understand your legal responsibilities. This may include obtaining the prior consent of all users participating in the conversation or, if necessary, other approvals. Microsoft is not responsible for the recording features or how you use them.
	
narrator
	
Narrator is a built-in screen reader tool that allows you to use Windows without a screen. If an image or link doesn't have a clear description, Narrator provides an intelligent description of the image or page title or a summary of the web page.
	
Press Narrator + Ctrl + D to ask for an image description, and the image will be sent to Microsoft to analyze the image and generate a description. Images are used only for the purpose of generating descriptions and are not stored by Microsoft.
	
When you press Narrator + Ctrl + D to ask for a description of the page title, Microsoft will send the URL of the site you're viewing. Along with generating page title descriptions, this information is also used to improve the quality of Microsoft services, such as the Bing services described in the "Bing" section above.
	
When you press Narrator + S twice to ask for a list of popular links on a web page, Microsoft will send the URL of the site you're viewing. Along with generating summaries of popular links, this information is also used to improve the quality of Microsoft services (such as Bing).
	
You can disable these features at any time in Narrator > Get image descriptions, page titles, and popular links in Windows settings.
	
You can also send us feedback about the narrator. Based on your feedback, Microsoft will work to diagnose and resolve issues with Narrator and improve the quality of Microsoft products and services, including Windows. You can press Narrator + Alt + F in Narrator to send you voice feedback at any time. This command will launch the Feedback Hub app and get you ready to send you voice feedback. If you enable the Narrator Better setting in the Windows Settings app and send you voice feedback from the Feedback Hub, we'll use the latest data about your device and usage, such as event trace log (ETL) data, to improve the quality of Microsoft products and services, such as Windows, is also sent with audio feedback.
	
Smartphone Link - Link to Windows
	
The Smartphone Link feature allows you to link your Android phone to your Microsoft account and iPhone via Bluetooth to connect to your Windows PC. Because your Android device is linked to your Microsoft account and your iPhone is linked via Bluetooth, you can implement a variety of cross-device experiences across all Windows devices that are signed in or connected via Bluetooth. Use Phone Connect to view recent photos from your Android phone on your Windows device, make and receive live calls from your Android phone on your Windows device, view and send text messages from your Windows device, and use Android from your Windows device You can take other actions on phone notifications, share your phone screen on your Windows device with Phone Mirroring, and instantly access Android apps installed on your Android phone on your Windows device. With Phone Link, you can make and receive calls from your iPhone, view and send text messages, and view, ignore, or take other actions on iPhone notifications from your Windows device.
	
To use the Smartphone Integration, you need to install the Windows Link service on your Android device. If you want, you can also download Phone Link on your iPhone.
	
To use Phone Integration, you need to sign in to the Phone Link feature on your Windows device, the Windows Link service on your Android phone, or a Microsoft account with Bluetooth enabled on your iPhone. Your Android phone and Windows device must be connected to the internet. Some features require Bluetooth to be enabled and to pair your phone with your PC. To use the calling feature, you must also have Bluetooth enabled on your Android phone.
	
During the setup of your Windows device, you can choose to link your phone to your Microsoft account. To do this, sign in to Windows on your Android phone, grant permissions, and complete the onboarding experience. Once done, the Link to Windows service syncs your data to all Windows PCs that are signed in to your Microsoft account. For more information on how we use your data, see:
	
As part of providing you with the functionality of Phone Link, Microsoft collects performance, usage, and device data, including, for example, the hardware capabilities of your phone and Windows devices, the number and duration of Phone Link sessions, and the time it takes during setup.
	
You can unlink your Android phone from your Windows device at any time by going to Phone Integration settings and selecting Remove Android phone. You can do the same from the Windows Link service settings on your Android phone. For more information, see the support page (https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/topic/unlink-a-device-in-the-phone-link-app-9382f770-b203-7e0e-c81e-18d4053cf4e5).
	
You can unlink your iPhone from your Windows device at any time by going to Phone Linkage settings and selecting Delete iPhone. To do the same from your iPhone, go to Settings> Bluetooth> Choose a PC name, > click the (i) icon, go to >, and then select Forget this device. By disabling the experience, all users can remove Bluetooth pairing.
	
Text Messages – Android devices. You can use a link to view text messages sent to your Android phone on your Windows device and send text messages from your Windows device. Only text messages sent and received within the last 30 days will appear on your Windows device. These text messages are temporarily stored on your Windows device. It does not store text messages on Microsoft's servers, nor does it modify or delete text messages on your Android phone. You can view messages sent using SMS (Short Message Service), MMS (Multimedia Messaging Service) on Android devices, and RCS (Rich Communication Service) on some Samsung devices on some mobile carrier networks. To provide this feature, Phone Link accesses the content of the text message and the contact information of the person or business that sends or receives the text message.
	
Text Messages – iPhone. With Phone Integration, you can view text messages sent to your iPhone on your Windows device and send text messages from your Windows device. Only text messages sent and received within a Bluetooth session or iMessage will appear on your Windows device. These text messages are temporarily stored on your Windows device. It does not store text messages on Microsoft's servers, nor does it modify or delete text messages on your iPhone. You can view messages sent via SMS (Short Message Service). To provide this feature, Phone Link accesses the content of the text message and the contact information of the person or business that sends or receives the text message.
	
Calls – Android devices. You can use Phone Link to make and receive calls from your Android phone on your Windows device. You can also use the Phone link to view recent calls on your Windows device. To activate this feature, you need to enable specific permissions on both your Windows device and Android phone, such as access to call logs and permissions to make calls from your PC. You can revoke these permissions at any time under the Settings page of the Phone link in Windows device and Android phone settings. Only calls made and received within the last 30 days will appear in the call log on your Windows device. These call details are temporarily stored on your Windows device. Microsoft does not modify or delete the call history on your Android phone.
	
Calls – iPhone. With Phone Integration, you can make calls from your iPhone to and from your Windows device. You can also use the Phone link to view recent calls on your Windows device. To enable this feature, you need to enable the Sync Contacts feature in your iPhone's Bluetooth settings. These call details are temporarily stored on your Windows device. Microsoft will not modify or delete your iPhone's call history.
	
Photos – Android devices. With Phone Integration, you can copy, share, edit, save, or delete photos from your Android phone on your Windows device. Only some of the recent photos in the Camera Roll and Screenshots folders on your Android phone will always be visible on your Windows device. These photos are temporarily stored on your Windows device, and when you take more photos on your Android phone, the temporary copy of the old photos will be deleted from your Windows device. We do not store your photos on Microsoft's servers, nor do we modify or delete photos on your Android phone.
	
Notifications – Android devices. You can use the Phone link to display notifications on your Android phone on your Windows device. You can use Phone Link to read and dismiss notifications on your Android phone from your Windows device, and perform other actions related to notifications. To activate this Phone Link feature, you need to enable certain permissions, such as syncing notifications on both Windows devices and Android phones. You can revoke these permissions at any time under the Settings page of the Phone link in Windows device and Android phone settings. For more information, see the support page (https://support.microsoft.com/your-phone-app).
	
Notifications – iPhone. You can use phone integration to display iPhone notifications on your Windows device. You can use Phone Connect to read and dismiss notifications on your iPhone from your Windows device, and to perform other actions related to notifications. To activate this smartphone linkage feature, you need to enable certain permissions, such as syncing notifications on both your Windows device and iPhone. You can revoke these permissions at any time under the Smartphone Links settings page in your Windows device and iPhone Bluetooth settings.
	
Mirroring your smartphone screen on your Android device. On supported devices (https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/topic/supported-devices-for-phone-link-app-experiences-cb044172-87aa-9e41-d446-c4ac83ce8807), you can use Phone Link to display the screen of an Android phone on a Windows device. Your Android phone's screen appears as a pixel stream on your Windows device, and any audio you enable on your Android phone's screen when linked to your Windows device using a phone link will play from your Android phone.
	
App mirroring – Android devices. On supported devices, phone integration allows you to use Android apps installed on your Android phone on your Windows device. For example, you can launch a music app in a Windows session and listen to the app's audio on your PC speakers. Microsoft collects and provides a service with a list of installed Android apps and recent activity to show you recently used apps. Microsoft does not store any information that you install or that your app displays in your experience with the app.
	
Content Transfer – Android devices. On supported devices, Phone Integration allows you to copy and paste content, such as files, documents, and photos, between your Android phone and your Windows device. You can transfer content from your Android phone to your Windows device and from your Windows device to your Android phone by dragging and dropping content between devices.
	
Instant Hotspot – Android devices. On supported devices, the Link to Windows service allows users to share mobile hotspot information with their paired PC through secure Bluetooth communication. Your PC can now connect to the internet through the Windows network pop-up. Keep in mind that depending on your mobile data plan, mobile data charges may apply.
	
Contact sync – Android devices. With Link to Windows, you can sync your Android contacts to the Microsoft cloud to access your contacts from other Microsoft products and services. To enable this feature, go to the Windows link settings and enable the "Sync Contacts" feature. Your contact information is stored online and associated with your Microsoft account. You can disable syncing and delete these contacts at any time. Learn more here (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2202359).
	
Contact sync – Android devices. With Phone Integration, you can sync your contacts from your iPhone and access them for messaging and calling. To enable this feature, after connecting your iPhone to your phone, go to your iPhone's Bluetooth settings and turn on Sync Contacts under your PC name. You can turn off Sync Contacts at any time by toggling it off.
	
Text-to-speech. Features of Phone Link include accessibility features such as text-to-speech. You can activate the text-to-speech feature to hear the content of text messages or notifications as audio. If you activate this feature, text messages and notifications will be read aloud when they are received.
	
Office Enterprise – Android devices. With Link to Windows, you can insert photos directly from your phone into the web and desktop versions of some Microsoft 365 apps, such as PowerPoint, Excel, and Word. To do so, your IT admin must have enabled the optional connected experience for Microsoft Office applications. You must also associate your mobile device with your school or work account and give your account photo permissions. After onboarding, the session will last 15 minutes, and you will be able to transfer photos from your mobile device. To use this feature again, you need to scan the QR code. Link to Windows does not collect any information about your school or work account or enterprise. To provide this service, Microsoft uses cloud services to relay files for the purpose of inserting photos into the web and desktop versions of selected Microsoft 365 apps, such as PowerPoint, Excel, and Word files.
	
Cross-device experience
	
With the cross-device experience on Windows, you can access your mobile device from your PC using your Microsoft account. You can manage these in the Bluetooth & Devices section of your Windows PC settings under Mobile devices. As part of providing these features, Microsoft collects performance usage and device data, including information about the hardware capabilities of mobile and Windows devices. You can enable or disable this feature at any time in your PC settings in Windows.
	
Use your mobile device as a connected camera. This feature allows you to use your mobile device's camera with apps or products on Windows that support the camera feature. You can enable this feature under Mobile devices in the Bluetooth & Devices section of your PC's settings. Microsoft does not record or store your camera session or the information displayed by your camera in any application or product.
	
Get notifications for new photos on your mobile device. This feature allows you to receive notifications from your linked mobile device on your Windows PC. These photos are temporarily stored on your Windows PC when you edit or open them. Until you decide to delete these photos, you need to start saving them to your PC to save them. We do not store your photos on Microsoft's servers, nor do we modify or delete photos on your mobile device.
	
View your mobile device in File Explorer. This feature allows you to access files on your mobile device in File Explorer. You can enable this feature under Mobile devices in the Bluetooth & Devices section of your PC's settings. Microsoft does not store the contents of the file in the service.
	
Security and Safety Features
	
Device encryption. Device encryption uses BitLocker drive encryption technology to encrypt personal information and protect personal information stored on the user's device. When device encryption is enabled, Windows automatically encrypts the drive where Windows is installed and generates a recovery key. The BitLocker recovery key for the user's personal device is automatically backed up online in the user's personal Microsoft OneDrive account. Microsoft does not use your personal recovery key for any purpose.
	
Run the malicious software removal tool. The Malicious Software Removal Tool (MSRT) runs on devices at least once a month as part of Windows Update. MSRT checks the device for infections caused by individual, associated malicious software ("malware") and removes any infections found. If malware is present on your device, running MSRT will remove the malware listed on the Microsoft support website. During the malware check, a report is sent to Microsoft with information about detected malware, errors, and other data about the device. To prevent MSRT from sending this data to Microsoft, disable the MSRT reporting component.
	
Microsoft family. Parents can use Microsoft Family Safety to understand how their children are using their devices and set boundaries. If you choose to create or join a family group, click Microsoft Family Safety (https://support.microsoft.com/account-billing/microsoft-family-safety-bb97220e-9dd8-4b4a-9d15-8194d5941dc5) Please check the information carefully. If you live in a region that requires permission to create an account to access Microsoft services, you may be asked to obtain parental consent or provide parental consent. If the user is under the legal age in your region, during the registration process, they will be asked to obtain consent from their parent or guardian by entering their adult email address. If Family Activity Reporting is enabled for a child, Microsoft collects information about how the child uses the device and provides parents with a report on their child's activity. Activity reports are periodically deleted from Microsoft servers.
	
Microsoft Defender SmartScreen and Smart App Control. Microsoft strives to protect your device and passwords from insecure apps, files, and web content.
	
Microsoft Defender SmartScreen helps protect you when you use Microsoft services by identifying threats to your customers, devices, and passwords. These threats can include potentially unsafe apps or web content that Microsoft Defender SmartScreen detects when reviewing websites visited, files downloaded, and apps installed and run. Web and app content checks with Microsoft Defender SmartScree send data about content and devices to Microsoft. This includes the full web address of the content. If additional analysis is required to identify security threats, information about suspicious websites or apps, such as the content displayed, the sounds played, and the application's memory, may be sent to Microsoft. This data is used only for security purposes in detecting, protecting, and responding to security incidents, identity theft, fraud, or other malicious, deceptive, or illegal activity. If Microsoft Defender SmartScreen detects that content is dangerous, users will see a warning instead of the content. Microsoft Defender SmartScreen can be turned on or off in the Windows Security app.
	
When supported, Smart App Control can help check for software installed and running on the device to determine if there is malicious software, potentially unwanted software, or other threats to the user and device. On supported devices, Smart App Control starts in evaluation mode, and the data collected for Microsoft Defender SmartScreen, such as file name, file content hash, download location, and digital certificate for files, is used to protect the device by using Smart App for additional security protection. It is used to determine if you are a good candidate to use the control. Smart App Control is not enabled and is not blocked in evaluation mode. Because smart app controls can interfere with legitimate tasks that users intend to do – such as developers who use a lot of unsigned files, some devices may not be good candidates. If you're a good candidate for Smart App Control, it's automatically enabled and provides additional protection to your device beyond Microsoft Defender SmartScreen. Otherwise, Smart App Control is unavailable and turned off completely. If your device isn't supported or isn't a good candidate for Smart App Control, Microsoft Defender SmartScreen can still help protect your device. If Smart App Control is enabled and identified as malicious, potentially unwanted, or unknown or unsigned, it will be blocked and notified before you can open, run, or install the app. Learn more about Smart App Control (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2185232).
	
When you check a file with Microsoft Defender SmartScreen or Smart App Control, data about that file is sent to Microsoft. This includes the file name, hash of the file content, download location, and the file's digital certificate.
	
You can turn off Smart App Control in the Windows Security app.
	
Microsoft Defender Antivirus. Microsoft Defender Antivirus detects malware and other unwanted software, potentially unwanted apps, and other malicious content on your device. If your device isn't actively protected by other anti-malware software, Microsoft Defender Antivirus is automatically enabled to protect your device. When Microsoft Defender Antivirus is enabled, the security status of your device is monitored. If Microsoft Defender Antivirus is enabled or running (because regular scans are enabled), a report with data about suspected malware or other unwanted software, potentially unwanted apps, and other malicious content will automatically be sent to Microsoft. In some cases, they may send files that may contain malicious content, such as malware or unknown files, for further inspection. If the report may contain personal information, the report will not be sent automatically and will be prompted for review by the user before submission. You can also configure Microsoft Defender Antivirus to prevent reports and suspected malware from being sent to Microsoft.
	
Voice recognition, voice activation, hand-drawn typing, keyboard typing
	
Speech recognition. Microsoft offers both device-based speech recognition capabilities and cloud-based (online) speech recognition technology.
	
If you turn on the online speech recognition setting, your app will be able to use Microsoft cloud-based speech recognition. In addition, Windows 10 allows you to use dictation within Windows with online speech recognition settings.
	
When you enable speech recognition during HoloLens device setup or Windows Mixed Reality installation, you can use your voice for commands, dictation, and app interactions. Both device-based speech recognition and online speech recognition settings are enabled. With both settings enabled, when the headset is on, the device always listens for your voice input and sends voice data to Microsoft's cloud-based speech recognition technology.
	
When using Microsoft's cloud-based speech recognition technology, whether enabled in your online speech recognition settings or interacting with HoloLens or voice typing, Microsoft provides speech recognition services by collecting and using voice recordings to create text transcriptions of spoken words in your speech data. Microsoft will not store, sample, or listen to audio recordings without your permission. For more information about how Microsoft manages your speech data, see Speech recognition technology (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainspeechrecognitionmodule).
	
You can also use device-based speech recognition without sending voice data to Microsoft. However, Microsoft's cloud-based speech recognition technology is more accurate than device-based speech recognition. If you turn off the Online Speech Recognition setting, speech recognition services (such as Live Captions, Narrator, and Voice Access) that use only device-based recognition that are cloud-agnostic will work, and Microsoft will not collect speech data.
	
You can disable online speech recognition at any time. This will stop apps that rely on your online speech recognition settings from sending voice data to Microsoft. If you're using a HoloLens or Windows Mixed Reality headset, you can also disable device-based speech recognition at any time. Disabling it prevents the device from hearing your voice input. Learn more about Windows speech recognition (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=874646).

Activation by voice. Windows provides supported apps with the ability to respond and take actions based on voice keywords specific to that app.
	
If your app is allowed to listen for voice keywords, Windows will actively listen for these keywords with your microphone. Once the keyword is recognized, the app can access the user's voice recording, which can process the recording, take action, respond with voice responses, and more. The app may send voice recordings to its own service on the cloud and process commands. Each app must ask for the user's permission before accessing the voice recording.
	
In addition, voice activation can be enabled when the device is locked. When enabled, the relevant app can continue to listen to voice keywords with the microphone and activate any user speaking near the device while the device is locked. When the device is locked, the app can access the same list of features and information as if the device is unlocked.
	
You can disable voice activation at any time. Learn more about voice activation in Windows (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=874646).
	
If you turn off voice activation, some third-party desktop apps and services may still listen for your microphone and collect your voice input. Learn more about third-party desktop apps and how they can access your microphone even when the setting is turned off (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2007461).
	
Voice input. In Windows 11, dictation has been updated and renamed to voice typing. Voice input uses both device-based and online speech recognition technologies to enhance speech-to-text services. You can also provide audio clips to improve your voice typing. If you choose not to provide audio clips, you can still use voice typing. You can change your selection at any time in the dictation settings. Microsoft will not store, sample, or listen to audio recordings without your permission. Learn more about Microsoft and voice data (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=2145715).
	
Voice access. Windows allows everyone, including those with motor disabilities, to control their PC and use their voice to create text. For example, voice access supports scenarios such as opening and switching apps, browsing the web, reading and composing emails, and more. Voice access utilizes the latest on-device speech recognition to accurately recognize speech and is supported without an internet connection. When a user calls for voice access, the device's microphone is used. More information about voice access (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2173502).
	
Personalization of hand-drawn and keyboard input. Typing input and handwritten input words are also collected. It is intended to provide users with a custom word list and apply proper character recognition when typing and handwriting on the device to provide typing hints when typing and handwriting.
	
You can disable the Draw & Keyboard Input personalization settings at any time. This will remove any custom word lists stored on your device. If you enable it again, you will need to recreate the custom word list. Learn more about freehand typing & typing personalization in (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=544945)Windows.
	
Sync and backup settings
	
When you sign in to Windows with a Microsoft account, Windows can store your settings, files, and device configuration data on Microsoft's servers. Windows only uses stored settings, files, and device configuration data to facilitate the migration of experiences on another device.
	
You can turn off this feature to prevent Windows from saving settings, files, and configuration data from Windows Settings. You can delete data that you previously backed up to your Microsoft account by visiting the Microsoft account device page (https://account.microsoft.com/devices).
	
Learn more about Windows backup and sync settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2172845).
	
Renewal Services
	
Windows update services include Windows Update and Microsoft Update. Windows Update is a service that provides software updates for other supporting software, such as drivers and firmware provided by Windows software and device manufacturers. Microsoft Update is a service that provides updates for other Microsoft software, such as Microsoft 365.
	
Windows Update automatically downloads Windows software updates to your device. If Windows Update is available (recommended), or if Windows notifies you of a restart that requires the update to finish installing, configure Windows Update to install these updates automatically. As described in the "Microsoft Store (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainwindowsstoremodule)" section of this Privacy Statement, applications available in the Microsoft Store are automatically updated through the Microsoft Store.
	
Web browsers: Microsoft Edge Legacy and Internet Explorer
	
This section applies to legacy versions of Microsoft Edge (version 44 and earlier). For non-legacy versions of Microsoft Edge, see the Microsoft Edge (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainmsedgemodule)section of the Privacy Statement.
	
Microsoft Edge is the default web browser for Windows. Microsoft's legacy browser, Internet Explorer, is also available for Windows. Whenever you use a web browser to access the Internet, data about your device ("Standard Device Data") is sent to the websites you are visiting and to the online services you are using. Standard device data includes the user's IP address, browser type, language, access time, and referring website address. This data is logged on to the website's web server. What data is logged on and how it is used depends on the privacy policy of the websites you visit and the web services you use. In addition, Microsoft Edge sends a unique browser ID to specific websites so that Microsoft can develop aggregate data that we use to improve browser features and services.
	
In addition, the user's browser usage data, such as history, web form data, temporary Internet files, and cookies, is stored on the user's device, for example. Users can delete this data using Delete browsing history.
	
Microsoft Edge allows you to capture content such as and save it to your device:
		
Web Notes. You can create ink and text annotations on the web pages you visit, and then clip, save, or share them.
		
Active reading. You can create and manage reading lists that contain websites or documents.
		
Hub. Easily manage your reading list, favorites, downloads, and history in one area.
			
Pin a website to the taskbar. You can pin your favorite websites to the Windows taskbar. Because websites can identify web pages that users have pinned, you can provide users with a notification badge to let them know that there is a new item to refer to on the website.
	
Some Microsoft browser information stored on the device is synchronized across devices when the user signs in with their Microsoft account, so they can access data on all browsers that they are signed in to on any device. For example, browsing history and favorites in Internet Explorer, favorites, reading lists, and autofill form entries (such as name, address, and phone number) fall under this information, and may also include data about the extensions you have installed. For example, in Microsoft Edge, when you sync your Reading List across multiple devices, a copy of the content you choose to save to your Reading List will be sent to all synced devices for you to view later. You can disable Internet Explorer sync by going to Start > Settings > Accounts > Sync Settings. (For more information, see the Sync settings (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainsyncsettingsmodule) section of this privacy statement.) Also, to disable Microsoft Edge browser information syncing, disable the sync option in Microsoft Edge settings.
	
Microsoft Edge and Internet Explorer use your search queries and browsing history to provide faster browsing and more relevant search results. These features include:
		
Internet Explorer Search Suggestionsautomatically sends information entered in the browser address bar to the user's default search provider (such as Bing) and provides search recommendations as characters are entered.
	
Microsoft Edge Search Suggestions and Site Suggestions automatically send information entered in the browser address bar to Bing (regardless of whether the user has selected a different default search provider) and provide search suggestions as a character is typed.
	
Users can disable these features at any time. To provide search results, Microsoft Edge and Internet Explorer send search queries, standard device information, and location information (if location is enabled) to your default search provider when you use the app. If Bing is your default search provider, Microsoft will use this data as described in the Bing (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainbingmodule) section of this Privacy Statement.
	
AI features in Windows
	
Click to Run
	
Run with a click can work with Recall or as a standalone feature. Once launched, you can use the Click to Run feature to capture and analyze screenshots, identify the presence of text or images, and take appropriate action on each. For example, Click to Run offers options to edit screenshot images and correct or rewrite captured text. While click-to-run doesn't allow you to identify the content of the text or image identified within the screenshot, you can use local AI or other tools to modify the content as needed. Unless you make an explicit choice, all data remains on your local device. For example, you can send an image to Bing to do a search, ask a click-to-run to create a summary of the user's selected text (in this case, it will be sent to Microsoft's Azure AI cloud service), or use other local AI or other tools to correct a screenshot of a click-to-send submission.
	
In Run with a click, you can also use Microphone to search for text in the captured screenshot. Click the Microphone button to hear what is being spoken, it is entered in the search box, and all search results are highlighted. The audio captured by the microphone is not transmitted to the device.
	
Windows Recall
	
Recall is a Windows feature only available on Copilot+ PCs that allows users to search for what they see on their device using text or visual cues they remember. To use Recall, users must opt-in to save snapshots to their Copilot+ PC, which is an image containing everything displayed on the screen. The snapshot contains relevant metadata, such as the app's name and timestamp. All data is stored locally on the device and protected by Windows Hello Sign-in Enhanced Security (ESS). ESS provides more secure biometric sign-in, ensuring that only you have access to your information. Each time you launch Recall, users are prompted to authenticate with a Windows Hello biometric sign-in or PIN before the contents of the snapshot folder are decrypted. Click to do appears above the snapshot of the Recall and helps users get things done faster by allowing them to take action on the content on the screen (image or text). Snapshot analysis is always performed locally on the device, and the actions that can be taken change depending on the type of content detected.
	
You can also use the Copilot+ PC device's microphone as a way to search for text in captured snapshots. Click the Microphone button in the search input box in the Recall window to hear what is being spoken and enter it into the search box. The microphone is used until you pause speech recognition input, at which point it turns off until you explicitly press the Microphone button again. All matching points in the search results will be highlighted. The audio captured by the microphone is not transmitted to the device.
	
Data captured by Recall (for example, personal data such as snapshots, metadata, processing results, and user queries) is stored on the device of the account you are signed in to on your Copilot+ PC and is not sent externally from the device unless you take certain actions. This could be for example if you copy and paste a snapshot into another app, or if you choose to include a snapshot when you submit feedback through the Windows Feedback Hub. The only way you can share Recall content with someone is if the user takes an explicit action on the device.
	
You can control content (such as snapshots, metadata, search queries, and history) by pausing or deleting snapshots, filtering content, and using the privacy mode of supported browsers. Learn more about privacy and controlling your Recall experience here (https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/privacy-and-control-over-your-recall-experience-d404f672-7647-41e5-886c-a3c59680af15).
	
In addition to the Recall search feature, Recall also has a timeline, in which snapshots are organized in chronological order and visualized with a horizontal scrollbar. You can use this scroll bar to search for and utilize past activity on your PC. In addition to the features available in the timeline, you can delete individual snapshots from this view, all snapshots containing a specific website's domain (e.g., all snapshots of www.bing.com), and specific app snapshots collectively.
	
Recall also has a sensitive content filter that is enabled by default, which prevents sensitive information (e.g., credit card numbers, government-issued ID numbers, etc.) from being stored. Users can turn off this filter from Windows settings if they wish.
	
Many Microsoft applications are built into Windows, and others can be purchased in the Microsoft Store. Windows apps include:
	
Maps app. Maps apps provide location-based services and utilize Bing services to process user searches within the Maps app. If the Maps app has allowed you to access your location and location-based services are enabled in Windows, Bing services will collect the text you type after the "@" key to show location-based suggestions when you start a search using the "@" key in a supported text box in the Windows app. For more information about your Bing experience, see the Bing (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainbingmodule) section of this privacy statement. When the Maps app accesses your location, Microsoft collects anonymized location information from your device to improve Microsoft services, even when you're not using Maps. You can disable the Maps application from accessing your location by disabling location services or disabling access to location services for the Maps application.
	
Users can record their favorite places, the latest map searches in the Maps application. Your favorite places and search history will be added to your search suggestions. By giving the Maps app access to your camera, you can capture where the photo was taken. For example, if you take a picture of a car, you can see where the car is parked. You can also share your location with other people in your contacts. If you're signed in with a Microsoft account, your favorite locations, search history, and some app settings are synced to and from other devices and services. For more information, see the Sync and back up settings (https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-us/privacystatement#mainsyncsettingsmodule) section of this privacy statement.
	
Camera app. When you allow the camera application to use your location, your location is recorded in the photos and videos you take on your device. Detailed data such as camera model and date of photo and video capture are also recorded in photos and videos. When you share a photo or video, the recorded data is available to the person you share it with and the service. If you do, you can disable the camera application from accessing your location at any time by disabling all access to location services in the device's settings menu, or by disabling access to location services for the camera application.
	
When you open the Camera app, it displays a rectangle of the area of the image that may be used for image enhancement on the selected camera. The camera app doesn't retain any image enhancement data. You can change the camera's access settings at any time in the Windows settings menu. The camera app uses a variety of device features, including location, camera, microphone, video, and image library. For more information, visit the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9wzdncrfjbbg).
	
Photos app. There are two versions of the Photos app available. The updated Photos app includes features such as iCloud integration and local and cloud folder views. The previous legacy version of the Photos app includes features such as a video editor, People tab, and albums. If the "Overview" section of the Photos app settings indicates that the app is an "updated" Photos app, you are using the updated Photos app. In some cases, both the updated Photos app and the legacy version of Photos may be downloaded on the user's device.
	
The updated Photos app helps you organize, view, and share your photos and videos. For example, the Photos app offers different ways to group photos and videos by name, date taken, or date modified. You can also group them into folders and other cloud services where those files are stored, such as stored locally on your device or synced from OneDrive, iCloud to your device. The app can also move, copy, or upload files to different locations on your computer or on OneDrive. The All Photos tab shows photos and videos that have been stored or synced locally, depending on the date they were taken. The Favorites tab allows you to view photos and videos that you have previously added to your favorites. The Folders tab allows you to view photos and videos by storage location. There is also a tab where you can view photos and videos from any available cloud services that you have synced to your device, such as OneDrive or other third-party services.
	
The Photo Legacy app also helps you organize, view, and share your photos and videos. However, if you are using the classic Photos app, you may see other features that are not available in the new version of the Photos app, such as collections, albums, video editors, and person settings. The Collections tab displays photos and videos according to the date they were taken. The Albums tab helps you organize your photos and videos by location and general tags. The video editor allows you to edit, create, and share videos.
	
You can enable the People setting on the Settings page of the Photos Legacy app and on the People tab of the app. When enabled, the Photo Legacy app uses face grouping technology to organize your photos and videos into groups. The grouping feature detects faces in photos and videos and identifies whether they are visually similar to faces in other photos or videos in your local photo gallery. You can choose to associate a face group with your contacts in the People app.
	
When enabled in the Photos Legacy app, groupings are stored on your device as long as you choose to group or keep photos and videos. If the People setting is turned on, you'll be prompted to allow the Photo Legacy app to continue allowing face grouping after you haven't worked with it for three years. You can turn the People setting on or off at any time by going to the Settings page in the Photos Legacy app. Turning off this feature will remove the face grouping data from the classic app for Photos, but not your photos and videos. Details of traditional apps and face grouping in photos (https://support.microsoft.com/help/4468245/group-photos-by-faces).
	
If you choose to share photos and videos using the Photos app or the classic Photos app, the user or service you share the photo or video with will have access to the embedded data (such as location, camera model, and date).
	
People application. You can use the People application to view all your contacts in one place and communicate with your contacts. When you add an account to the People app, the contacts in the account are automatically added to the People app. You can add other accounts, such as social networks (Facebook, Twitter, etc.) or email accounts, to the People application. When you add an account, you will see the data that you want to import or sync from a specific service to the People application. At this time, the user can select the data they want to add. Other applications that you install also sync data with the People app, for example, by adding information to existing contacts. When you view a contact in the People app, you get information about your recent interactions with your contacts, such as emails and calendar events from apps that the People app uses to sync data from. From the People app, you can delete your account at any time.
	
Outlook mail/calendar app. The Mail and Calendar apps allow you to connect all your email, calendars, and files, including information from third-party email and file storage providers, in one place. The app provides location-based services, such as calendar weather information, but you can disable the app's use of your location. When you add an account to the Mail & Calendar app, the email, calendar items, files, contacts, and other settings in that account are automatically synced with your device and Microsoft servers. You can delete your account at any time, and you can change the data you sync with your account at any time. To configure your account, you need to enter your account credentials (such as username and password) in the app. The credentials entered are then sent over the internet to the third-party provider's servers. The app will first attempt to configure your account using a secure connection (SSL), but if your email provider doesn't support SSL, it will send this information unencrypted. If you're adding an account provided by an organization, such as a company or school, the owner of your organization's domain may implement certain policies and controls (for example, requiring multi-factor authentication or the ability to remotely wipe device data), which may affect how you use the app. This app uses device features like location, camera, and more. For more information, visit the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9wzdncrfhvqm).
	
Windows Operator Messages (formerly Microsoft Messaging) app. The Windows Operator Messages app receives and displays SMS texts from your carrier related to your account for your data plan on your PC or device, such as billing or data limits. These messages are stored locally on your device. From your device, you can also access, view, and delete these messages. This app uses device features such as contacts. For more information, visit the Microsoft Store on Windows.
	
The Clock app is a hub for time management and focuses on Windows. When users sign in with their Microsoft account, they can enable Microsoft To Do, a connected experience in the cloud. When a user turns on a focus session, the session data is stored locally and can be cleared by going to the watch's settings page. Additionally, focus sessions support connecting to Spotify accounts, allowing users to listen to ambient audio to help them focus. For more information, see the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9wzdncrfj3pr).
	
Microsoft Journal is a Windows application designed specifically for devices that can use touch and pen capabilities, such as tablets and 2-in-1 devices. Provide users with a free-form personal note-taking experience. The app leverages artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning to better recognize handwriting that processes data locally on the device. Once connected to Microsoft 365 (subscription required), users can seamlessly access their M365 calendar and contacts within the app. All user-created content is automatically saved to the default storage location in the document library for future reference. The journal gives you access to your photo library, your device's camera, and microphone, and you can add them to your book. Learn more about the Journal app here (https://support.microsoft.com/topic/microsoft-journal-help-and-learning-3605c04e-0fc6-40d5-b3fd-95a5cc365bc2) or visit the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9n318r854rhh).
	 
With the Cellular Plans app, you can easily access online from more locations on your Windows 10 PC and 11 LTE devices. When you sign up for a data plan on your device, you establish a connection with your carrier and you can complete your purchase on their online portal. To use this app, you need a supported SIM card. The Cellular Plans app uses IMEI, IMSI, EID, ICCID, and Country (the approximate location determined by your cellular ID or Wi-Fi reverse IP) to determine which carriers are available in your area. Your carrier may send notifications to you through your cellular plan app. This app uses the features of your device, such as camera and microphone. For more information, see the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9nblggh5pnb1).
	
Microsoft PC Manager is a desktop tool that is available in some regions and aims to improve PC performance. PC Manager will scan your device based on your request, allowing you to delete unnecessary and temporary documents, optimize cache, stop or recover unauthorized changes, and use other features such as health checks, one-click boosts, storage cleanup, file and pop-up management, and protection of default settings.
	
PC Manager blocks pop-ups based on ad-blocking rules and the pop-up windows selected by the user using custom blocking. If you agree to join the "Microsoft PC Manager Pop-up Plan" and block pop-up windows with custom blocks, you can take a screenshot of the pop-up and then send it to Microsoft to help optimize the pop-up management feature in Microsoft PC Manager. Microsoft doesn't collect any information other than screenshots, Windows titles, and Windows classes. Sent screenshots are only kept for a short time and are deleted periodically. You can manage your pop-up plan preferences at any time using the PC Manager settings. The PC Manager feedback feature may also process personal data if you include it in the feedback you provide to Microsoft. User feedback is periodically deleted after processing. For more information, see the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9pm860492szd).
	 
The Snipping Tool is a handy utility in Windows that uses your microphone and image library to capture and save screenshots and screen recordings. The Snipping Tool includes a text action feature that uses built-in optical character recognition (OCR) support. You can use OCR to select and copy text directly from an image. You can also use the text action feature to edit sensitive information from the captured text. When you use the clipboard to copy an integrated item from the Snipping Tool, it is also copied to the clipboard. By enabling clipboard history across devices, you can seamlessly use your copied content across different devices. Users can use Windows settings to manage clipboard and snipping preferences. For more information, see the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9mz95kl8mr0l).
	 
The Windows Sound Recorder app is a versatile tool designed to capture audio from the microphone in various scenarios. During the recording, you can mark important moments so that you can easily find important sections later. You can trim the volume levels, adjust them, apply other changes as needed, and even play back recordings. Recordings are auto-saved and saved in the Documents folder for easy access, allowing you to share your recorded audio with friends and family. For more information, see the Microsoft Store (https://apps.microsoft.com/detail/9wzdncrfhwkn).
	
Microsoft Clipchamp is a video editor designed to help you create video creations with ease. Users can combine videos, images, and audio files, add text and effects, and then save the finished video to their device, or use their Microsoft account to save the video to their personal OneDrive. Users can also add stock videos, stock music, sound effects, stickers, graphic elements, backgrounds, and more. Users can choose to allow Clipchamp to access their camera and microphone to record video directly from their device. To provide an even better experience, such as the language you want to display, Clipchamp collects inaccurate locations. Users can access Clipchamp using their personal or family Microsoft account from the Clipchamp app for Windows 10, or Windows 11, and from https://app.clipchamp.com (https://app.clipchamp.com/) in Edge or Chrome browsers.
	
Media Player is the default built-in player for multimedia (audio and video) files. When you choose to open a multimedia file, Media Player reads its contents. When you open Media Player, it reads the contents of your music and video library folders and creates your own music library and video library pages within Media Player to help you organize, view, and play multimedia content.
	
To enrich the experience when playing music, Media Player attempts to automatically display artist and album art for the content you play and for content in your Music Library. To provide this information, Media Player sends a request for information to Microsoft, including standard device data such as IP address, device software version, region and language settings, and content identifiers. If you want, you can disable this feature on the app's settings page.
	
Film and television. With Movies & TV from Microsoft, you can rent or buy movies and TV episodes and play them on your device.
	
To make it easier to find content that interests you, Movies & TV collects data about the movies and TV shows that users watch, such as watch time and ratings given by users.
	
Movies & TV also allows you to view and play local video files stored on your PC. To do this, you need to access the video library on your device.
	
Windows Media Player Classic. Windows Media Player legacy allows you to import media content, such as video, audio, and photo files, and you can play CDs and other digital content (such as video and audio files), rip CDs, and manage your media library. To provide users with a rich experience when playing content, Windows Media Player Legacy displays relevant media information, such as album titles, song titles, album art, artists, and composers. Windows Media Player Legacy sends a request to Microsoft that includes standard computer information, media content identifiers, and media information already stored in the Windows Media Player Legacy library, including information that you have entered or edited yourself, to expand the media information. This information allows Microsoft to recognize the track and return additional information that is available.
	
Windows Media Player Legacy also allows you to play content that has already been streamed over a network. In the previous version of Windows Media Player, you need to communicate with a streaming media server to provide this service. These servers are typically operated by content providers other than Microsoft. Windows Media Player Legacy sends logs to streaming media servers and other web servers when requested by the streaming media server while streaming media is playing. The logs include details such as connection time, IP address, operating system version, Windows Media Player legacy version, Player identification number (Player ID), date, and protocol. To protect user privacy, Windows Media Player legacy versions send a different Player ID for each session by default.

Windows Hello provides instant access to a user's device through biometric authentication. If you have Windows Hello enabled, Windows Hello uses your face, fingerprint, and iris to identify you based on your characteristics, which are extracted from images and stored as templates on your device. However, it does not store images of the user's actual face, fingerprints, or iris. The biometric data used to sign in remains on the device. Your biometric data remains on your device until you delete it. However, after Windows Hello has been inactive for a period of time, you'll be prompted to confirm that you want to continue saving your biometric data. Biometric data can be cleared in the settings. For more information, see Windows Hello (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=617027).

Windows Search allows you to search for items and websites that you own from a single location. When you search for "user-owned items" in Windows Search, your personal OneDrive, OneDrive for Business (if enabled), other cloud storage providers (to the extent supported by third-party providers), and your device are searched. When you use Windows Search to search for a website, or when you get search suggestions in Windows Search, the search results are provided by Bing. We use your search queries as described in the Bing section of this Statement. Learn more about the Windows search feature (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2106608).

Entertainment and related services provide users with a great experience so that they can avail of a variety of content, applications, and games.

Xbox
The Xbox Network is Microsoft's online gaming and entertainment service consisting of software that enables online experiences across various platforms. The service allows you to search and play games, view content, and connect with friends on Xbox and other games and social networks.
	
When you sign up for an Xbox profile, you assign a gamertag (public nickname) and a unique identifier to the user. When you sign in to an Xbox device, app, or service, the data collected about your usage is stored using these unique identifiers. Some jurisdictions may require you to verify your age or ID to access some Xbox services and features. If you are asked to verify your age or identity, please refer to the accompanying notice for more information about the data collected and how it is used, as well as information about third-party verification providers. The type of data collected depends on the location and verification method.
	
An Xbox console is a device that you can use to search for and play games, movies, music, and other digital entertainment. When you sign in to the Xbox experience with an app or console, your device is also assigned a unique identifier. For example, if your Xbox console is connected to the Internet and you sign in to your console, it identifies the console you're using and the version of your console's operating system.
	
The data we collect about your use of Xbox services, games, apps, and consoles includes:

When the user signs in and out of Xbox, what they purchased, and what they earned.

The games played by the user, the apps the user used, game progress, achievements, time played per game, and other statistics about playing.

Performance data about your Xbox console, Xbox Game Pass, and other Xbox apps, the Xbox network, connected devices, and your network connection, such as software and hardware errors.

Content that you add, upload, or share over the Xbox network, such as text, photos, and videos captured in games and apps.

Social activities such as chat data, interactions with other gamers, and connections on the Xbox network (friends you add or people you follow).

If you sign in to use Xbox on another device that has access to the Xbox network, and that device contains a storage device (hard drive or memory unit), your usage data will be stored on the storage device and sent to Microsoft the next time you sign in to Xbox. The same applies even if you are playing offline.

The data we collect allows us to provide services and curated experiences. This includes associating users with games, content, and services, as well as providing them with plans, discounts, and recommendations. To change the settings for these recommendations, see the Xbox Online Safety and Privacy Settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2170314) page.

Camera and microphone. While using Xbox, players can use the device's features, such as microphone, camera, and screen recording, to enhance their gaming experience. When you play Xbox games on Windows Game Bar, you can use your camera and microphone, including reading photos and videos, capturing and recording screenshots, and more.

Xbox diagnostic data. There are two categories of diagnostic data: mandatory and optional.

must. Xbox sends the required data to Microsoft. Collect the minimum data needed to keep your Xbox safe, secure, and up to date and working correctly.

Options. Optional data is additional data that you can share with Microsoft or choose to use. Optional data may include supplemental information about the operation, usage, and performance of Xbox products and services, as well as enhanced error reports.

For more information, see Manage optional data sharing settings (https://www.xbox.com/managedatacollection).

Game capture. Any player in a multiplayer gaming session can record video (game clips) and capture screenshots of the view of the gameplay. Game clips and screenshots of other players can capture in-game characters and gamertags during that session. When a player captures game clips and screenshots on their PC, the resulting game clips may also capture voice chat.

Subtitles. During real-time ("party") chat on Xbox, players can activate the voice-to-text feature that allows them to view the chat as text. If the player has enabled this feature, all audio communications at the party will be subtitled in the player. Microsoft uses the resulting text data for the purpose of providing chat captions to users who require them, as well as for other purposes described in this statement.

Xbox data that other users can view. Your gamertag, game and play statistics, achievements, presence (whether they're currently signed in to Xbox), content they're sharing, and other data about their activity on Xbox can also be viewed by the following users:

Other players who are signed in to Xbox.

A customer of a third-party service that linked your profile to, or

Customers of other services related to Xbox, including partner services.

For example, a user's gamertag or score that appears in the game leaderboard is considered public and cannot be hidden. For other types of data, you can adjust your privacy settings on your console or Xbox.com (https://www.xbox.com/) to limit or block what you share with the public or friends.

For more information, see Xbox online safety and privacy settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2170314).

Xbox data shared with third parties, such as game and app publishers. When you use an Xbox online game or networked app on your Xbox console, PC, or mobile device, the publisher of that game or app has access to usage data that helps the publisher provide, support, and improve the product. This data may include Xbox user identifiers, gamertags, and limited account information (such as country and age range), as well as data about in-game communications, Xbox running activity (such as in-game movements and the type of vehicle used in the game), presence on the Xbox network, time spent using the game or app, rankings, statistics, gamer profile, This includes your avatar or gamer icon, friends list, activity feed for your official club, club memberships, and content you create or submit in-game or in-app.

Third-party publishers and developers of games and apps have their own independent relationships with users, and the collection and use of personal data is subject to specific privacy policies. To see how your data is used, read the publisher's policies carefully. For example, publishers may disclose or display game data through their own services (e.g., in leaderboards). These policies may be linked from the game or app details page in the Microsoft Store.

For more information, see Data sharing with games and apps (https://www.xbox.com/Legal/ThirdPartyDataSharing).

To stop sharing your game or app data with publishers, remove it from all devices where you installed the game or app. Some publishers' access to data may be revoked at https://microsoft.com/consent.

AI-powered features. Xbox offers optional AI-enhanced features, such as Xbox's support virtual agent and Copilot, which can use text or voice to enter prompts. To provide responses, these AI-powered features use prompts, publicly available support articles, and other relevant data described in the "Personal Data We Collect (https://www.microsoft.com/privacy/privacystatement#mainpersonaldatawecollectmodule)" section or within the features. Other privacy settings are available in certain Xbox AI-enhanced features, including Copilot in Xbox. In the Microsoft privacy dashboard (https://account.microsoft.com/privacy), you can view, export, or delete chats with Copilot.

Children and families. If you have children who want to use the Xbox network, you can set up profiles for them and your child over 13 years old once you have a Microsoft account. Adult hosts of Microsoft family groups can change their consent choices and online safety settings for their children and those 13 and older in Xbox.com (https://www.xbox.com/).

For more information about Microsoft family groups, see Simplify your family's life (https://account.microsoft.com/family/about).

For more information about managing your Xbox profile, see Xbox online safety and privacy settings (https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2170314).

For more information about Microsoft's collection of children's data, including Xbox, see the Collection of data from your children section of this privacy statement.

Security. To make the Xbox network a safe gaming environment and to enforce Xbox's Community Standards, Microsoft may collect and review audio, text, images, video, and in-game content (game clips you upload, conversations, and content you post in clubs and games).

Anti-fraud and fraud prevention. Providing a fair gameplay environment is important to us. We prohibit cheating, hacking, account theft, and other cheating or fraudulent activities when using Xbox online games or network-connected apps on Xbox consoles, PCs, or mobile devices. We may use anti-cheat tools, anti-fraud tools, applications, and other technologies to detect and prevent cheating and cheating. These technologies may use certain information collected from your Xbox console, PC, or mobile device and how you use that device to create a digital signature (called a "hash"). This may include information about your browser, device, activity, game identifiers, and operating system.
	
Legacy.
Xbox 360。 This Xbox console collects limited mandatory diagnostic data to keep it behaving as expected on your console while using the Xbox network.
Kinect。 The Kinect sensor is a combination of camera, microphone, and infrared sensor that uses movement and voice to control gameplay. Here are some examples:

If selected, you can use your camera to automatically sign in to the Xbox network with facial recognition. This information is stored on the console and is not visible to anyone, and users can delete this data from the console at any time.

To play the game, Kinect maps the joints of the user's body to create a figure of the user in the form of a stickman so that they can enjoy playing.

Kinect's microphone allows players to voice chat with each other, even while playing. You can use voice commands with this microphone to control your console, enter games, apps, and search criteria.

The Kinect sensor can also be used for audio and video communication.

For more information about Kinect, see Xbox Kinect and privacy (https://aka.ms/kinectprivacy/).

	
Microsoft Store
The Microsoft Store is an online service that allows you to browse, download, buy, rate, and review applications and other digital content. You can access it on your PC, Xbox console, and the Xbox app. Offers from the Microsoft Store include:

Apps and content for Windows devices like phones, PCs, and tablets.

Games, subscriptions, and other apps for 

Xbox consoles and other devices.

Products and apps for Microsoft 365, SharePoint, Exchange, Access, and Project (2013 versions and later).

We collect data about your access to and usage of the Microsoft Store, the products you view, purchase, or install, the preferences you use to view apps in the Store, the ratings, reviews, and issues you submit. The user's Microsoft account is associated with ratings and reviews. When you complete a review, the user's Microsoft account name and image are published on the review. The Store uses the regions configured by your device to display relevant eligible content and merchandising plans. The Microsoft Store uses device identifiers to manage product rights associated with a specific device.

Microsoft Store app permissions. Many apps that you install from the Microsoft Store are designed to take advantage of the capabilities of specific hardware and software on your device. When an application uses certain hardware and software features, the application or related services may access your data. For example, a photo editing application accesses the user's device's camera. This allows users to take new photos or access photos and videos stored on their devices for editing. Restaurant Guide uses the user's location to recommend nearby restaurants. Information about the app's features can be found on the application's product description page in the Microsoft Store. Many features used in Microsoft Store apps can be toggled on or off in your device's privacy settings. Windows often allows you to choose which apps can use it for each specific feature. Start > Settings > Privacy or Privacy & Security , select a feature (such as Calendar), and then select the app permissions you want to turn on or off. The list of hardware and software features that apps can use in Windows privacy settings doesn't show "classic Windows" applications, but they aren't affected by this setting.

Application updates. Unless you have disabled automatic app updates in the relevant Microsoft Store settings, or if you get an app provided and updated by the app developer, the Microsoft Store automatically checks for app updates, downloads, installs, and ensures that the latest version is installed. Updated applications may use different Windows hardware and software than previous versions, which may allow these hardware and other devices to access different data on your device. When an updated application accesses certain features, such as location, the user is asked for consent. You can also view the Microsoft Store product description page to see the hardware and software features your app uses.

The use by each application of the data collected by these features is subject to the app developer's privacy policy. If an application that is available for purchase in the Microsoft Store collects and uses users' personal information, the application developer is required to publish a privacy policy. Links to these policies can be found on the App Product Description page in the Microsoft Store.
Sideload application and developer mode. Developer features, such as setting up "Developer Mode", are used for development purposes only. When developer features are enabled, the user's device becomes unstable or unusable, exposing the user to security risks. When you download or purchase an application from a source other than the Microsoft Store, known as "sideloading" an application, your device and personal information are affected by an attack or unintended use of the application. If you use a sideload app or have developer features enabled, Windows policies, notices, permissions, and other features designed to protect user privacy when accessing your app's user data may not work as described in this Statement.
	
Microsoft Start
Microsoft Start, formerly known as MSN or Microsoft News, is a content service that includes news, weather, sports, and finance. The Microsoft Start app is available on multiple platforms, including iOS and Android. The Microsoft Start service is also included in the Microsoft Edge browser and other Microsoft services.

When you install the Microsoft Start app, the MSN Weather app, or the Microsoft News app, we collect information about your device, such as whether the app was installed correctly, the date it was installed, the app version, and other operating systems and browsers. This information is collected periodically and used to identify performance issues related to the number of users of the application and different versions of the application and OS, as well as browsers. When you use the Weather App, Microsoft uses your location to provide you with relevant weather content.

Microsoft also collects data about how users interact with Microsoft Start content, such as how often they use it and what content they watch, in order to provide you with relevant content. Some parts of Microsoft Start offer an enhanced experience when a user signs in with a Microsoft account. For example, it allows users to customize their interests and favorites. We use your location to provide you with relevant content, such as local weather and news. Users can manage personalization features through Microsoft Start and Bing settings, as well as through settings for other Microsoft services, including Microsoft Start services. We also use the data we collect to provide you with ads that may be of interest to you. You can opt out of interest-based advertising through the advertising link within the Microsoft Start service, or by visiting Microsoft's opt-out page (http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=286759).

Previous versions of MSN Money allow users to access their personal financial information from third-party financial institutions. MSN Money only displays this information and does not store it on our servers. The login credentials used to access user financial information from third-party financial institutions are encrypted on the device and are not sent to Microsoft. These financial institutions and other third-party services that you access through MSN are subject to their own terms and privacy policies.
	
	
Silverlight
Microsoft Silverlight is software that helps users access and enjoy rich content on the web. Silverlight allows websites and services to store data on the user's device. Other Silverlight features include connecting to Microsoft for updates or to Microsoft or third-party servers for playback on protected digital content.

Silverlight configuration tools. The Silverlight Configuration Tool provides choices for these features. To access the Silverlight configuration tool, right-click on the content that Silverlight is currently displaying, and select Silverlight. You can also run the Silverlight configuration tool directly. For example, on Windows, you can search for "Microsoft Silverlight" to access the tool.

Silverlight application storage. Silverlight-based applications store data files locally on a user's computer for a variety of purposes. For example, saving customized settings, large files with graphical features (such as games, maps, images, etc.) and saving content created in specific applications. The Silverlight configuration tool allows you to disable or configure the storage of your application.

Updates for Silverlight. Silverlight regularly checks Microsoft's servers for updates and provides users with the latest features and improvements. A small file containing information about the latest Silverlight version is downloaded to the user's computer and compared to the current installed version. If a new version is available, it will be downloaded and installed on your computer. The Silverlight configuration tool allows you to disable or configure the storage of your application.

Digital rights management. Silverlight uses Microsoft Digital Rights Management (DRM) technology to protect the rights of content owners. When you access DRM-protected content (such as music or video) in Silverlight, the content requests media usage rights from an Internet rights server. To provide a seamless playback experience, there is no instruction to the user before Silverlight sends a request to the rights server. When requesting media usage rights, Silverlight provides the rights server with the ID of the DRM-protected content file and basic data about the device. This includes data about the DRM content on the device, such as device confirmation, security levels, and unique identifiers.

DRM updates. When accessing DRM-protected content, you may need to update the DRM components on your device or to Silverlight. If a user attempts to play DRM updated content, Silverlight sends a request for basic data about the device to Microsoft servers. This includes information about the DRM content on the device, such as device checks, security levels, and troubleshooting data and unique identifiers. Microsoft servers use this identifier to send an update for the device's unique DRM, and Silverlight installs this sent update. In the Playbacktab of the Silverlight configuration tool, you can disable or configure DRM component updates.
	
	
Windows Mixed Reality
Windows Mixed Reality allows for virtual reality experiences and allows you to dive into the world of apps and games. In Mixed Reality, you can use the camera, microphone, and infrared sensors on supported headsets to control gameplay with your movements and voice, as well as to interact with apps and games.
We collect diagnostic data and use it to troubleshoot issues and keep Mixed Reality running on Windows up to date, secure, and working properly. Diagnostic data also helps us improve Mixed Reality and related Microsoft products and services, depending on the diagnostic data settings you choose for your device. Learn more about Windows diagnostic data (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#maindiagnosticsmodule).
Mixed Reality also processes and collects data such as: These are especially relevant to the Mixed Reality experience.
Mixed Reality maps the distance between body joints and recreates them with stick figures. If you have an internet connection, collect these numbers to improve your user experience.
Mixed Reality detects specific hand movements to perform simple system interactions, such as menu movements, panning/zooming, and scrolling. This data is processed on your PC and not stored.
You can use voice commands on your headset's microphone to control games and apps, enter search terms, and more. Learn more about voice data collection (https://privacy.microsoft.com/privacystatement#mainspeechinkingtypingmodule).
Windows Mixed Reality can also be used for audio and video communication.

